Name: Centro Cristiano Manantial De Vida
Description: Centro Cristiano Manantial De Vida is a faith based organization that offers services to the community of Fontana, CA

Name: Kaleidoscope Youth Center
Description: Kaleidoscope Youth Center (KYC) seeks to serve and support LGBTQIA+ youth and young adults. They primarily function as a drop-in center for youth ages 12-20, and also do community outreach and trainings. Recently they have begun housing initiatives for homeless and housing insecure LGBTQIA+ youth

Name: 10000 degrees
Description: 10000 Degrees provides education and scholarship opportunities for students from all over Marin and Sonoma county.

Name: 100% College Prep Institute
Description: 100% College Prep Institute works with 8th to 12th graders. They offer 4 programs that help create college awareness, ready and eligible students.  Youth work 1:1 with academic coaches who help them plan their college-going journey by setting and achieving academic goals.  They also engage in group activities that support school success, academic proficiency, and college entrance.

Name: 1736 Family Crisis Center
Description: 1736 Family Crisis Center provides assistance for victims of domestic violence, homeless youth and families, runaways, at-risk veterans, and other community members in need.

Name: 18percent
Description: 18percent is a free and global online peer-to-peer support group centered around mental health. Communities are hosted on the app Slack (Slack is an internal chat service that offers “channels” for community members to hang out and spark conversation).

Name: 1951 Coffee Company
Description: 1951 Coffee is a non-profit company that provides a free, 2-week Barista Training Program for refugees and asylum-seekers in the San Francisco Bay Area. The program focuses on skills for the specialty coffee industry, American workplace culture, and customer service. After completing the course, graduates work with an employment specialist who connects them with job openings and helps with interview prep, mock interviews, and addresses any concerns or questions.

Name: 1k Project
Description: The 1k Project directly matches a family with a sponsor willing to donate money during the COVID-19 pandemic.

Name: 211 Alberta
Description: 211 is a free, confidential, multilingual, 24 hour information and referral system. 211 provides information on government and community based health and social services. 211 is available in certain regions across the province.

Name: 211 LA County
Description: 211 LA is the central source for providing information and referrals for all health and human services in LA County.

Name: 3 WINS Fitness
Description: 3 WINS Fitness is starting its newest campaign, AMPED (America Moves to Prevent/Evitar Diabetes), with the idea of creating L.A.'s Largest free Diabetes Prevention and Exercise Program. All fitness levels are welcome!

Name: 30th Street Senior Center
Description: Provides health and wellness programs, meals, and social services such as case management and an aging and disability resource center.

Name: 3rd Street Youth Center And Clinic
Description: The 3rd Street Youth Center and Clinic is a community based agency providing youth in Bayview Hunters Point with health services that encourage them to make decisions that support their health, safety, and development.

Name: 4-H
Description: 4-H helps youth acquire knowledge and develop life skills that enable them to find and focus their energy into their passions while also giving back to the community.

Name: 510 Families
Description: 510 Families provides information on family-friendly activities in the East Bay and beyond.

Name: 511 SF Bay
Description: 511 SF Bay provides a real-time overview of Bay Area traffic conditions, incidents, and driving times plus schedules, route, and fare information for public transportation.  It also offers instant carpool referrals, bicycling information, and more.

Name: 70Strong
Description: 70 Strong is a free referral service for people 60 years old and older to stay active and connected.  Older adults can talk with a social worker for support and navigation of resources.

Name: 826 Valencia
Description: 826 Valencia provides tools and resources to support students ages 6-18 in the San Francisco Bay area with their creative and expository writing skills.

Name: 826LA
Description: 826LA provides free programs for students ages 6–18, including tutoring, field trips, workshops and more.

Name: 9 Dots
Description: 9 Dots is a collaborative of engineers, educators and volunteers committed to introducing computer science and engineering to children. Students learn robotics, coding, photoshop and more. Students participate in fun team-building activities and community projects that can also help them to develop as leaders.

Name: A Better Living Permanent Housing and Supportive Services
Description: A Better Living provides individuals in need with the opportunity to obtain permanent housing, access supportive services, and educate themselves on useful life skills for day to day living.

Name: A Better Way Inc.
Description: A Better Way Inc. helps place children with adoptive or foster families in San Francisco and Alameda County. They also provide behavioral health services for children ages 0-5 years old.

Name: A Caring Mind Inc.
Description: A Caring Mind Inc. provides psychological services including EMDR, individual, family, couples, and crisis counseling. Other services such as pain management, worker's compensation, psychological assessment, and divorce mediation are offered.

Name: A Home Away From Homelessness
Description: A Home Away From Homelessness provides educational, social, and recreational opportunities for children of homeless and formerly homeless families. They offer small peer groups, meal preparation, guided trips, family style dinners, and outdoor activities.

Name: A Home Within
Description: A Home Within matches current and former foster kids with licensed volunteer therapists who provide weekly pro-bono therapy.

Name: A Light of Hope
Description: A Light of Hope provides support groups for parents, caregivers, young adults, children, and families.

Name: A New Way of Life Reentry Project
Description: A New Way of Life provides housing, case management, pro bono legal services and social support to formerly incarcerated women to help them successfully re-enter their communities and families.

Name: A Place-2-Live, Inc.
Description: A Place-2-Live provides residential placement services for individuals and families with financial challenges, such as fixed incomes, poor credit and evictions.

Name: A Safe Place
Description: A Safe Place helps individuals live a life of independence, self-efficiency, change, empowerment, and free of domestic violence. Its services include a 24-hour crisis hotline, emergency transportation, counseling, and re-entry services.

Name: A Second Wind Violence Prevention Project
Description: Offers anger management services, couples and individual counseling, domestic violence classes.

Name: A Step in the Right Direction
Description: A Step in the Right Direction provides  alcohol and drug detox.

Name: A to Z Royal Medical Supply
Description: Provides supplies such as hospital beds, manual wheelchairs, diabetic shoes and socks. The counties covered for these items through Medicare are Marin, Contra Costa, Alameda, San Mateo, and, San Francisco

Name: A Trabajar Center
Description: Provides free clothing to community members on Thursdays at noon. Five pieces of clothing per person and recommended to take their own bags.

Name: A Vision of Health
Description: A Vision of Health provides early detection and lifestyle interventions for diseases such as diabetes.

Name: A Woman's Place Community Awareness & Treatment Services Inc. (CATS)
Description: Community Awareness & Treatment Services Inc. (CATS) serves the chronically homeless population providing safe and accessible services. They have a network of seven programs that offer a continuum of care where staff give support, transportation, and housing.

Name: A-TEX Family Fun Center
Description: A-TEX sells Hot Tubs, Spas, Pools, Pool and Billiard Tables, Shuffleboard, Foosball, and Air Hockey to Austin Texas

Name: A. Philip Randolph Institute San Francisco (APRISF)
Description: The A. Philip Randolph Institute of San Francisco (APRISF) supports racial equality and economic justice in the Bayview-Hunters Point community through employment, advocacy and education.

Name: AA San Mateo County Intergroup of Alcoholics Anonymous (Al Anon)
Description: San Mateo County Intergroup of Alcoholics Anonymous (Al Anon) seeks to connect recovering alcoholics and those seeking help with addiction with a place to find peers and support in their times of need.

Name: AAIMM Doula Project
Description: The AAIMM Doula Project connects pregnant Black/African American women with birth doula services provided by Black doulas in order to reduce stress and medical interventions that put pregnant and birthing people at risk of poor outcomes.

Name: ABC Adult School - Cabrillo Lane Campus
Description: Adult schools provide education for the adult population to reach their educational goals such as obtaining a GED certificate, job training ESL, etc.

Name: ABC Adult School- Cuesta Campus
Description: Adult schools provide education for the adult population to reach their educational goals such as obtaining a GED certificate, job training ESL, etc.

Name: ABC Unified School District
Description: The AEBG block consortia seeks to expand and improve adult education to more members of the public.

Name: Abilities United
Description: Abilities United provides training and education programs for children and adults with disabilities, their families, and the community.    **Many of the services have been temporarily suspended due to the Covid-19 pandemic.

Name: Ability Now Bay Area
Description: Ability Now Bay Area is licensed by the State of California and has a contract with the Regional Center of the East Bay (RCEB) to provide services to persons with developmental disabilities.

Name: AbilityFirst
Description: AbilityFirst provides socialization and recreation activities for children and adults with mild-to-severe developmental disabilities.

Name: Able Works
Description: Able Works is an organization focused on giving people skills to empower them and help them get out of poverty, such as financial literacy and other life skills training.

Name: Abode Communities
Description: Abode Communities is a Los Angeles based nonprofit developer of affordable housing.

Name: Abode Services
Description: Abode Services provides shelter, housing, and supportive services to individuals and families.

Name: Abram Friedman Occupational Center
Description: Abram Friedman OC is committed to providing its diverse student population the academic, technical and life skills needed for personal growth and/or economic potential. Abram aims to provide and promote an exemplary career education, career development and workforce preparation and contributes to students' career success.

Name: AC Transit - Alameda-Contra Costa Transit District
Description: AC Transit is the public transit system of the East Bay and provides public transportation in Alameda and Contra Costa counties plus portions of San Francisco.

Name: Acacia Network
Description: Provide services for those who are homeless, struggling with substance use, and mental illness.

Name: Academy Prep Junior High Schol
Description: Academy Prep Junior High is a STEM (Science, Technology, Engineering and Math) based school within the Antelope Valley Union High School District for 7th and 8th graders.

Name: Acalanes Adult School
Description: Acalanes Adult School provides adult education including GED preparation and ESL classes.

Name: Acalanes Union High School District
Description: Acalanes Union High School District is a public high school district in Contra Costa County in California.

Name: Access
Description: Access is a paratransit service for functionally disabled individuals living in Los Angeles County that provides curb-to-curb ride service seven days a week.

Name: Access Adventure
Description: Access Adventure enriches the lives of people with disabilities and other underserved members of our community by providing outdoor recreation, open space access, education and therapy, through a working partnership with horses

Name: Access Alameda
Description: Access Alameda helps individuals identify and connect with the accessible transportation services available in Alameda County, including public transit.

Name: Access Alliance
Description: Access Alliance Multicultural Health and Community Services provides accessible, community-governed, inter-professional, primary health care services, including health promotion, illness prevention and treatment, chronic disease management, and individual and community capacity building. Their goal is for all people who face barriers to good health to have access to high quality primary health care within an integrated system of care.

Name: Access California Services
Description: Access California Services is a community-based organization with a focus on Arab-American and Muslim-American communities. Its services include refugee social services, healthcare, counseling and support, employment, tax preparation, financial assistance, immigration support, youth programs and more.

Name: Access Institute for Psychological Services
Description: Access Institute for Psychological Services offers low and no-fee psychological services to those who want and need psychological support, but aren’t able to access it for any number of reasons including income, cultural barriers, stigma around mental health and lack of mobility.

Name: Access Services
Description: Access Services offers paratransit as an alternative mode of flexible passenger transportation that does not follow fixed routes or schedules. Vans, minibuses, shared taxis, and jitneys are used as forms of transportation.

Name: AccessMatters
Description: AccessMatters (formerly Family Planning Council) innovates, empowers, and works to equalize access to sexual and reproductive health care for teens and adults in need. AccessMatters develops, implements, and evaluates innovative programs that make a sustained community impact, including: family planning, HIV and STD prevention and testing, breast and cervical cancer screening and prevention, teen pregnancy prevention, and condom distribution.

Name: Accounting Career Awareness Program
Description: ACAP is an organization that promotes accounting as a career, particularly for underrepresented ethnic minorities, by offering scholarships and summer programs for youth interested in accounting.

Name: AchieveKids
Description: AchieveKids schools in San Jose and Palo Alto provide individualized and multi-disciplinary programs that deliver special education, mental health and family support services for students ages 5 to 22 who have complex and often severe developmental, emotional and behavioral challenges.

Name: ACLU SoCal
Description: The ACLU SoCal works to eradicate discrimination based on sexual orientation, gender identity and gender expression. The ACLU SoCal is creating a state where LGBTQ people can live openly and with dignity, where their identities, relationships and families are respected, and where there is fair treatment on the job, in schools, in housing, in public places and in government programs.

Name: Acorn Computer Learning Center
Description: The Acorn Computer Learning Center offers free computer classes, help with resumes and other programs.

Name: ACORN Medical Clinic
Description: The Alachua County Organization for Rural Needs (ACORN) Inc. Medical Clinic provides low-cost medical, dental and social services care to residents of North Central Florida.

Name: AcroSports
Description: AcroSports is a Bay Area non-profit offering classes in gymnastics, circus and urban arts for children, teens and adults.

Name: ACT for Mental Health
Description: ACT for Mental Health provides affordable mental health services including counseling, therapy, classes and support groups offered by its staff of licensed psychologist, therapists, counselors and interns.

Name: Acta Non Verba: Youth Urban Farm Project (ANV)
Description: Acta Non Verba creates a safe and creative outdoor space for children and youth. Activities include gardening, camping, and field trips.

Name: ACTCM Community Clinics
Description: The American College of Traditional Chinese Medicine (ACTCM) Community Clinics operates a Community Clinic of Traditional Chinese Medicine (e.g. Acupuncture, herbal therapy, nutritional counseling, Tui Na (Chinese medical massage), Qigong, cupping, moxibustion, electro-stimulation; services may also be accessed through Castro Mission Health Center, Maxine Hall Health Center, Mission Neighborhood Health Center and Haight Ashbury Free Medical Clinic.

Name: Action Family Counseling (AFC)
Description: Action Family Counseling (AFC) is a drug and alcohol rehabilitation program that provides services to individuals, teens, and adults.

Name: Action Wellness
Description: Action Wellness is a nonprofit organization serving individuals with chronic disease in the Greater Philadelphia area.

Name: Action with Immigrants and Refugees Montreal (AGIR)
Description: AGIR's mission is to develop and offer services, information, programs and resources, in addition to protecting and defending the legal, social and economic rights of migrants (asylum seekers, refugees, immigrants, and those with undetermined status) from lesbian, gay, bisexual , trans and queer (LGBTQ) communities, all in a spirit of solidarity.

Name: Active Adults
Description: Active Adults is a program funded by Santa Rosa Recreation and Parks. It has two community centers that provide daily activities, monthly social events, legal services and dance programs for the 50 and older community.

Name: Actors Fund of America
Description: The Actors Fund is an organization that helps all professionals in the performing arts and entertainment who are in need, crisis or transition due to unpredictable employment.  Services include emergency financial assistance, affordable housing, health care and insurance counseling, senior care, secondary career development and more.

Name: Acts Full Gospel Church
Description: Acts Full Gospel Church provides community activities and services for the needy.

Name: ADA
Description: ADA (Beyond the rainbow) is a not-for-profit community organisation based in Montreal founded by members of the Spanish-speaking group. ADA offers meeting and conversation for men gays. ADA’s goal is to help newcomers who have had difficulty in their country of origin due to sexual orientation.  ADA offers an atmosphere of acceptance, encouragement, support and inspiration.

Name: Adaptive Learning Center
Description: Adaptive Learning Center provides customized living skills training, vocational guidance, health and fitness instruction, and recreational activities for adults with autism or developmental disabilities.

Name: Administration for Children and Families
Description: The Administration for Children and Families (ACF) is a division of the Department of Health & Human Services. We promote the economic and social well-being of children, families, individuals and communities with leadership and resources for compassionate, effective delivery of human services.

Name: Adolescent Counseling Services
Description: Adolescent Counseling Services offers affordable, comprehensive counseling services and substance use treatment for youth and their families in Santa Clara and San Mateo Counties.

Name: Adolph and Esther Gottlieb Foundation
Description: The Adolph and Esther Gottlieb Foundation has been giving grants to painters, sculptors and printmakers who have been creating mature art for at least 20 years and who are in current financial need.

Name: Adopt a Family of Marin
Description: Adopt a Family of Marin provides subsidies for rental assistance, security deposits, utility payments, food vouchers, and auto repair for families.

Name: Adopt International
Description: Adopt International helps pregnant mothers through every step of adoption and offers adoption services for those looking to adopt.

Name: Adoption Connection
Description: Adoption Connection provides support and resources to adoptive parents as they grow their families.  As well as to birth mothers as they gain stability during and after their pregnancies.

Name: Adoption Horizons
Description: Adoption Horizons provides adoption services.

Name: AdoptUSKids
Description: AdoptUSKids is a project of the US Children’s Bureau that provides tools and technical assistance to help child welfare systems connect children in foster care with families

Name: Adult Day Services Network of Contra Costa
Description: Adult Day Services Network of Contra Costa provides seniors, people with disabilities, their families, and the community with opportunities to socialize, exercise, receive therapy services, and care.

Name: Adult Education Center Pomona Unified School District
Description: Adult and career education services and opportunities.

Name: Adult Survivors of Child Abuse (ASCA)
Description: Adult Survivors of Child Abuse (ASCA) provides self-help and support to adult survivors of childhood sexual, physical and emotional abuse. All resources are available free of charge.

Name: Advancing Justice-LA
Description: Advancing Justice-LA (formerly Asian Pacific American Legal Center of Southern California, Inc.) provides legal information, counseling and representation to individuals especially those who speak little or no English.

Name: Advent Group Ministries
Description: Advent Group Ministries provides counseling and addiction recovery services to people of all ages and income levels.

Name: Adventist Health - St. Helena Hospital
Description: Adventist Health - St. Helena Hospital is a faith-based organization that provides health care services.

Name: Adventist Health White Memorial
Description: Adventist Health White Memorial is a full-service, 353-bed, teaching hospital in Los Angeles, California

Name: Adventist Health, Glendale
Description: Adventist Health is a faith-based, nonprofit comprehensive health delivery system that provides affordable community care throughout California.

Name: Affecting Change Inc - Project Blueprint Job Transition Program
Description: Affecting Change Inc provides charitable services to low income members of the community. Project Blueprint is a six-week, pre-employment program, designed to help individuals with life and occupational skills training, transition from welfare/public assistance to work. The six-week program includes 60 hours of classroom training and 120 hours of occupational (job) skills training. During the training program, participants learn the importance of job acquisition skills, safety training, communication, personal life skills and job retention. Participants who successfully complete the program will be placed in various companies.

Name: Affinity Community Services
Description: Affinity Community Services is a social justice organization serving the needs of the Black LGBTQ community of Chicago with a particular focus on Black women.

Name: Affirmed Housing
Description: Affirmed Housing Group offers affordable housing throughout California.

Name: Affordable Care Physical Therapy
Description: Affordable Care Physical Therapy offers physical therapy services.

Name: Affordable Living for the Aging
Description: Affordable Living for the Aging provides affordable housing, supportive services, and alternative housing options for low-income and formerly homeless seniors.

Name: Afghan Coalition
Description: The Afghan Coalition is an organization that works to strengthen refugee families locally and in Afghanistan to build bridges between the United States and Afghanistan. This is accomplished through public services, community-based programs and reconciliation between the people of Afghanistan and the United States.

Name: African Advocacy Network (AAN)
Description: African Advocacy Network (AAN) provides social and immigration legal services for African and Afro-Caribbean immigrants through the delivery of quality services by Department of Justice (DOJ) Accredited staff in a culturally and linguistically- supportive environment.

Name: African American Community Service Agency
Description: The African American Community Service Agency (AACSA) provides quality educational, cultural, social and recreational programs plus services and activities in order to perpetuate and strengthen African American identity, culture, values, traditions and knowledge.

Name: African American Cultural Center
Description: The African American Cultural Center helps to recover, research, collect, preserve, interpret, teach, and promote knowledge and appreciation of the culture of African people with emphasis on African Americans. Services include educational programs, communal and public dialog, collections, exhibitions, and other initiatives.

Name: African Cultural Alliance of North America, Inc.
Description: The African Cultural Alliance of North America Inc. (ACANA) is a non-profit agency providing culturally sensitive social services, arts and cultural programs, legal services, community engagement and development programs and other services to African and Caribbean immigrants in the United States.

Name: African Hope Committee
Description: The African Hope Committee offers a variety of services to African and immigrant communities living in New York City. All activities are planned with the purpose of relieving the poor, distressed and underprivileged migrant populations and minority groups.

Name: AFS Intercultural Programs San Francisco Bay Area
Description: AFS is non-profit organization that provides young people with opportunities to live and study abroad.

Name: After Class Enrichment (ACE)
Description: After Class Enrichment (ACE) provides youth in Napa Valley with free after school programs and athletic teams to foster learning and social support outside of classroom hours.

Name: After-School All-Star
Description: After-School All-Stars is a national non-profit organization that partners with schools across the United States to expand learning for children.

Name: Agape International Ministry
Description: Agape International Ministry provides religious and community services.

Name: Age Well Senior Services
Description: Age Well Senior Services provides services that are specially designed to help enable seniors to stay in their own homes and maintain quality of life.

Name: Agency for Persons with Disabilities
Description: APD works in partnership with local communities and private providers to assist people with developmental disabilities and their families that support them.

Name: Aguilas
Description: Aguilas is a organization that aims to promote the health, well-being, and strength of the bisexual and gay Latino community. Services include HIV testing, support groups, counseling, asylum assistance, and social events.

Name: AHF Healthcare Center
Description: The agency provides HIV/AIDS services and thrift shops for people who have AIDS or HIV-related illness in Los Angeles County.

Name: AHRC New York City
Description: AHRC New York City is an organization serving people with intellectual and developmental disabilities in New York City.  Services include health, education and employment.

Name: AIDS Activities Coordinating Office
Description: The City of Philadelphia's AIDS Activities Coordinating Office (AACO) provides services to prevent and treat HIV.

Name: AIDS Coalition of Nova Scotia
Description: AIDS Coalition of Nova Scotia (ACNS) provides HIV/AIDS support, education and prevention programs across Nova Scotia.

Name: AIDS Committee of Newfoundland and Labrador (ACNL)
Description: ACNL is a provincial organization committed to preventing the spread of HIV and Hepatitis C and supporting people living with and/or affected by HIV/AIDS or Hepatitis C.

Name: AIDS Community Research Consortium (ACRC)
Description: AIDS Community Research Consortium (ACRC) connects people living with or at risk to contracting AIDS with needed resources, programs and means of empowerment.

Name: AIDS Healthcare Foundation (AHF)
Description: AIDS Healthcare Foundation (AHF) provides cutting-edge medicine and advocacy for people living with HIV/AIDS, including support groups for the transcommunity, through a network of healthcare centers. AHF provides services regardless of ability to pay.

Name: AIDS Law Project of Pennsylvania
Description: The AIDS Law Project of Pennsylvania is a nonprofit public-interest law firm providing free legal assistance to people living with HIV and AIDS and those affected by the epidemic.

Name: AIDS Legal Referral Panel
Description: The AIDS Legal Referral Panel provides low-cost legal and advocacy services to people living with HIV/AIDS. They offer services in almost every area of civil law, including housing, employment, and immigration.

Name: AIDS New Brunswick
Description: AIDS New Brunswick Inc. is a provincial organization that aims to promote and support the health and well-being of people living with and affected by HIV/AIDS while helping to reduce the spread of HIV, Hepatitis C and other sexually transmitted and blood borne infections in New Brunswick through the provision of prevention, education, and support initiatives.

Name: Aim High
Description: Aim High is a free summer learning and enrichment program that prepares youth in middle school for the transition to high school and beyond.

Name: Aimee's Babies Word Gap App
Description: The Word Gap App from Aimee's Babies provides valuable resources to help parents find ways to interact with their babies.

Name: Al Otro Lado
Description: Al Otro Lado is a bi-national organization that serves deportees, migrants, and refugees in Tijuana, Mexico with free immigration assistance . The company is composed of professionals that specialize in family, labor, employment and criminal law.

Name: Al Wooten Jr. Youth Center
Description: The Al Wooten Jr. Youth Center provides free after school and low-cost summer programs for boys and girls in grades 3-12.

Name: Al-Anon Family Groups (AFG) and Alateen of Northern California
Description: The Al-Anon Family Groups helps families of alcoholics. They do this by practicing the "Twelve Steps", by welcoming and giving comfort to families of alcoholics, and by giving understanding and encouragement to the alcoholic.

Name: Al-Anon Family Groups of Greater Los Angeles
Description: Al-Anon Family Group is an organization that helps friends and families of alcoholics.

Name: Al-Anon San Francisco
Description: Al-Anon San Francisco is a fellowship of relatives and friends of alcoholics who share their experiences, strength, and hope in order to solve their common problems.

Name: Al-Anon Santa Clara Valley
Description: Al-Anon Santa Clara Valley offers support services to individuals experiencing problems with the drinking of a friend, family member or loved one.

Name: Ala Costa Center
Description: Ala Costa Centers serves individuals with developmental disabilities such as autism, Down syndrome, cerebral palsy, fetal alcohol syndrome, intellectual disabilities, and developmental delay. Ala Costa employees are trained on a continuous basis to work with this wide spectrum of disabilities.

Name: Alachua County Crisis Center
Description: The Alachua County Crisis Center offers 24 hr/day phone crisis and suicide intervention counseling to all residents of Alachua County.

Name: Alachua County Department of Social Services
Description: Alachua County Department of Social Services offers a range of services to its residents.

Name: Alachua County Housing Authority
Description: The Alachua County Housing Authority provides rental subsidies and manages affordable Public Housing units for low income families, seniors, and persons with disabilities throughout Alachua County, Florida.

Name: Alachua County Humane Society
Description: Alachua County Humane Society is a non-profit 501(c)(3) organization dedicated to helping pets in Alachua County for more than 40 years.

Name: Alachua County Humane Society Thrift Store
Description: Low cost clothing, pet supplies, furniture and household items.

Name: Alachua County Office of Emergency Management - Response and Recovery Unit
Description: Provides large-scale disaster preparedness for hurricanes and other natural disasters, disasters caused by humans, and technological hazards. They also offer public education about how to prepare for a disaster as well as its aftermath.

Name: Alachua County Public School Adult Education
Description: The Alachua County Adult Education Program provides GED classes and tests, adult high school, adult basic education, and literacy training.

Name: Alachua County Supervisor of Elections
Description: Assistance with voter registration.

Name: Alachua County Veteran Services Office (VSO)
Description: Alachua County Veteran Services Office (VSO) helps Veterans apply for Veterans' benefits.

Name: Alachua County Victim Services and Rape Crisis Center
Description: The Alachua County Victim Services & Rape Crisis Center provides services to survivors of interpersonal violence, sexual violence and personal injury crimes.

Name: Alachua Habitat for Humanity
Description: Alachua Habitat for Humanity’s Critical Home Repair program addresses unsafe, severely inadequate living conditions and enables families to stay in their homes.

Name: Alameda Adult School
Description: Alameda Adult School provides education courses for adults including English as a Second Language, HS Diploma & GED/HiSET Test Prep and Family Literacy classes.

Name: Alameda Alliance for Health
Description: Alameda Alliance for Health is a public, not-for-profit managed health care plan that is affordable for residents of Alameda County.

Name: Alameda and Berkeley One Stop Career Centers
Description: The Alameda and Berkeley One-Stop Career Center provides free employment services to job seekers and employers for the local and surrounding areas.

Name: Alameda County Auditor-Controller Agency
Description: The Alameda County Auditor-Controller Agency collects court-related fines and restitutions, Social Service Agency overpayments and other receivables mandated by laws and regulations.

Name: Alameda County Behavioral Health Care Services (ACBHCS)
Description: Alameda County Behavioral Health Care Services (ACBHCS) provides mental health and substance abuse services for Alameda County residents.

Name: Alameda County CASA
Description: Alameda County Court Appointed Special Advocates (CASA) trains and supports community volunteers who advocate for youth in the child dependency system. Volunteers participate in a 30-hour training, are sworn in by the court, and matched with a child in the foster care system. The role of a CASA Volunteer is to investigate what is going on with the youth, advocate and speak up for their best interests, coordinate with child's team (foster parents, social worker, teachers, etc.) in order to facilitate resources and services, and monitor the case to make sure the youth's needs are met. CASA asks for a year commitment and estimates that this role takes 10-15 hours a month. This includes advocating for your youth in court twice a year, checking in with your Case Supervisor who is there to support you, and being a positive role model with your youth. Participate in an info session and learn more about how you can help raise the voice of a child in foster care.

Name: Alameda County Children of Incarcerated Parents Partnership (ACCIPP)
Description: The Alameda County Children of Incarcerated Parents Partnership (ACCIPP) is a regional coalition focused on those who work with or are concerned about children of incarcerated parents. The goal is to improve the lives of children with an incarcerated parent through increased awareness, improved programs, and policy reforms.

Name: Alameda County Community Food Bank
Description: The Alameda County Community Food Bank distributes food through a network of 240 member agencies - food pantries, soup kitchens, child-care centers, senior centers, after-school programs, and other community organizations - as well as its own direct programs.

Name: Alameda County Court Self-Help Center
Description: The Alameda County Court's Self-Help Center provides individuals with workshops, information, and assistance on legal matters including family law, name changes, child support, restraining orders, small claims, and custody/guardianship.

Name: Alameda County Deputy Sheriffs’ Activities League (DSAL)
Description: The Alameda County Deputy Sheriffs’ Activities League (DSAL) offers recreational and educational opportunities for children in Alameda county.

Name: Alameda County District Attorney's Office
Description: Alameda County District Attorney's Office's mission is to review and prosecute criminal violations of the law, protect consumers and the environment, and support and protect victims of crime within Alameda County on behalf of the people of the State of California.

Name: Alameda County Family Justice Center
Description: Alameda County Family Justice Center provides crisis intervention, shelter, case management, and more for individuals and families experiencing domestic violence, stalking, sexual assault and exploitation, child abuse, child abduction, elder and dependent adult abuse, or human trafficking.

Name: Alameda County Health Care for the Homeless
Description: Alameda County Health Care for the Homeless provides many types of care to homeless people in Alameda County through a network of community health clinics, mental health, specialty care, dental, optometry and homeless services organizations.

Name: Alameda County Health Care Services Agency
Description: Alameda County Health Care Services Agency provides information about free and low-cost health care services for Alameda County residents.

Name: Alameda County Healthy Homes Department
Description: Alameda County Healthy Homes Department provides minor home repairs, lead hazard repair grants, and blood lead testing for children.

Name: Alameda County Healthy Homes Department (ACHHD)
Description: The Alameda County Healthy Homes Department offers free services to prevent lead poisoning and to promote health and safety in the home.

Name: Alameda County Housing & Community Development Department
Description: The Alameda County Housing and Community Development Department (HCD) provides programs for households, homeless, and disabled individuals. Services include rehabilitation and repair assistance programs for homes, expanding affordable housing, public accessibility improvements, and shelter and housing for the homeless.

Name: Alameda County Independent Living Skills Program (ILSP)

Description: Arab Resource and Organizing Center provides direct legal services to Arab and Muslim immigrants regarding family reunification, deportation defense, asylum and other matters.

Name: Arab-American Family Support Center (AAFSC)
Description: Arab-American Family Support Center (AAFSC) is a non-profit, non-sectarian organization established to provide culturally and linguistically competent, trauma-informed, multigenerational social services to immigrants and refugees. While they support anyone who walks through their doors, over nearly 25 years of experience, they have developed expertise in serving the Arab, Middle Eastern, Muslim, and South Asian (AMEMSA) immigrant and refugee communities. Note: All of AAFSC's Priority Areas are linked. Program participants are exposed to a range of initiatives every time they enter the Center and staff across the agency are equipped to work with clients across priority areas.

Name: Arbor Free Clinic
Description: The Arbor Free Clinic is a Stanford University student-run free clinic offering medical services to adults regardless of immigration status.

Name: Arbor House
Description: Arbor House provides affordable transitional housing in a communal setting to working mothers with children.

Name: Arcadia Adult Education
Description: Adult schools provide education for the adult population to reach their educational goals such as obtaining a GED certificate, job training ESL, etc.

Name: Arcadia Transit
Description: Arcadia Transit offers shared dial-a-ride service for senior residents and people with disabilities.

Name: Archdiocesan Youth Employment Services (AYE)
Description: Archdiocesan Youth Employment Services (AYE) provides career services, work experience, and resources to help youth and adults.

Name: Archdiocese of Los Angeles
Description: The Archdiocese of Los Angeles is a faith-based organization that provides religious and community services in Los Angeles, Ventura, and Santa Barbara counties.

Name: Archdiocese of San Francisco
Description: Archdiocese of San Francisco has several ministries including a school.  They also have different departments that work with the community specifically on social justice issues as well.

Name: Archive408
Description: This is a mutual aid project that allows individuals to give and request financial assistance in a transparent and public forum.

Name: Ariel Outreach Mission
Description: Ariel Outreach Mission provides emergency shelter, transitional housing, assistance with employment, skills training, and medical care for women with or without children.

Name: Arise and Shine Transitional Living
Description: Arise and Shine Transitional Living helps women who have successfully graduated a drug/alcohol or anger management program obtain housing, support services, and life skills.

Name: Ark of Refuge
Description: The mission of the Ark of Refuge is to challenge and overcome the individual and institutional barriers that discourage or prevent underserved populations from accessing vital services.

Name: Arkansas Justice Collective
Description: The Arkansas Justice Collective is a nonprofit law firm serving immigrants and refugees through the practice of immigration law. It also provides published reports on situations that hurt LGBTQIA+ people, black and brown people, poor people of all colors, and other vulnerable populations.

Name: Arkansas United
Description: Arkansas United provides legal services and adult English classes throughout Arkansas.

Name: Arlington Food Assistance Center
Description: Since 1988, the Arlington Food Assistance Center remains dedicated to its simple but critical mission of obtaining and distributing groceries, directly and free of charge, to people living in Arlington, VA, who cannot afford to purchase enough food to meet their basic needs.

Name: Armenian Relief Society of Western U.S.A
Description: Armenian Relief Society of Western U.S.A. serves the needs of its community members including new immigrants, refugees and the elderly who have difficulties accessing services due to language barriers and other hardships.

Name: Armory Center for the Arts
Description: Armory Center for the Arts is an education center that offers art classes to the community and provides spaces for exhibitions and galleries.

Name: Arriba Juntos

Name: Arroyo Vista Family Health Center
Description: Arroyo Vista Family Health Center provides comprehensive and affordable health care services to families.

Name: Arthritis Foundation
Description: The Arthritis Foundation offers information and resources to individuals with arthritis.

Name: Artist Relief
Description: Artist Relief is an organization created during COVID-19 to support artists financially.

Name: Artistic Noise
Description: Artistic Noise offers art training to young people who are incarcerated, on probation or otherwise involved in the justice system. It offers studio art workshops on Rikers Island and at its studio in Harlem.

Name: Arts Administrators of Color Network
Description: The Arts Administrators of Color Network (AAC) is an arts service network that supports artists of color and focuses on networking and community building through the arts.

Name: ArtSeed
Description: ArtSeed is an arts education program for children. They offer fine arts classes, workshops, and apprenticeships at their office, along with a rotating gallery. They also lead field trips and work with schools in the Bay Area.

Name: ArtSpace
Description: Artspace runs programs that aim to provide artists with space for their work and living, and their work focuses on Property Development, Asset Management, and Consulting Services.

Name: artworxLA
Description: ArtworxLA provides art programs that link alternative high school students with professional artists, cultural institutions and communities to produce their own work.

Name: Ascencia
Description: Ascencia provides services to individuals and families who are homeless.

Name: Ascentria Care Alliance (ACA)’s Immigration Legal Assistance division, LGBT Human Rights Protection Project
Description: The Ascentria Immigration Legal Assistance Program provides free and low-cost legal services to immigrants in Massachusetts.

Name: Ashland Churches Community Emergency Shelter Services
Description: Provides emergency shelter services for women and families.

Name: Ashland Free Medical Clinic
Description: The Ashland Free Medical Clinic provides free medical care to adults who do not have health insurance. They provide non-emergency care for both acute and chronic conditions and the clinic is staffed by volunteer physicians, nurse practitioners and other support staff.

Name: Asian American Center of Frederick
Description: The Asian American Center of Frederick offers services to low-income, minority, and immigrant groups including insurance enrollment, interpretation/translation, ESL/Citizenship classes, and housing, education, job, and business development assistance.

Name: Asian American Drug Abuse Program (AADAP)
Description: Asian American Drug Abuse Program (AADAP) provides treatment for Asian and Pacific Islanders with drug abuse issues.

Name: Asian Americans Advancing Justice - Asian Law Caucus
Description: Asian Americans Advancing Justice - Asian Law Caucus provides low-cost legal assistance for housing, employment, immigration and other legal issues for low-income Asian Pacific American communities.

Name: Asian Americans for Community Involvement
Description: Asian Americans for Community Involvement (AACI) offer services to the community including healthcare, addiction recovery, emergency shelter, senior care and more.

Name: Asian Art Studio
Description: Asian Art Studio teaches children language skills in Mandarin while deepening knowledge of Chinese culture and art through age-appropriate play-based classes and activities. AAS has programs during the school year and over the summer.

Name: Asian Community AIDS Services (ACAS)
Description: Asian Community AIDS Services (ACAS) is a charitable, non-profit, community-based organization located in Toronto, Canada. They provide safer sex education and services to the East and Southeast Asian communities and support services to persons living with HIV/AIDS and members of the LGBTQ communities. *Note: You must be physically in Toronto to be eligible for ACAS' services.

Name: Asian Counseling and Referral Service (ACRS)
Description: Asian Counseling and Referral Service (ACRS) is a nonprofit organization working for social justice and offering a broad array of behavioral health programs, human services and civic engagement activities for Asian Americans, Pacific Islanders and other underserved communities.

Name: Asian Health Services
Description: Asian Health Services (AHS) offers medical, dental, and mental health services for all ages. They provide services in English and more than fourteen Asian languages.

Name: Asian Immigrant Women Advocates (AIWA)
Description: Asian Immigrant Women Advocates (AIWA) seeks to empower women and youth in the workforce through education, leadership development and collective action.

Name: Asian Law Alliance
Description: Asian Law Alliance provides legal services to Asian Pacific Islanders and other community members.

Name: Asian Liver Center
Description: The Asian Liver Center at Stanford University is a non-profit organization that addresses the disproportionately high rates of chronic hepatitis B infection and liver cancer in Asians and Asian Americans through collaboration, advocacy, research, and education and outreach.

Name: Asian Neighborhood Design
Description: Asian Neighborhood Design offers training programs for jobs in construction.

Name: Asian Network Pacific Home Care and Hospice
Description: Asian Network Pacific Home Care and Hospice provides culturally sensitive home health services in Alameda, San Francisco, Santa Clara and Contra Costa counties.

Name: Asian Pacific American Community Center
Description: Asian Pacific American Community Center helps Asian Pacific American families living in Visitation Valley by providing linguistically and culturally appropriate education, resources, and referrals needed to adapt and become self-sufficient.

Name: Asian Pacific American Dispute Resolution Center (APADRC)
Description: The Asian Pacific American Dispute Resolution Center (APADRC) provides mediation and conflict resolution services to communities in the Los Angeles area, with a focus on the Asian Pacific Islander Population.

Name: Asian Pacific Counseling & Treatment Centers (APCTC)
Description: The Asian Pacific Counseling & Treatment Centers (APCTC) offers outpatient mental health services for children, adolescents, and adults, plus employment services.

Name: Asian Pacific Environmental Network
Description: Asian Pacific Environmental Network (APEN) is an environmental justice organization with deep roots in California’s Asian immigrant and refugee communities.

Name: Asian Pacific Fund
Description: Asian Pacific Fund supports Asian and Pacific Islander organizations in the Bay Area. It also funds college scholarships.

Name: Asian Pacific Health Care Venture, Inc.
Description: Asian Pacific Health Care Venture provides health care services for adults and children.

Name: Asian Pacific Islander (API) Mental Health Alliance
Description: API Mental Health Alliance provides comprehensive, community-based, culturally and linguistically appropriate therapeutic services to Asian and Pacific Islander adults with severe and persistent mental illness.

Name: Asian Pacific Islander Legal Outreach
Description: Asian Pacific Islander Legal Outreach provides multilingual, culturally competent legal representation, social services and advocacy for women, seniors, recent immigrants, and youth.

Name: Asian Pacific Policy and Planning Council
Description: The Asian Pacific Policy and Planning Council (A3PCON) is a coalition of community-based organizations that advocates for the rights and needs of the Asian and Pacific Islander American (APIA) Community in the greater Los Angeles area, with a particular focus on low income, immigrant, refugee and other disadvantaged sectors of the population.  To accomplish this mission, A3PCON strives to: Serve as a vehicle for promoting the needs, interests and concerns of the APIA Community to policy makers and the general public. Promote collaboration, planning and collective action amongst its members to support common advocacy/policy, organizational development and capacity-building goals. Activate the APIA electorate and promote public accountability to the APIA Community through non-partisan political and electoral participation.

Name: Asian Perinatal Advocates
Description: Asian Perinatal Advocates provides support services to families in San Francisco, California.

Name: Asian Prisoner Support Committee (APSC)
Description: Asian Prisoner Support Committee (APSC) provides support, re-entry community, and job services to Asian & Pacific Islander prisoners being imprisoned, detained, and deported.

Name: Asian Professional Exchange (APEX)
Description: APEX works to help support the Asian Community in greater Los Angeles by creating a professional network with volunteering, professional development workshops and networking mixers.

Name: Asian Women's Home
Description: Asian Women's Home is a program offered by the Asian Americans for Community Involvement (AACI).  It serves survivors of domestic violence and human trafficking with case management, emergency food, clothing, shelter and peer counseling.

Name: Asian Women's Shelter
Description: Asian Women's Shelter (AWS) provides comprehensive services to domestic violence and human trafficking survivors and their children. They provide shelter, case management, access to health and legal services with a 24-hour crisis line.

Name: Asian Youth Center
Description: Educational Enrichment Services, Youth & Family Services, and Employment Services

Name: Asian-American Recovery Services (AARS)
Description: Asian-American Recovery Services (AARS) is a community-based organization providing substance abuse and HIV prevention outreach services to the Asian and Pacific Islander communities throughout San Francisco.

Name: ASIAN, Inc.
Description: ASIAN, Inc. empowers Asian Americans and other minorities by increasing their access to opportunities in business development, housing, and financial education.

Name: ASOSAL
Description: ASOSAL is a non-profit that educates and gives legal advice to the immigrant community in Los Angeles. They can assist with petitions for alien relatives, status adjustments, consular processing, applications for travel documents, DACA renewal, green card renewal and more.

Name: Asotin County Health District
Description: Asotin County Health District helps the community prevent disease, disability, and premature death.

Name: Aspiration Diploma Plus High School
Description: Aspirations Diploma Plus High School, in association with the Child Center of NY and the Sports and Arts in School Foundation, offer small class sizes and learning environment to develop a close relationship with all students in and out of the classroom. The school provides comprehensive programs to support students' personal growth as they transition into young adulthood, earn a high school diploma, and acquire the skills and experiences to succeed in college or a career path. Graduation rate is at 50%.

Name: Aspire Education Project
Description: Aspire Education Project works with K-12 students to improve academic performance, increase standardized test scores, and encourage life-long learning.

Name: Assistance League
Description: Assistance League Los Angeles provides services and resources for newborns and foster children and their families, including preschool, school clothes, and supplies

Name: Assistance League of Covina Valley
Description: Assistance League of Covina Valley supports Azusa, Covina, Glendora, and West Covina community members through outreach, education, and youth programs.

Name: Assistance League of Long Beach
Description: Assistance League of Long Beach provides dental health and new school uniforms for economically disadvantaged children. As well as, scholarships for deserving California State University, Long Beach, and Long Beach City College students.

Name: Assistance League of Los Altos
Description: Assistance League of Los Altos is a chapter of the National Assistance League and provides support services for children, seniors and those with medical emergencies for over 50 years.

Name: Assistance League of Pomona Valley
Description: Assistance League of Pomona Valley offers services to the community including dental treatment, clothing, assistance to survivors of violence and more.

Name: Assistance League of San Mateo County
Description: Assistance League of San Mateo County provides supplies for families, mothers and other community members in need.

Name: Assistance League of San Pedro-South Bay
Description: Assistance League of San Pedro-South Bay provides community aid, scholarships, and dental health to those in the surrounding area.

Name: Assistance League of Southern California - Foster Children's Resource Center
Description: Assistance League of Los Angeles is a nonprofit dedicated to improving the lives of children in the Los Angeles area.

Name: Assistance League Santa Clarita
Description: Get clothing, education and emotional support for families, the elderly and the disabled. Assistance League Santa Clarita helps children succeed in school by providing new school clothes, shoes, eye exam and eyeglasses to help them focus on learning.

Name: Assisted Christian Therapy
Description: Do you need support and help to remove barriers and work through obstacles? Do you want to accomplish goals and live in your purpose? Everyday, in every way we have the ability to get better and better, and I would be honored to support you in your journey t. I have a passion and purpose to be of meaningful service to others. I combine my education, professional and real world experience to provide gentle, honest and insightful care within a compassionate, client centered, spiritual approach. I have worked in the clinical fields of behavioral therapy, parenting, eating disorders, domestic violence, clinical research, and vocational counseling. My specialties include the treatment of trauma, depression, anxiety, interpersonal/relationship issues and psychotic disorders.

Name: Associated Students Child Development Center, San Jose State University
Description: The Associated Students Child Development Center at San Jose State University offers child care services by trained specialists. Services are offered primarily to students and staff of the University

Name: Assurance Wireless
Description: Assurance Wireless is a federal Lifeline Assistance program sponsored by Virgin Mobile. The program provides free cell phones and discounted monthly plans for participants.

Name: ASUC Renters’ Legal Assistance (RLA)
Description: ASUC Renters’ Legal Assistance (RLA) is an undergraduate student organization at UC Berkeley that provides information to the community regarding rental issues.

Name: Asylee Women's Enterprise (AWE)
Description: Asylee Women Enterprise (AWE) helps asylum seekers navigate the immigration legal process, begin to heal from past trauma, and rebuild their lives. They offer comprehensive services from housing to english classes to mental health services.

Name: Asylum Seeker Advocacy Project
Description: The Urban Justice Center's Asylum Seeker Advocacy Project (ASAP) prevents wrongful deportations by connecting refugee families to community support and emergency legal aid. They provide rapid representation at a distance, reaching families who could not otherwise access legal services in the United States. ASAP's focus is on formerly detained asylum-seeking families. Currently, ASAP's online community is only for Spanish-speaking mothers who are seeking asylum.

Name: Asylum Seeker Assistance Project (ASAP)
Description: The Asylum Seeker Assistance Project (ASAP) is the first and only nonprofit exclusively dedicated to serving the estimated 50,000 asylum seekers living in the D.C. Metro region. Through direct services, education, and community support, ASAP empowers asylum seekers to rebuild their lives with dignity and purpose. Fill out the online form on their website to see if they are able to assist you.

Name: Asylum-Seekers Sponsorship Project
Description: The Asylum-Seekers Sponsorship Project is an entirely volunteer-run effort to connect asylum-seekers with qualified sponsors in order to be released from detention and increase the chances of winning their asylum claim.

Name: At The Crossroads
Description: At The Crossroads reaches out to homeless youth and young adults to help them build healthy and fulfilling lives. They focus on young people who do not access traditional services and are disconnected from any type of consistent support. They work with young people who others have given up on, who would not get help without them. They remove common barriers to service by bringing counselors onto the streets and shaping their support services around the needs of each individual client. Their goal is to help clients build outstanding lives, not just the lives of subsistence.    Have nighttime outreach, one-on-one counseling services, and collaboration with other organizations.

Name: AUDIENT
Description: AUDIENT is a nationwide program that helps those in need obtain hearing aids at a reduced cost.

Name: Authors League Fund
Description: The Authors League Fund supports professional authors, journalists, poets, and dramatists who find themselves in financial need because of medical or health-related problems, temporary loss of income, or other misfortune.

Name: AV Saving Grace
Description: AV Saving Grace is a community, faith-based organization serving women and children who are at risk, and seeking safety from domestic violence and/or homelessness.

Name: Avalon Carver Community Center
Description: Avalon Carver Community Center provides support and services for families who are affected by substance abuse.

Name: Avenidas

Name: Aviva Family and Children's Services

Description: Axis Mundi Center for Mental Health offers mental health services for individuals, groups, couples and Families. It has offices in Oakland, Napa and Alameda and offers multi-culturally competent clinicians.

Name: Ayuda
Description: Ayuda advocates for and defends the legal and human rights of low-income foreign-born people living in the Washington, DC, metropolitan area. Ayuda serves immigrants who come from many parts of the world and speak many different languages. Ayuda provides legal services focusing on immigration and domestic violence/family law issues, social services to immigrant victims and survivors of domestic violence, and  access to language interpretation.

Name: Aza Health
Description: Aza Health offers medical, dental, and mental health services in Alachua County.

Name: Aztlan Family Clinic
Description: Aztlan Family Clinic offers individual and group medical and mental health counseling.

Description: Baby First Solano provides free and low-cost prenatal care to pregnant women. Additional services include childbirth & parenting classes, substance abuse help, case management support throughout pregnancy, and mental health services.

Name: Baby Safe LA
Description: Baby Safe LA provides a listing of locations to safely surrender a baby as well as helpful information on Los Angeles County's baby surrender program.

Name: Baby2Baby
Description: Baby2Baby provides eligible children, ages 0-12 years, with diapers, clothing and all the basic necessities that every child deserves. Basic essentials are distributed through a network of other non-profits and social services agencies.

Name: Bal Jagat - Children's World Inc.
Description: Bal Jagat - Children's World Inc. is a fully Hague Accredited international adoption agency that provides international adoption services and home study, post-placement, and post-adoption services in counties throughout Southern California.

Name: BALANCE (formerly Consumer Credit Counseling Service of San Francisco CCCS)
Description: BALANCE is a non-profit service that helps individuals and families with debt management, financial counseling, student loan repayment, bankruptcy and more.

Name: Balboa High School
Description: Balboa High School offers college preparation workshops and presentations, after school classes, tutoring, and JROTC programs for its students.

Name: Banning Adult Learning Center
Description: Adult schools provide education for the adult population to reach their educational goals such as obtaining a GED certificate, job training ESL, etc.

Name: Banteay Srei
Description: Banteay Srei is an Oakland organization that provides education, community, and leadership development for young Southeast Asian women who are at risk of or engaged in, sexual exploitation.

Name: Bar Association of San Francisco
Description: The Bar Association of San Francisco provides legal services to disadvantaged and underserved individuals in San Francisco.

Name: Barbara J. Riley Senior and Community Center
Description: Provides a variety of recreational and social activities mainly to seniors who are aged fifty and older, but activities are also available to people of all ages.

Description: Barrio Action Youth & Family Center operates the FamilySource center focused on helping youth and their families in the Lincoln Heights/El Sereno area of Los Angeles.

Name: Barry J Nidorf: Juvenile Hall Mental Health Unit
Description: Barry J. Nidorf Juvenile Hall in Sylmar provides mental health support to the youth in its halls and camps.

Name: Bartz-Altadonna Community Health Center
Description: Bartz-Altadonna Community Health Center is the Antelope Valleys first Federally Qualified Health Center A 501 (c ) non-profit organization, committed to provide patient centered, trauma informed primary care services to all its patients.  No one will be denied access to services due to inability to pay we offer a discounted sliding fee schedule, and accept all types of health plans. A place of excellence for medical care

Name: Bassett Unified School District
Description: The AEBG block consortia seeks to expand and improve adult education to more members of the public.

Name: BASTA
Description: BASTA provides affordable legal counseling and representation for issues including evictions, immigration and more. BASTA wants to help everyone regardless of economic limitations, immigration status, race, religion or any other factor.

Name: Battered Women's Justice Project (BWJP)
Description: Battered Women's Justice Project (BWJP) provides training and assistance to criminal and civil justice practitioners, the general public, and victims of domestic violence.

Name: Bay Area Addiction Research and Treatment Center (BAART)
Description: Bay Area Addiction Research and Treatment Center (BAART) provides drug treatment and rehabilitation for addiction to prescription medications such as oxycontin and hydrocodone, as well as other opioids.

Name: Bay Area Air Quality Management District
Description: BAAQMD strives to reduce air pollution through legal means as well as educational events. In addition to reducing air pollution they work on related issues, such as public health and climate change.

Name: Bay Area Cancer Connections
Description: Bay Area Cancer Connections supports people affected by breast or ovarian cancer by providing supportive services.

Name: Bay Area Community Health Advisory Committee (BACHAC)
Description: The Bay Area Community Health Advisory Committee (BACHAC), in partnership with Mills-Peninsula Health Services, is dedicated to eliminating health disparities across generations and diverse communities through education and services. BACHAC also works to increase awareness and reduce the debilitating effects of health concerns that disproportionately affect communities of color.

Name: Bay Area Community Resources (BACR)
Description: Bay Area Community Resources (BACR) provides a range of services for individuals and families in six counties around the San Francisco Bay Area. BACR offers after school programs, community service, youth leadership programs, health centers, alcohol and drug treatment, tobacco education, and counseling.

Name: Bay Area Community Services (BACS)
Description: Bay Area Community Services (BACS) offers resources for behavioral health, housing, and aging with independence for teens, adults, seniors, and their communities.

Name: bay area cooperative association
Description: housing, cohousing, community living
Region: San Francisco Bay Area, CA, USA

Name: Bay Area Crisis Nursery
Description: The Bay Area Crisis Nursery provides 24-hour care to children from birth to through age 11 while their parents are experiencing a crisis.

Name: Bay Area Furniture Bank
Description: Bay Area Furniture bank help individuals transitioning out of homelessness or displacement, and others who are overcoming difficult circumstances in life with free furniture.

Name: Bay Area Housing Corporation
Description: Bay Area Housing Corporation offers housing for people with intellectual and developmental disabilities.

Name: Bay Area Legal Aid
Description: Bay Area Legal Aid provides free civil legal advice and counsel to anyone, regardless of their location, through their toll-free number. If court representation is necessary, you must live near a county administrative office.
Region: San Francisco Bay Area, CA, USA

Name: Bay Area Outreach and Recreation Program - BORP
Description: Bay Area Outreach and Recreation Program (BORP) provides people with physical disabilities the ability to participate in sports, fitness, and recreation programs. BORP is headquartered in Berkeley and supports accessible sports and recreation opportunities for children and adults with physical disabilities in the greater San Francisco Bay Area.

Name: Bay Area Rapid Transit (BART)
Description: Bay Area Rapid Transit (BART) provides public transportation throughout the Bay Area.

Name: Bay Area Rescue Mission
Description: Bay Area Rescue Mission provides an emergency shelter, job training, and a food pantry to individuals and families in need.

Name: Bay Area Safety Net
Description: The Bay Area Safety Net is a non-profit dedicated to supporting artists in the Bay Area during the COVID-19 Crisis.

Name: Bay Area Sex Worker Advocacy Network (BAYSWAN)
Description: BAYSWAN provides referrals and support for sex workers and survivors of human trafficking.

Name: Bay Area Video Coalition (BAVC)
Description: Bay Area Video Coalition (BAVC) provides classes and workshops on media arts, technology, and storytelling. In addition, BAVC also provides Artist Development residencies and fellowships.

Name: Bay Area Women Against Rape
Description: Bay Area Women Against Rape provides Alameda County residents a place where rape and incest survivors can receive the quality counseling and advocacy they need and provides community education regarding sexual assault issues.

Name: Bay Area Women’s and Children’s Center (BAWCC)
Description: Bay Area Women’s and Children’s Center (BAWCC) offers food, clothing, education opportunities, youth sports programs and more to families, children and women in the San Francisco Tenderloin neighborhood.

Name: Bay Area Workers Support (BAWS)
Description: Bay Area Workers Support is a peer-led organization providing material resources, information, advocacy, and support for people in the sex trade.

Name: Bay Area Youth EMT (BAY EMT)
Description: Bay Area Youth EMT (BAY EMT) provides free EMT and fire curriculum for inner-city youth to learn about the first responder profession. Youth apply their newly learned skills to community based programs as well as in local EMS and fire agencies. Transitional age youth are encouraged to join, however, students outside this range are also accepted.

Name: Bay Leaf Kitchen
Description: Bay Leaf Kitchen teaches children and families how to create, cook and share sustainable, healthy food.

Name: Bay Positives
Description: The mission of Bay Area Young Positives (BAY Positives) is to help young people (26 and under) with HIV/AIDS to live longer, happier, healthier, more productive, and quality-filled lives.

Name: Bayanihan Community Center
Description: BCC offers a variety of services for the Filipino-American community. This includes a twice a month clinic for basic health, behavioral, and dental. As well as cultural events, rooms for rent for family gatherings, and finding after school programs.

Name: Bayanihan Equity Center
Description: The Bayanihan Equity Center provides services to address the needs and advance the rights of low-income seniors, immigrants, LGBTQ, people with disabilities, homeless and formerly incarcerated people living in the San Francisco area.

Name: Bayshore Christian Ministries
Description: Bayshore Christian Ministries provides after school and summer programs for youth in East Palo Alto and Belle Haven. They provide ways for youth to gain both spiritual as well as life skills.

Name: Bayshore Elementary School District
Description: Free English classes for parents

Name: Bayview Child Health Center
Description: Bayview Child Health Center offers medical services, mental health services, dental services, nutritional assistance, referrals to specialists as needed, and academic collaboration with schools for individuals ages 0-18.

Name: Bayview Footprints Network of Community Building Groups
Description: Bayview Footprints was formed in 2007 by a network of community-building groups – many of them informal – committed to working together to make the Bayview stronger though positive strategies like creating community-defined art, helping our youth achieve health and success, preserving our history, growing community gardens, and telling a balanced story about a maligned neighborhood. Today, Bayview Footprints is primarily a community communications network facilitated by Quesada Gardens Initiative. A free bi-weekly e-newsletter (Bayview Footprints Local News) reaches several thousand subscribers, and the neighborhood’s longest-running blog, It’s What Community Looks Like, serves nearly 600 posts about a great neighborhood and its people. The group also hosts special issue Footprints Forums.

Name: Bayview Hunters Point Center for Arts & Technology (BAYCAT)
Description: Bayview-Hunters Point Center for Arts and Technology (BAYCAT) educates and employs young people from underserved communities in the Bay Area in digital media arts. Areas of study include video production, music production, animation, graphic, and web design.

Name: Bayview Hunters Point Clinic
Description: Bayview Hunters Point Clinic provides medical, dental, behavioral health, and recovery services to everyone living in the neighborhood.

Name: Bayview Hunters Point Foundation for Community Improvement
Description: Bayview Hunters Point Foundation for Community Improvement provides substance abuse treatment, group and individual counseling, and residential housing and homeless services for the people living in the Bayview Hunters Point neighborhood.

Name: Bayview Hunters Point Radio Network
Description: The Bayview Hunters Point Radio Network is our community's conversation with each other. The BVHP Radio Network is a network of tiny radio studios in community centers, senior centers, youth centers, low-income housing developments, churches, counseling centers, case-management organizations, schools, cafes, private homes and street-corners throughout the 94124 zip code.

Name: Bayview Hunters Point YMCA
Description: The Bayview Hunters Point YMCA offers recreational programs and social services for local residents, including the TLC Family Resource Center and a family support program that connects families with a network of local and citywide resources.

Name: Bayview Opera House Ruth Williams Memorial Theatre
Description: Bayview Opera House Ruth Williams Memorial Theatre offers free and low-cost community arts events and arts education for youth.

Name: Bayview Senior Services
Description: Bayview Senior Services offers a range of local resources to support the seniors in the San Francisco Area. Amenities include a nutrition program, a senior connection hub for referrals and financial assistance and three senior centers for recreation.

Name: Bayview/Linda Brooks Burton Branch, San Francisco Public Library
Description: The Bayview Linda Brooks-Burton Library was renamed on March 28, 2015.  There is a collection of high interest materials for adults, teens, and children. There is a special collection of books and materials by and about African Americans.  There is a medium sized Chinese Language and Spanish Language collection.  California residents with a valid identification can receive a free SFPL library card to borrow books, DVDs,music, audiobooks, magazines, and e-books from any public library in San Francisco.  You are also able to access the internet for 2 hours per day on the public computers.  All San Francisco public libraries offer free wireless internet access.  There are weekly and monthly events for all ages such as movies, basic computer classes, science and art workshops, author readings, SAT classes, in addition there is also preschool and toddler story time, with a special attention to diverse programming.  A program room is available for community use by reservation on the SFPL website under "Services."

Name: Bikers Against Child Abuse
Description: Bikers Against Child Abuse, Inc. (B.A.C.A.) exists with the intent to create a safer environment for abused children. We exist as a body of Bikers to empower children to not feel afraid of the world in which they live. We stand ready to lend support to our wounded friends by involving them with an established, united organization. We work in conjunction with local and state officials who are already in place to protect children. We desire to send a clear message to all involved with the abused child that this child is part of our organization, and that we are prepared to lend our physical and emotional support to them by affiliation, and our physical presence. We stand at the ready to shield these children from further abuse. We do not condone the use of violence or physical force in any manner, however, if circumstances arise such that we are the only obstacle preventing a child from further abuse, we stand ready to be that obstacle.

Name: Bridge HIV
Description: We can envision the end of HIV. Can you?     Check out www.bridgehiv.org to learn how you can make a difference as an HIV prevention study volunteer.    Bridge HIV works with local and international communities to discover effective HIV prevention strategies through research, community partnerships, and educational initiatives. We operate as a 100% grant-funded, clinical trial unit within the San Francisco Department of Public Health and are affiliated with the University of California, San Francisco (UCSF).    Bridge HIV's early research, which dates back to the beginning of the AIDS epidemic, played an important role in the identification of the HIV virus and the risk of transmission.

BCHS has an accelerated credit program so students will have the opportunity to earn additional credits. Graduation rate is at 54%.

Name: BronxWorks

Graduation rate is at 57%, students aged 16-21 years old can apply, along with a requirement of a minimum of 10 credits and have passed at least 1 Regent Exam.

Name: Brooklyn Botanic Garden

The school provides support and counseling for students to make informed choices about their learning and post-secondary life, through counseling, access to healthcare, and employment support. Graduation rate is at 60%, and students who are looking to enroll should typically be 1-2 years behind academically, experienced significant attendance problems in a previous high school, and have been enrolled in another high school for at least one year.

Name: Brooklyn Community Pride Center
