The Law Center assists asylum seekers, victims of crime, victims of domestic violence, children, and provides other forms of relief, including DACA.

Name: Casa de Clara San Jose Catholic Worker
Description: Casa de Clara San Jose Catholic Worker provides food, donated supplies, showers and hygiene supplies to individuals and families who are homeless.

Name: Casa de los Angelitos
Description: Casa de los Angelitos is a safe and secure maternity home that helps pregnant women, and women and their infants through life skills and parenting programs.

Name: Casa de Vida
Description: Casa de Vida helps individuals who are homeless or dependent on drugs or alcohol.

Name: Casa Nova
Description: Casa Nova is an affordable public housing complex, units owned by Marin Housing Authority for seniors.

Name: CASA of Los Angeles
Description: CASA of Los Angeles advocates for children who have experienced abuse and neglect. Their services include providing support at court hearings, early childhood training, health and mental health advocacy, and more.

Name: Casa Ruby
Description: Casa Ruby's Drop Inn-Community Center is the only bilingual multicultural LGBT safe space in Washington, D.C. open 5 days a week. Staff and volunteers work together to provide basic human services which include: hot meals, a clothing exchange, Cyber Center, support groups, case management, emergency housing referrals, and legal services counseling (criminal/immigration). Casa Ruby mainly serves the Latino LGBT community.

Name: Casa Segura Drop-In Center
Description: Casa Segura is part of the HIV education and prevention project of Alameda County.  It offers a place to get off the street, clean up, eat, and rest. During drop-in hours, clients can do laundry, shower, get free STD testing, and more.

Name: Casa Treatment Center
Description: Casa Treatment Center provides adult women with a safe environment in which to overcome substance abuse and related disorders. The treatment center offers both residential and outpatient services, and all are based on non-medical therapies.

Name: Cascades High School
Description: Cascades High School, in association with CAMBA, is an alternative school that offers small class sizes, and more attention for older students who have struggled in other schools. Students' academic success is supported by a comprehensive pupil personnel services team, consisting of a guidance counselor, college advisor and parent coordinator. Participation in the arts and technology programs are strongly encouraged. Graduation rate is at 67%, and enrollment is open to students aged 16-21 with a minimum of 10 credits.

Name: Casey Family Programs
Description: Casey Family Programs works directly with children and families to find solutions to safely reduce the need for foster care, improve well-being, and secure safe and lifelong families for children in foster care.

Name: Castro Valley Adult & Career Education
Description: Castro Valley Adult & Career Education offers affordable classes for adults including ESL, parenting, job skills, exercise and more.

Name: Castro-Mission Health Center
Description: Castro-Mission Health Center provides comprehensive outpatient AIDS treatment services including comprehensive primary and preventive health care services, a dedicated children’s clinic, a teen clinic, and a family planning clinic; immunizations and U shots; screenings for colorectal cancer, hepatitis, tuberculosis, and hypertension; Public Health nurses for home visits and health education;  Dimensions Program for lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender and questioning individuals 12 to 25 years of age, primary health care, individual counseling, case management and health education; HIV Anonymous Testing.

Name: Cathedral Basilica of St. Joseph
Description: Cathedral Basilica of St. Joseph provides religious and community services to the vulnerable and homeless populations in San Jose.

Name: Cathedral Center of St. Paul
Description: Cathedral Center of St. Paul is a faith based organization located in Echo Park, Los Angeles.

Name: Cathedral of Our Lady of the Angels
Description: Cathedral of Our Lady of the Angels is a faith based organization that offers services to the Los Angeles community.

Name: Catherine White Holman Wellness Centre
Description: At the Catherine White Holman Wellness Centre, they aim to provide low-barrier wellness services to transgender and gender non-conforming people in a way that is respectful and celebratory of clients’ identity and self-expression. Their centre is volunteer run, and all of their practitioners are volunteering their time, so that the Centre can offer free services to people who need them, regardless of factors like citizenship, health insurance, or residential address.

Name: Catholic Charities Maine - Refugee and Immigration Services (CCMRIS)

Name: Catholic Charities of Gainesville
Description: Fully licensed adoption agency offering home studies, post-placement reports, and adoption counseling. Counseling and support for teens and women facing unplanned pregnancies. Food Pantry, rent/financial assistance.

Name: Catholic Charities of Los Angeles, Inc.
Description: Catholic Charities offers services to the community including food pantries, youth employment services, counseling, immigration assistance, pre-school, and more.

Name: Catholic Charities of San Francisco, Marin, and San Mateo Counties
Description: Catholic Charities provides housing services, children and youth programs, refugee and immigrant services, and aging support services serving the homeless, children and youth, low-income families, seniors, HIV/AIDS patients, immigrants, and adults with disabilities throughout San Francisco, Marin, and San Mateo Counties.

Name: Catholic Charities of Santa Clara County

Name: Catholic Charities of Solano

Name: Catholic Charities of the Diocese of Santa Rosa

Name: Catholic Charities of the East Bay
Description: Catholic Charities of the East Bay is a faith-based service organization that provides emergency assistance with shelter, food, clothing, medical services, and more to those in need.

Name: Catholic Charities of Washington, D.C.
Description: Catholic Charities of Washington, D.C. operates 58 programs in 36 locations all in Washington, DC and the surrounding five Maryland counties. These services include legal services, emergency shelter, health services, food programs, and employment programs. Specific programs vary between locations. Their doors are open to everyone regardless of race, religion, orientation, or status.

Name: Catholic Charities West Virginia - Migration & Refugee Services
Description: Catholic Charities of West Virginia offers a wide range of programs and services for immigrants in West Virginia. In addition, they handle humanitarian relief in cases involving refugee and asylee benefits and offer services for victims of domestic violence, certain other crimes, and human trafficking.

Name: Catholic Funeral and Cemetery Services (CFCS)
Description: Catholic Funeral and Cemetery Services (CFCS) provides funeral and cemetery services.  As a charity CDCS offers innovative programs that provide financial assistance plus free options and programs to meet the needs of the community.

Name: Catholic Legal immigration Network, Inc.
Description: Embracing the Gospel value of welcoming the stranger, CLINIC promotes the dignity and protects the rights of immigrants in partnership with a dedicated network of Catholic and community legal immigration programs.

Name: Catholic Outreach in Action

Name: Catholic Social Service of Solano County
Description: Catholic Social Service of Solano County offers family assistance, counseling, anger management group therapy, and immigration services to Vallejo residents. Catholic Social Services serves senior citizens, the homeless, families facing hardship, the disabled and parents of children aged 18 or younger.

Name: Catholic Social Services of Philadelphia - Immigration Legal Services
Description: Catholic Social Services of Philadelphia's mission is to provide comprehensive, high quality, low-cost Immigration Legal Services. They serve families and individuals in the Archdiocese of Philadelphia and within the jurisdiction of the USCIS Philadelphia District Office and the Philadelphia Immigration Court.

Name: Catholic Worker Hospitality House San Bruno

Name: Center for Early Intervention on Deafness (CEID)

Name: Center for Elders' Independence (CEI)
Description: CEI is a Program of All-inclusive Care for the Elderly (PACE), a long-term comprehensive health care program that enables older adults to live at home in their communities for as long as medically and socially possible. CEI also has a health plan which provides all medical care (24-hours-a-day), a PACE Day Center, home care services and transportation.

Name: Center for Employment Training

Name: Center for Empowering Refugees and Immigrants
Description: CERI is a grassroots, non-profit organization founded in 2005 by a small group of bilingual/bicultural mental health professionals. It is dedicated to providing culturally competent mental health and social service resources to refugee and immigrant families with complex needs. The agency’s focus is on healing through community-led program activities. We serve refugees and immigrants from Afghanistan, Bosnia, Cambodia, and Iran. The majority of our 200 clients are Cambodian refugees living in Oakland, California.  We offer weekly support groups for women, men, young women, and young men. The adult programs maintain a community garden near Laney College, provide ESL classes, mental health services, group therapy, dance classes, and a yearly retreat. Youth groups engage through weekly peer support groups, community outings, mental health referrals when needed,  academic support, career opportunities, a yearly retreat, and one to one mentoring.

Name: Center for Family Health & Education
Description: Center for Family Health & Education provides primary care to adults and children, dental & orthodontic services, and mental health care.
Region: Panorama City, Los Angeles, CA, USA

Name: Center for Health Care Rights
Description: The Center for Health Care Rights (CHCR) is a non-profit organization that provides services to Los Angeles residents. Services include providing access to quality health care through information, counseling, education, advocacy, and research programs such as Medicare advocacy services, including education counseling and legal assistance.

Name: Center for Health Justice
Description: Reentry Service Center providing Health Education, Substance Abuse, Mental Health, Sexual & Gender Diversity Training.   The Stan Price Reentry Service Center also provides:  DMV CA ID Vouchers Clothing Vouchers  Reentry Hygiene Kits Small meals  Support Groups for people who've experienced incarceration.

Name: Center for the Vulnerable Child (Children’s Hospital of Oakland)

Their mission is to protect and defend Central and South American asylum-seekers and to expand the civil rights of all immigrants. CALA has had an open door to newly-arrived immigrants since 1985. CALA’s staff are all bi-lingual. Based in a Brooklyn church, CALA offers immigrants a home base for advice or counseling as well as legal representation. They have put thousands of Latino immigrants on the road to citizenship.

Description: CRECE is a grassroots organization, whose mission is to organize and educate the Latino immigrant community to improve its social, economic and cultural conditions.  CRECE was created in 1990 to help Central Americans in the Bay Area and abroad. Our goal in El Salvador is to help rural communities with donations and access to resources.

They help tenants understand their rights and provide a safe space for SRO tenants to share their experiences and access city and state-building and health code laws.

Name: Dream Scholarship Fund
Description: Many of the people who entered the United States to work as immigrants during the economic boom years of the last few decades brought their minor children with them. The parents of these children were encouraged to come to the United States and work here by employers seeking to fill low paying job openings.  For the great majority of these children, English is their primary language and they have not been to the country of their parents’ birth since early childhood. Many are honor students.  The Dream Scholarship Fund helps these children reach their potential of becoming highly successful, productive, tax paying citizens who will contribute to renewing our economy. Name: El/La Para TransLatinas
Description: El/La Para TransLatinas  is a safe space and holistic support organization for transgender women of Latin American descent (translatinas). We are the only organization in the Bay Area (and in California) solely providing direct services to translatinas. We are dedicated to seeing them thrive, be who they want to be and live a dignified, healthy life, free of violence and HIV.   Majority of our participants are monolingual immigrants of low-income status. In the safe space that El/La creates, they come together to eat, celebrate, express themselves, play, practice their spirituality, learn, access resources, collaborate with other organizations and participate in public community events.   Here they receive culturally competent services (across their intersecting identities, i.e. ethnicity, gender, sexual orientation) in Spanish which include violence and HIV prevention education groups, one-on-one peer counseling, accompaniment to service agencies, HIV testing, leadership development and case management, as well as spiritual ceremonies, social activities and field trips.   Our staff is made up of queer and trans activists and as an organization we also participate in coalition-building and advocacy on transgender and immigration issues.

Description: WE BELIEVE in one God—Creator of all, infinitely perfect, and eternally existing in three persons: Father, Son, and Holy Spirit.  WE BELIEVE that Jesus Christ is true God and true man, conceived of the Holy Spirit, and born of the virgin Mary. He lived a perfect, sinless life, died on the cross as a sacrifice for our sins, rose bodily from the dead, and ascended into heaven where, at the right hand of God, He is our High Priest and Advocate.  WE BELIEVE that the ministry of the Holy Spirit is to glorify Christ, convict men, regenerate the believing sinner, indwell, guide, and empower the believer for Godly living and service.   WE BELIEVE that the New Birth (Salvation) and the Baptism of the Holy Spirit are the same experience. All believers have been baptized into Jesus Christ by the Holy Spirit making one unified body; because of this, we do not teach a second definite work of grace. As a result of the ministry of the Holy Spirit, His gifts and fruit are to be manifested during this church age.   WE BELIEVE the Bible to be the only inspired Word of God, without error in the original, the complete revelation of His will for the salvation of men, and the final authority for all Christian faith and life.   WE BELIEVE that man, created in the image of God, fell into sin and is therefore lost. Only through regeneration by the Holy Spirit can salvation and spiritual life be obtained.

Name: Hacienda of Hope
Description: Hacienda of Hope is a safe alternative to emergency hospitalization for individuals with mental illness who are experiencing a stressful life event or crisis. This short-term respite home offers the space where peer-guests are able to stay short periods of time (usually a few days) to work on their personal growth and wellness in a safe space free of charge. Hacienda of Hope is a welcoming, non-clinical environment, staffed by others who are able to relate, empathize and offer hope and support through crisis.  The two-story home has nine bedrooms which can accommodate up to eight guests at a time. Guests can participate in cooking and household activities of on-site self-help and wellness groups. The orientation process is simple and each guest works with a peer provider who helps them set goals for their stay. Guests have the opportunity to create individualized wellness and recovery plans and connect with local resources for employment, housing, and mental/physical health care. Frequently Asked Questions  Who can stay at Hacienda of Hope?  Hacienda of Hope serves adults 18 and older.  How long can each guest stay?  Typically, guests stay for 3 to 5 days. If additional support is needed, guests can stay up to 14 days.  Do you need health insurance to stay at Hacienda of Hope?  No insurance is required. Our services are free of charge.  If someone is homeless, can they stay at Hacienda of Hope for a few days?  Guests at Hacienda of Hope must have an identified source of housing or a permanent residence.  Where are you located?  Hacienda of Hope is located in Long Beach, CA centrally located to a variety of community and social resources.  Can someone get there on public transportation?  Yes. Contact us to find out how.  How do you handle medication management for individuals taking prescribed medication?  There are no medical personnel on staff. Guests are responsible for managing their own medication. Lock boxes are provided for safe keeping.  Are there doctors on staff?  No, there are no medical personnel on staff. All services are provided by peers, individuals with lived experience of mental illness.  Do guests work with a Peer Specialist?  Yes. A peer specialist helps guests develop a personal plan for recovery and wellness.  Does Hacienda of Hope offer self-help groups and classes?  Our self-help groups are centered on the Wellness Recovery Action Plan (WRAP) and the SAMHSA’s Eight Dimensions of Wellness.  Is Hacienda of Hope accessible to those with physical disabilities?  Hacienda of hope is fully wheelchair and disability accessible.

HEAT offers a wide range of services for all members of the community including comprehensive medical care, case management, HIV counseling and testing (C/T), mental health care, treatment adherence, outreach, support services and access to research to high-risk and HIV-infected youth. All of their services are confidential and comprehensive. The program takes referrals from all 5 boroughs and offers services regardless of their ability to pay.

Name: Health & Human Resource Education Center (HHREC)
Description: The Health and Human Resource Education Center (HHREC) is committed to creating and improving the life quality of Bay Area residents by reducing the use of alcohol, tobacco, and other drugs. The Downtown TAY focus on young adults and helps them to find housing, employment, health, education service, and mental health wellness.

Name: Health Advocates
Description: Health Advocates represents individuals with disabilities who wish to apply for and/or appeal a denied application for Supplemental Security Income (SSI) / Social Security Disability Insurance (SSDI), Medi-Cal and other forms of health insurance.

Name: Health and Environment Resource Center
Description: The Health & Environment Resource Center (HERC) offers education programs to help people learn about the connection between the environment and human health.

Name: Health and Wellness Online Resources
Description: Resources help families stay informed and active while at home.

Name: Health Brigade
Description: Health Brigade provides quality health services, especially to those least served, in a compassionate and non-judgmental environment. Health Brigade is proud to be an inclusive organization.

Name: Health Career Connection (HCC)
Description: Health Career Connection (HCC) helps recent undergraduate and graduate students gain health promotion/education, community organizing, finance/accounting, policy analysis/ advocacy, research, quality improvement experience in the healthcare and public health fields through internships at health organizations.

Name: Health Connected
Description: Health Connected offers comprehensive sexual health education programs for youth and parents.

Name: Health Express
Description: Health Express is a transportation service that transports Novato residents for medical appointments in Novato.

Name: Health Flex Home Health Services
Description: Health Flex Home Health Services provides home care and disease management programs.

Name: Health Initiatives for Youth (HIFY)
Description: Health Initiatives for Youth is a multicultural organization whose mission is to improve the health and well being of young people through youth leadership, popular education and advocacy. It also provides health information to young people and supports them in making their own decisions.

Name: Health Insurance Counseling & Advocacy Programs (HICAP)
Description: Health Insurance Counseling & Advocacy Programs (HICAP) offers free, unbiased, one-on-one assistance about health insurance benefits, options, and rights.

Name: Health Net
Description: Health Net provides more affordable health care plans for individuals, families, and Medicare beneficiaries. There are a variety of plans to choose from, and these plans include coverage for vision, dental, chiropractic, acupuncture, and mental health services.

Name: Health Partnership
Description: Health Partnership is a care ministry of Whittier Area Community Church which promotes physical, emotional, and spiritual well being in the context of our relationship to God.

Name: Health Plan of San Mateo
Description: Health Plan of San Mateo is a non-profit that provides health coverage to San Mateo County residents.

Name: Health Resources & Services Adminstration (HRSA)
Description: Health Resources & Services Adminstration (HRSA) is an agency that focuses on improving health care for people who are isolated and vulnerable.

Name: Health Right 360
Description: Health Right 360 provides affordable and accessible healthcare that offers a full range of traditional health care services, as well as mental health, substance use disorder treatment, non-Western medicine and specific programs focusing on testing, prevention and treatment of HIV/AIDS, Hepatitis C and diabetes.

Name: Health Trust
Description: Health Trust offers health, housing and nutrition services to residents of Santa Clara County.

Name: Healthier Kids Foundation
Description: Healthier Kids Foundation assists with newborn/infant healthcare coverage, health education classes/outreach, dental, hearing, and vision screening and follow-up.

Name: HealthRIGHT 360
Description: HealthRIGHT 360 provides primary medical care, mental health services, substance use disorder treatment, social support and re-entry services, dental, and more.

Name: HealthRight International's Human Rights Clinic (HRC)
Description: Through its Human Rights Clinic (HRC), HealthRight International provides forensic psychological, medical, and gynecological evaluations of foreign-born survivors of torture and other human rights abuses for use in immigration proceedings. Evaluations are performed by HRC-trained volunteer medical and mental health professionals. The HRC is currently active in the New York metro area (NY, NJ, CT). In recent years, HealthRight has served vulnerable immigrant populations including: unaccompanied migrant children fleeing gang violence, abuse and neglect in their home countries; women and children escaping severe domestic abuse; sexual and gender minorities escaping persecution in countries due to homophobia and transphobia; and survivors of human trafficking who have been exploited and abused in their home countries and in the U.S.

Name: Healthy African American Families
Description: Healthy African American Families is a nonprofit that offers community services and health education to the African American, Latino and Korean communities in Los Angeles.

Name: Healthy Communities
Description: Healthy Communities offers community members physical and mental health services, financial class, computer labs, and more at their seven regional locations.

Name: Healthy Families FL
Description: Healthy Families Florida is a nationally accredited home visiting program for expectant parents and parents of newborns.

Name: Healthy Hearts San Francisco
Description: Control and prevent cardiovascular disease in Latino and African American communities by connecting patients to physical activity resources

Name: Healthy Mendocino
Description: Healthy Mendocino and Covered Mendocino is a coalition of community organizations and government agencies offering enrollment assistance to Mendocino County residents in need of affordable health insurance coverage through Medi-Cal or Covered California.

Name: Healthy Minds-Healthy Aging
Description: Healthy Minds-Healthy Aging provides a variety of mental health services for older adults (age 60 and older) living in Napa County

Name: Healthy San Francisco
Description: Healthy San Francisco is an Innovative Health Access Program that offers eligible individuals and families access to free or low-cost health care coverage regardless of immigration status, employment status, or pre-existing conditions.

Name: Healthy Start of North Central Florida Coalition
Description: Created in 1991 by Florida legislation, Healthy Start calls for the screening of all Florida’s pregnant women and infants to identify those at risk for poor birth, health and developmental outcomes. Services include parenting education, nutritional education, breastfeeding support and education, smoking cessation, care coordination and access to prenatal and child healthcare.

Name: Hearing Aid Helpline
Description: Hearing Aid Helpline provides cleaning, maintenance and repair, batteries for hearing aid. Free assistance for government employees and senior citizens.

Name: Hearing and Speech Center
Description: The Hearing and Speech Center of Northern California offers life-long professional services to all individuals with hearing loss or communication difficulties.

Name: Hearing Loss Association of America
Description: The Hearing Loss Association of America, California State Association (HLAA-CA) is a volunteer-run, nonprofit organization providing hearing loss information, education, support, and advocacy services to Californians with hearing loss, their families, and friends.

Name: Heart and Soul
Description: Heart and Soul offers a variety of mental health recovery-oriented and wellness support opportunities for adults within San Mateo County.

Name: Heart of Ida
Description: The Heart of Ida provides programs for older adults to preserve their independence and if needed offers assisted living services.

Name: Heart of Los Angeles (HOLA)
Description: Heart of Los Angeles (HOLA) gives students an equal chance to succeed through a comprehensive array of after-school academic, arts, athletics and wellness programs. Our success is founded on safe environments, nurtured by a no-wrong-door approach, amplified by world-renowned partners, and perpetuated by students who become productive, caring, and responsible citizens. All of HOLA’s programs continue to be offered at no cost to the families who it serves.

Name: Heart of the Valley Services for Seniors Inc.
Description: Heart of the Valley Services for Seniors Inc. facilitates, advocates, and supports independent living for seniors residing in West Santa Clara County. They provide escorted transportation, handyman work, light yard work, help with house projects, paperwork, shopping, errands, friendly visits, computer assistance, and more. All services are free of charge and conducted by qualified volunteers.

Name: Heartland Alliance's National Immigrant Justice Center (NIJC), LGBTQ Immigrant Rights Initiative
Description: Heartland Alliance's National Immigrant Justice Center (NIJC) is dedicated to ensuring human rights protections and access to justice for all immigrants, refugees and asylum seekers. NIJC's LGBTQ Immigrant Rights Initiative provides legal services to low-income immigrants who identify as lesbian, gay, bisexual, or transgender (LGBT) and those who are living with HIV. Their direct representation work is limited to the Midwest, mostly those appearing before the Chicago immigration courts. This limitation does not apply to detained individuals or those seeking assistance with an appeal. (If you or someone you know is detained by immigration, no matter where in the country the detention center is located, NIJC can provide information and assistance to help the detained individual avoid deportation.)

Name: Heartland Hospice Services
Description: Heartland Hospice Services provide home health care, hospice care, skilled nursing, memory care and post-acute care.

Name: Heartlight
Description: Heartlight offers support services for seniors, including assistance in finding independent living facilities, assisted living homes and nursing homes.

Name: Hebrew Free Loan Association of San Francisco
Description: Hebrew Free Loan Association of San Francisco assists Jewish people by aid of loans, grants, and such services as the individual may require. Such loans, grants, and services shall be rendered without interest or other charge.

Name: Hello Housing
Description: Hello Housing works with partners through the Bay Area to develop affordable housing and  loans to first time home buyers.

Name: Hello, Wonderful
Description: Hello, Wonderful offers creative DIY, arts, crafts, and fun activities for kids.

Name: Helmets to Hardhats
Description: Helmets to Hardhats provides construction job search services to Veterans, including resume building, job postings and apprenticeship programs for transitioning to civilian life.

Name: Help a Mother Out
Description: Help a Mother Out distributes diapers to families in need through a network of community-based organizations.
Region: San Francisco Bay Area, CA, USA

Name: Help Me Grow Solano

A Help Me Grow Family Navigator will assist you by listening to your concerns, assess your child’s and family’s needs, and provide you with information and referrals to appropriate resources.

Name: Help Me Help You
Description: Help Me Help You helps homeless and low-income families and individuals access food, provides health education and financial literacy, and assists in CalFresh (Food Stamp) & Medi-Cal/Covered California enrollment, and Social Security application.

Name: Help of Southern Nevada
Description: Help of Southern Nevada is a non-profit organization offering utility assistance, senior programs, emergency resources for shelter and housing, homeless services, and baby first services.

Name: Help One Child
Description: Help One Child offers assistance to foster parents.

Name: Help the Children

Name: Helping Hands Clinic

Name: Helping Hands, Caring Hearts

Name: Helpline Youth Counseling, Inc.
Description: Helpline Youth Counseling, Inc. provides a community helpline, substance abuse treatment and family services.

Name: HelpNow!

Name: Henrico Volunteer Rescue Squad

Name: Heritage Clinic

Name: Herman Ostrow School of Dentistry of USC
Description: The Herman Ostrow School of Dentistry of USC operates multiple clinics throughout Los Angeles.  Faculty members supervise dental students and residents in giving comprehensive care.

Name: HIAS Maryland
Description: HIAS works in the United States and 10 countries, helping to secure protection and legal status for those seeking protection. They provide pro bono representation in deportation proceedings and in obtaining humanitarian visas and asylum, while also providing holistic support to our clients through wraparound services.

Name: HIAS New York
Description: HIAS New York provides direct services to refugees, asylees, Special Immigrant Visa holders (SIVs) and other humanitarian migrants, with the goals of successful integration into the community and facilitating self-sufficiency. In New York City, HIAS resettles newly arrived refugees and provides legal support for asylum seekers. As an affiliate of the sole Jewish refugee resettlement agency, HIAS New York is proud to implement HIAS’ mission of welcoming the stranger and protecting the refugee regardless of race, religion, nationality or sexual orientation.

Name: HIAS Pennsylvania
Description: HIAS Pennsylvania provides legal, resettlement, citizenship, and supportive services to immigrants, refugees, and asylum seekers from all backgrounds in order to ensure their fair treatment and full integration into American society.

Name: High Desert Regional Health Center
Description: At the High Desert Regional Health Center, doctors, nurses and other health providers work together with patients and families to develop partnerships that improve patient care and wellbeing.

Name: High Road Program, Inc.
Description: High Road Program, Inc. offers multiple types of alcohol and drug abuse counseling and education in both Los Angeles and Riverside counties. Most of these services are provided to individuals referred by the Court, Department of Motor Vehicles, County Probation or State Parole Agency.

Name: High School for Excellence and Innovation
Description: High School for Excellence and Innovation provides students with opportunities to exercise student voices and choice during their high school experience. The school builds the students' capacity to fully participate as community members of their schools; helping them become agents of change who positively affect their homes, communities, and the world. The school's belief is that regardless of previous challenges, every student can earn a high school diploma and be prepared to transition to post-secondary training and education. Graduation rate is at 61%.

Name: Highland Hospital
Description: Highland Hospital is Alameda Health System’s flagship, with 236 inpatient beds; a renowned regional trauma center; nationally recognized medical and clinical teaching and research; and state-of-the-art primary, specialty, and multi-specialty care. It specializes in maternal-child services and advanced care.

Name: Hillcrest Congregational Church
Description: Hillcrest Congregational Church offers services such as free food and clothing for people in need.

Name: Hillside Church of God

Name: Hillsides

The Center also works with government and community agencies to address housing, employment and transportation needs.

Name: Hines Helping Hands

Name: HIP Housing (Human Investment Project)

Name: HippoCampus

Name: Hire Heroes USA

Name: Hispanic Scholarship Fund

Name: HIV/HCV Resource Center (H2RC)

Name: Hively

Name: Hollywood Food Coalition

Name: Hollywood Sunset Free Clinic
Description: Hollywood Sunset Free Clinic is a primary health care facility which provides free quality medical, counseling and related services to individuals of Echo Park, Silver Lake, East Hollywood and downtown communities of Los Angeles. Clinic services are provided by a small staff and volunteer medical and counseling professionals and paraprofessionals who donate their time and experience in service to the community.

Name: Hollywood WorkSource Center

Name: Holy Family Giving Bank

Name: Home First

Name: Home Hospital School Program

Carlson is staffed by fully credentialed contracted and retired teachers assigned to serve students in their homes or at hospital sites. Carlson teachers, to the maximum extent possible, provide instruction in subjects and courses correlating with the student's home school program.

Name: Home Match

Name: Home Owner Preservation Foundation

Name: Homeful.LA

Name: Homeless I.D. Project

Name: Housing Authority of the City of Alameda
Description: Housing Authority of the City of Alameda supports low-income housing in Alameda by administering Section 8 programs, developing and managing their own properties, and providing other housing-related support services.

Name: Housing Authority of the County of Alameda
Description: The Housing Authority of the County of Alameda (HACA) operates a number of housing programs that provide low-cost rental housing or rental assistance for low-income families, the elderly, people with disabilities, and others.

Name: Housing Authority of the County of Contra Costa
Description: The Housing Authority of Contra Costa County provides resources for those who hold section 8 vouchers and provides Project Based Vouchers and other resources for affordable housing when available.

Name: Housing Choices
Description: Housing Choices helps people with intellectual disabilities find and sustain affordable housing.

Name: Housing Consortium of the East Bay
Description: Housing Consortium of the East Bay offers services for affordable, independent housing opportunities for people with developmental disabilities and/or serious mental illnesses and their families in Alameda and Contra Costa counties

Name: Housing Education Program
Description: The Housing Education Program is a Division of Consumer Credit Counseling Service of San Francisco. They provide housing counseling and education to community residents.

Name: Housing Endowment and Trust of San Mateo County (HEART)
Description: Housing Endowment and Trust of San Mateo County (HEART) provides support for first time homebuyers including down payment assistance and homebuyer workshops.

Name: Housing Equality Law Project (HELP)
Description: Housing Equality Law Project (HELP) employs a diverse group of professionals to carry out its mission of addressing discrimination in housing.

Name: Housing Industry Foundation (HIF)
Description: HIF helps individuals and families remain in or find stable housing throughout the Counties of San Mateo and Santa Clara.

Name: Housing Rights Center
Description: Housing Rights Center is a nonprofit that offers landlord-tenant counseling, investigates discrimination complaints and conducts free housing workshops throughout Los Angeles county.

Name: Housing Rights Committee of San Francisco
Description: The Housing Rights Committee of San Francisco provides free counseling services to San Francisco tenants in all types of housing. They work with all tenants regardless of citizenship status.

Name: Housing Trust Silicon Valley (HTSV)
Description: HTSV gives loans and grants in order to increase the supply of affordable housing, assist first-time homebuyers and prevent homelessness in Silicon Valley.

Name: Housing Works
Description: Housing Works is a healing community of people living with and affected by HIV/AIDS. Their mission is to end the dual crises of homelessness and AIDS through relentless advocacy, the provision of lifesaving services, and entrepreneurial businesses that sustain their efforts.

Name: Housing Works
Description: Housing Works provides advocacy and supportive services for individuals living with HIV/AIDS including housing, healthcare, meals and nutritional counseling, mental health and substance use treatment, job training, and legal assistance.

Name: Houston Immigration Legal Services Collaborative - Immigrant Rights Hotline
Description: The Immigrant Rights Hotline is a source of timely and accurate information about changing immigration policies, a place to report discrimination and racial profiling, and a source for referrals to legal services providers and immigrant rights organizers. The hotline is staffed by non-profit staff and DOJ accredited representatives. Callers can get assistance Monday through Friday, 9:00 am to 5:00 pm (except holidays). Hotline is a project of the Houston Immigration Legal Services Collaborative, Boat People SOS, BakerRipley, United We Dream, Houston Volunteer Lawyers, and The ACLU of Texas.

Name: Howell Mountain Elementary School District
Description: Howell Mountain Elementary School District helps its students succeed by providing skills and resources.

Name: Hubert H. Humphrey Comprehensive Health Center
Description: Hubert H. Humphrey Comprehensive Health Center provides primary care and urgent care services.

Name: Huckleberry Youth Programs
Description: Huckleberry Youth Programs offers services for runaway, homeless and/or at-risk youth and their families.  Programs include counseling, a shelter, health care, career training, and support for trafficked and arrested youth.

Name: Human Rights Campaign
Description: Encourages lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender and queer Americans to live their lives openly and seeks to change the hearts and minds of Americans to the side of equality.

Name: Human Rights First
Description: Human Rights First helps people living in the greater Washington, D.C., New York City, Los Angeles and Houston metropolitan areas who do not already have legal representation, cannot afford an attorney, and need help with a claim for asylum or other protection-based form of immigration status. Their New York and Houston offices can also help people who are seeking asylum from within a nearby immigration detention center.

Name: Human Services Agency of San Francisco
Description: Human Services Agency of San Francisco provides supportive services including early child care, employment and job training, child welfare, financial assistance, food assistance, housing and homeless services plus services for seniors and adults with disabilities.

Name: Human Services Association (HSA)
Description: Human Services Association (HSA) is a nonprofit agency that provides social services to children, adults, and families who live in southeast Los Angeles County. Programs includes family services, early childhood education, and services for seniors.  DUE TO COVID NORMAL SERVICES HAVE BEEN SUSPENDED OR CHANGED

Name: Human Trafficking Task Force
Description: The Human Trafficking Task Force (HTTF) investigates claims of human trafficking in Santa Clara County.

Name: HumanGood
Description: HumanGood provides housing and services for seniors in California.

Name: Humanistic Alternatives to Addiction Research and Treatment Inc. (HAART) - Hayward
Description: HAART - Hayward offers treatment for problematic opioid use (this includes heroin and prescription analgesics such as oxycontin/oxycodone, morphine, hydromorphone, Vicoden, fentanyl, and others), poly-drug use, co-occurring disorders, selective pain management, and aftercare.  HAART offers both maintenance and long term detoxification services which includes private psychotherapy.

Name: Humanistic Alternatives to Addiction Research and Treatment Inc. (HAART) - Oakland
Description: Humanistic Alternatives to Addiction Research and Treatment Inc. (HAART) - Oakland provides counseling and legal and medically supervised access to opiate replacement therapy in a manner that encourages self-regulation.

Name: Humanities Preparatory Academy
Description: Humanities Preparatory Academy provides a diverse student body with personalized education with an emphasis on participatory democracy, inquiry-based learning, performance-based assessment, and community service. They accept both incoming 9th graders, and transfer students seeking an alternative, more individualized educational setting. Graduation rate is at 88%, accepting incoming 9-12th graders and international students. No credits or Regent exams required.

Name: Hunters Point Family
Description: Hunters Point Family is a community-based organization that provides programs supporting at-risk youth and young adults living in Bayview Hunters Point, San Francisco.

Name: Hunters Point Shipyard Artists
Description: Hunters Point Shipyard Artists support 300 artists with studios at the Shipyard, organize public Open Studios each spring and fall, and coordinate arts education programs for Bayview Hunters Point children and adults.

Name: Huntington Beach Adult School
Description: Huntington Beach Adult School (HBAS) as part of the Huntington Beach Union High School District serves the local adult community in academics, language acquisition, vocational training, and personal enrichment.  Courses include but are not limited to English as a Second Language (ESL), High School Diploma (ASE), General Education Development (GED), Career Technical Education (CTE), Community Education and Personal Enrichment.

Name: Huntington Hospital
Description: Huntington Hospital provides medical services.

Name: Huntington Park Community Adult School
Description: Adult schools provide education for adults to reach their educational goals such as obtaining a GED certificate, job training, ESL, and more.

Name: Huntington Park Farmers Market
Description: Huntington Park Farmers Market is a year-round farmers market open every Wednesday.

Name: Huntington Senior Care Network
Description: Multipurpose Senior Services Program (MSSP) for very frail adults with disabilities 65+ on Medi-Cal who qualify for placement in nursing facilities; Assisted Living Waiver for same population to be in assisted living facility instead of a facility.

Name: Hurting and Hungry Food Oasis: Los Angeles
Description: Food pantry with LA locations every week (call for dates as they vary).

Name: Hyde Street Community Services
Description: Hyde Street Community Services provides outpatient mental health services to San Francisco adults at a mental health clinic located in the Tenderloin.

Name: Hydrocephalus Association
Description: The Hydrocephalus Association serves as a library for research on hydrocephalus, a condition defined by an abnormal, excessive accumulation of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) within the cavities of the brain.

Name: HYPOTHEkids
Description: HYPOTHEkids provides qualified students with hands-on science and engineering educational plus mentorship experiences through internship summer programs.

Name: I Did Something Good Today Foundation
Description: I Did Something Good Today Foundation (IDSGTF) helps homeless seniors within Los Angeles County with health navigation services and social isolation prevention programs.

Name: Iglesia Dos Testamentos En El Desierto
Description: Provides weekly food distribution to the community.

Name: Iglesia Evangelica Camino de Santidad
Description: Provides food distribution weekly.

Name: Iglesia Fuente de Vida
Description: Provides free food and bus tokens to people in the community and members of the church.
Region: Sun Valley, Los Angeles, CA, USA

Name: Iglesia Pentecostes Templo Calvario
Description: Iglesia Pentecostes Templo Calvario provides religious and community services.

Name: Imagine LA
Description: Imagine LA provides mentorship and empowerment program for families who are homeless or at risk of being homeless.

Name: Imagine That!
Description: Imagine That! is a children's museum in Vacaville, CA that provides arts and science programs, exhibits, and community events for children of all ages, with an emphasis on hands-on learning, exploration, and creativity.

Name: Immaculate Conception Academy Cristo Rey
Description: Immaculate Conception Academy is a Catholic college preparatory school that educates young women for a life of faith, integrity, and service. They are committed to providing both excellent education and meaningful corporate work study experiences to students of limited financial resources.

Name: Immanuel Presbyterian Church
Description: Immanuel Presbyterian Church is a faith based organization that offers free food through its Saturday food pantry.

Name: Immanuel Presbyterian Church
Description: Immanuel Presbyterian Church is a faith based organization that offers services to the community in mid-Los Angeles.

Name: Immi

Name: Immigrant and Refugee Community Organization of Manitoba Inc. (IRCOM)
Description: Immigrant and Refugee Community Organization of Manitoba Inc. (IRCOM) provides affordable and safe housing and resources for newcomers to Winnipeg.

Name: Immigrant Defenders Law Center
Description: Immigrant Defenders Law Center (ImmDef) is a law firm that focuses on representing the most vulnerable immigrants, including children in immigration detention and adults with mental health challenges. They accept clients regardless of their eligibility to pay.

Name: Immigrant Legal Defense Program (ILDP)
Description: The Immigrant Legal Defense Program (ILDP) of San Francisco provides legal representation and assistance to immigrants facing deportation in an effort to better represent themselves in a court of law.

Name: Immigrant Legal Resource Center
Description: Immigrant Legal Resource Center (ILRC) is a national, non-profit resource center that provides legal training, educational materials, and advocacy to advance immigrant rights. ILRC aims to work with and educate immigrants, community organizations, and the legal sector.

Name: Immigrants Rising
Description: Immigrants Rising (previously E4FC) supports and encourages undocumented young people to pursue college, a career, and obtaining citizenship through legal services, support groups, and scholarships.

Name: Immigration Advocates Network (Immi)
Description: Immi helps immigrants in the U.S. understand their legal options. Immi offers a free online screening tool, legal information and referrals to nonprofit legal services organizations.

Name: Immigration Center for Women and Children (ICWC)
Description: Immigration Center for Women and Children (ICWC) provides legal services to immigrants in California and Nevada on a sliding scale fee system. It assists children who are abused, abandoned, or neglected and immigrants who are survivors of domestic violence, sexual assault, and other violent crimes.

Name: Immigration Counseling Service (ICS)
Description: Immigration Counseling Service (ICS) offers legal help with the asylum application and interview, deportation or removal proceedings, immigration detention, and deferred action for childhood arrivals (DACA).

Name: Immigration Equality
Description: Immigration Equality is a national organization dedicated to assisting LGBTQ (lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, queer) and HIV-positive people apply for asylum. *Note: Immigration Equality cannot accept walk-ins. They are only able to assist individuals who have scheduled an appointment prior to coming to their office. If you are in need of legal representation or information, call their legal hotline or contact their legal team through their website.

Name: Immigration Services of Mountain View
Description: Immigration Services of Mountain View provides free legal assistance for immigrants. Services include assistance related to visas for victims of domestic abuse and other serious crimes, DAPA and DACA cases, requests for fee waivers, and more.

Name: Immune Enhancement Project
Description: Immune Enhancement Project provides complementary alternative medicine for the community; services include acupuncture, therapeutic massage, herbal therapy, nutritional/lifestyle counseling addressing HIV/AIDS, cancer, hepatitis, substance abuse, cold and flu symptoms, allergies and other disorders such as depression, stress and insomnia; Sponsors several offsite free auricular clinics, where individuals may access acupuncture in a group setting. Operates drop-off site for unused HIV medicines in conjunction with the Recycled AIDS Medicine Program (RAMP).

Name: IMPACT
Description: IMProving Access, Counseling & Treatment (IMPACT) provides free prostate cancer treatment for men living in California with little or no health insurance.

Name: Impact Bay Area
Description: Impact Bay Area offers affordable self-defense classes for children, teens, women, men, and the LGBTQ community.

Name: Impact Drug and Alcohol Treatment Center
Description: Impact Drug and Alcohol Treatment Center offers residential, outpatient, and court ordered alcohol and drug treatment services.

Name: Impact Justice
Description: Impact Justice addresses issues currently facing the justice system, including ways to support successful re-entry.

Name: Imperial Church of Christ
Description: Imperial Church of Christ is a religious based organization that offers services to the Los Angeles community.

Name: Imperial Valley LGBT Resource Center
Description: The Imperial Valley LGBT Resource Center works to improve the quality of life for the LGBT population in Imperial County. The Imperial Valley LGBT Resource Center provides support for many different at-risk groups and populations through drug abuse education, HIV testing and counseling, individual and family counseling, anger management groups, youth programs, community events, and more. All services are provided free of charge.

Name: Imprint City
Description: Imprint City is a non-profit organization seeking to activate industrial, under utilized space with arts & culture to encourage economic vitality. The Bayview LIVE Festival, Southside Fest, Bayview SPARC.

Name: In the Meantime Men
Description: In the Meantime Men provides gay African American men with enriching social, educational, health and wellness programs and services.

Name: Independence at Home
Description: Independence at Home offers a number of no-cost innovative programs focused on connecting older adults and their caregivers to the services needed to stay safe and independent at home.

Name: Independence High School
Description: Independence High School offers small and safe environments with high academic standards. They offer a rigorous Common Core aligned curriculum infused with the arts and technology Through enhanced guidance services, and advisor works with each student and family to achieve academic goals and set post-secondary plans. Seniors have opportunities for paid internships. Graduation rate is at 54%.

Name: Independent Living Center of Southern California
Description: The center provides administrative services, emergency services and services for people with disabilities in Los Angeles County.

Description: Independent Living Resource Center of San Francisco provides comprehensive services to individuals with disabilities to help them increase and maintain their independence and provide information and referrals related to assistive technology, housing, employment, and eligibility for benefits, as well as free peer counseling.

Name: Independent Living Resources of Solano & Contra Costa Counties
Description: Independent Living Resources (ILR) of Solano & Contra Costa Counties provides people with disabilities and their families free assistive, accessibility, counseling, and housing services, as well as community education and advocacy.

Name: India Community Center
Description: India Community Center provides programs and resources to the Indo-American and Greater Bay Area community. Services include fitness classes, language classes, meals, community clubs, legal and medical clinics, career services, senior programs, and more.

Name: Indian Health Center
Description: Indian Health Center provides healthcare and wellness services to everyone, including the American Indians/Alaskan Natives community in Santa Clara Valley.

Name: Informed Immigrant
Description: Informed Immigrant is both a digital hub and offline network offering the most up-to-date and accessible information and guidance for the undocumented immigrant community.

Name: Inglewood High School

Name: Inglewood Unified School District
Description: The AEBG block consortia seeks to expand and improve adult education to more members of the public.

Name: Inland Valley Hope Partners

Name: Inland Valley Volunteer Resources Center
Description: Inland Valley Volunteer Resources Center connects volunteers with non-profits.

Name: Inner City Law Center
Description: Inner City Law Center provides a variety of legal services including housing rights, benfits, eviction defense, public benefits and more to low-income tenants, working poor families, immigrants, people who are living with HIV/AIDS or are disabled, and veterans.

Name: Inner City Visions
Description: Inner City Visions is a non-profit organization that helps families in need by providing them necessary resources.

Name: Inneract Project
Description: Inneract Project provides free design classes to underserved youth.

Name: Innovation Diploma Plus
Description: Innovation Diploma Plus, in associate with Catholic Charities Alianza Division, provides students with college preparatory experience, assisting them in post-secondary pursuits. The focus of the school is for every graduate to gain the analytical and social skills needed to success. Graduation rate is at 64%, and enrollment is open to students who have been in high school for at least one year, aged 16-21.

Name: Innovations Community Center
Description: Innovations Community Center Seeks to help families and youths in its community.

Name: Inquilinos Unidos
Description: Informs and educates low-income tenants on their rights and on ways to defend those rights.

Name: Inside/Out Youth Services
Description: Inside/Out Youth Services creates a brave space where LGBTIQIA+ youth (ages 13-22) can freely express themselves, build friendships, and the confidence to be who they are. Their programs include Queer Prom, Drag Night, support groups, healthy dating skills, leadership development, sexual health education, referrals to community resources, a gender affirming clothing closet and more.

Name: Insight Treatment
Description: Insight provides programs for teens experiencing drug, alcohol, and/or emotional problems, focusing on substance use, abuse, dependence, behavioral issues, and school problems.
Region: Sherman Oaks, Los Angeles, CA, USA

Name: Institute for Girls' Development
Description: Institute for Girls' Development supports girls by offering therapy services, perinatal/postpartum services, an individual and group therapy program, help fostering connections, psychological assessment and screening, and a parent group.

Name: Institute for Health and Healing
Description: Offers primary care services such as annual physicals, flu shots and urgent care appointments. Members will have a physician-led team of holistic practitioners with access to onsite integrative medicine services.

Name: Institute for Human and Social Development
Description: Institute for Human and Social Development (IHSD) provides childcare and education services for children ages 0-5 in San Mateo County.

Name: Institute for Multicultural Counseling and Education Services
Description: Institute for Multicultural Counseling and Education Services (IMCES) is an outpatient community clinic. It provides clinical services, clinical training, and education in the Los Angeles community.

Name: Institute for the Redesign of Learning
Description: The Institute for the Redesign of Learning provides special education, mental health, and transition and adult services for individuals with learning, developmental, behavior and/or emotional disabilities as well as individuals with Autism Spectrum Disorders.

Name: Institute of Hispanic-Latino Cultures
Description: The Institute of Hispanic-Latino Cultures aims to support, empower and advance the Hispanic-Latino/a community at the UF.

Name: Institute On Aging - California
Description: Institute On Aging offers a range of services for seniors which include in-home support services, money management, counseling, and case management.

Name: Instituto de Educacion Popular del Sur de California (IDEPSCA)
Description: Instituto de Educacion Popular del Sur de California (IDEPSCA) connects day laborers and household workers (nannies, house cleaners, and personal attendants) with employers for job opportunities, worker rights workshops, leadership development, job skills classes, ESL classes, medical check ups, and more.

Name: Instituto Familiar de la Raza
Description: Instituto Familiar de la Raza (IFR) provides health and wellness programs to the San Francisco Latino community. The organization focuses on HIV, violence, family disputes, trauma, behavioral and mental health issues, and more.

Name: Instituto Laboral de la Raza
Description: Instituto Laboral de la Raza is a resource center that provides free labor rights education, peer counseling, financial education, translation services, and more.

Name: Integral Counseling Center
Description: Integral Counseling Center, through the California Institute of Integral Studies, provides affordable individual, couple, family, youth and group counseling and psychotherapy services.

Name: Integrated Behavioral Health Team (IBHT)
Description: The Integrated Behavioral Health Team (IBHT) provides mental health services in the Los Angeles area, helping individuals with case management services and referrals for mental health treatment.

Name: Integrated Community Services
Description: Integrated Community Services is an organization that focuses on helping individuals with disabilities reach independence and gain self-sufficiency skills.

Name: Inter-Agency Drug Abuse Recovery Program
Description: I-ADARP is an outpatient alcohol and drug abuse recovery treatment program. It is a provider for the Alcohol and Drug Program Administration, a division of the County of Los Angeles Department of Public Health. I-ADARP is committed to providing affordable, quality services.

Name: Inter-City Services (ICS)
Description: Inter-City Services provides free employment training and job placement in computer engineering with an emphasis on sustainability and environmentalism.

Name: Intercounty Fellowship Of Alcoholics Anonymous
Description: Intercounty Fellowship of Alcoholics Anonymous is a fellowship of men and women who share their experience, strength and hope with each other that they may solve their common problem and help others to recover from alcoholism.

Name: Interface Children and Family Services
Description: Interface Children & Family Services provides local clients annually with direct, responsive, wrap-around services to address the complex needs of client and community.    As a critical safety net for children and families, we provide 24 distinct programs across six major program areas including mental health services, youth services, family violence intervention, justice-involved families, and community development and 2-1-1 information and referral in 19 counties.

Name: Interfaith Food Center
Description: Interfaith Food Center provides food to families in Whittier, La Mirada and Santa Fe Springs.

Name: Interfaith Refugee & Immigration Service Episcopal Diocese of LA
Description: The Interfaith Refugee and Immigration Service (IRIS) provides tools and connections to help new arrivals achieve self-sufficiency in the United States. They have several programs including: refugee resettlement, immigration legal services, refugee employment program, cultural orientation, a food pantry program and an ESL/Civics program.

Name: InterFaith Shelter Network
Description: InterFaith Shelter Network (IFSN) provides housing services for homeless individuals, with focus on the chronically homeless in thirteen facilities. Comprehensive services include transitional housing, assistance getting permanent housing, case management, counseling, addiction relapse prevention, parenting education, employment preparation, nutritional food program, and transportation assistance.

Name: Internal Revenue Service (IRS)
Description: The IRS is the U.S. government agency responsible for tax collection and tax law enforcement.

Name: Internal Revenue Service (IRS)
Description: The Internal Revenue Service (IRS) oversees and enforces U.S. federal tax laws.

Name: International Art Society
Description: The International Art Society is an international non-profit organization whose purpose is to encourage excellence, to advance education, to promote the appreciation and development of the International arts, and to support the worldwide community of artists who work with all types of mediums. The International Art Society strives to stimulate communication among artists, educators, students, collectors, gallery and museum personnel, art critics, manufacturers, and all others interested in and involved with the production, technology and aesthetics of art. We are dedicated to creating greater public awareness and appreciation of the International arts. Application for membership is open to anyone interested in art. Members are entitled to vote, hold office, and enjoy all other rights and privileges as determined by the Society's bylaws.

Name: International Association For Premenstrual Disorders (IAPMD)
Description: IAPMD is a not-for-profit organization providing education, support, advocacy, and resources for those affected by Premenstrual Dysphoric Disorder (PMDD) and Premenstrual Exacerbation of underlying disorders (PME).

Name: International Hearing Society
Description: Professional associations of specialists who test hearing aid select, fit, and dispense hearing aids. The society conducts programs of competence qualifications, education, and training, and promotes specialty-level accreditation. The Hearing Aid Helpline provides consumer information and referral.

Name: International Institute of LA
Description: International Institute of LA provides services such as childcare, immigration law, and different types of management services from over 130 multicultural staff members that include child care, transportation, nutrition, and refugee services.

Name: International Institute of the Bay Area (IIBA)
Description: The International Institute of the Bay (IIBA) is a non-profit organization that provides high-quality, low-cost immigration legal services to the Bay Area community. Programs include: citizenship services, deferred action for childhood arrivals, family reunification services, humanitarian services (for survivors and refugees) and more.

Name: International Myeloma Foundation (IMF)
Description: The International Myeloma Foundation (IMF) serves myeloma patients, family members, and the medical community. The IMF provides a wide range of programs in the areas of Research, Education, Support, and Advocacy.

Name: International Pre-Diabetes Center Inc.
Description: International Pre-Diabetes Center Inc. provides diabetes self-management and prevention education.

Name: International Railroad for Queer Refugees (IRQR)
Description: IRQR assists LGBT asylum seekers with finding refuge and and provides them services to help with building a new life. IRQR provides education, guidance, and support throughout the resettlement process to individuals making asylum claims outside of Iran, Afghanistan, Syria, and Iraq.

Name: International Rescue Committee
Description: International Rescue Committee (IRC) offers assistance to newly arrived refugees with the following services: housing, healthcare, food, English language classes, job search and placement, education, social services, legal support and more.

Name: Internet Archive
Description: Internet Archive is a non-profit library of millions of free books, movies, software, music, websites, and more.

Name: Internet Essentials by Comcast
Description: Internet Essentials by Comcast works with schools, government, and non-profit partners to connect Americans with affordable internet, low cost computers, and computer classes.

Name: Internet for All Now
Description: California Emerging Technology Fund is partners with schools & districts serving students with limited resources to access reduced-cost Internet Offers. Through Internet For All Now Act (AB 1665) California in bridging the Digital Divide in California.

Name: Interval House
Description: Interval House provides comprehensive domestic violence services in over 70 different languages to individuals and families in Los Angeles County and Orange County. Over 98% of Interval House staff are multilingual, ethnically diverse, and have been personally affected by domestic violence.

Name: inTRANSitive
Description: inTRANSitive is a Trans led movement working to educate, organize and celebrate the intersections of Trans Community in Arkansas. inTRANSitive seeks to support, liberate and celebrate the Trans Community in Northwest Arkansas through community building, organizing and political education.

Name: Inward Bound Mindfulness Education
Description: Inward Bound Mindfulness Education leads mindfulness retreats for teens, parents, and professionals to cultivate awareness, compassion, and kindness for themselves, others, and the natural world.

Name: iQ Academy California - Los Angeles
Description: iQ Academy California - Los Angeles is an accredited online charter school that offers individualized learning plans for students grade K-12 and accommodations to foster different learning styles.

Name: Iris Center
Description: Iris Center offers mental health services for women living with HIV and their families, including individual, couples, family, and child therapy; therapists offer support on issues related to HIV, drug use and recovery, as well as other issues such as depression, anxiety, recover from trauma and relationship services; provides counseling services (individual and group) for women experiencing depression, anxiety counseling, counseling for physical, sexual or emotional abuse, and family counseling; offers case management, substance abuse recovery services through group, individual, family and job counseling, HIV prevention education and outreach for women, and a prenatal recovery program called Program Day Treatment [formerly known as Save Our Sisters (SOS)] for substance dependent pregnant women, new mothers and children.

Name: Irish Immigration Pastoral Center
Description: The Irish Immigration Pastoral Center (IIPC) assists Irish immigrants in the San Francisco and the Bay Area by providing advice, information, advocacy, referral, and support, including spiritual, social, medical, educational, legal and financial guidance.

Name: Islah LA
Description: Islah LA is an inner-city community center founded by Muslim-Americans to serve South Los Angeles.

Name: Islamic Center of Southern California
Description: Islamic Center of Southern California is a faith based organization that offers food to individuals and families through its food pantry program.

Name: Islamic Circle of North America (ICNA) Bay Area Chapter
Description: Islamic Circle of North America (ICNA) Bay Area Chapter is a faith-based organization that provides services to the community such as meals and a health clinic.

Name: Ismaili Queers Support Group
Description: Ismaili Queers is an informal community group comprising of Jamati members of all ages which seeks to provide a safe space for queer Ismailis to talk to and support one another. In recent years, it has seen energetic leadership from Jamati members who identify as both Ismaili and LGBTQQ who are also invested in building community and sharing support to others belonging to a sexual or gender minority group within the larger Ismaili community. Much of the information sharing occurs online, however there are occasionally events held in Toronto.

Name: ISS of BC
Description: ISS of BC provides a supportive environment for newcomers to Canada of all backgrounds. They are able to help with accessing healthcare, accessing housing, learning English, and gaining employment.

Name: Italian Catholic Federation
Description: Italian Catholic Federation provides a financial assistance program for developmentally disabled children and adults seeking to achieve greater independence in their lives.

Name: Italian Community Services
Description: Italian Community Services provides Bay Area Italian-American individuals and families with trusted resources to help them live healthy, independent and productive lives.

Name: J Cole Recovery Homes, Inc.
Description: Cole House is a treatment provider offering a 12-step Social Model Residential Program for men suffering from drug addiction and alcoholism. Residents receive care in a adobe style family home.

Name: J-Sei
Description: J-Sei is a Japanese community organization that provides programs, services, and assisted living for the elderly plus community events and classes for families and youth.

Name: Jalloh's Upright Services of North Carolina
Description: Jalloh's Upright Services of North Carolina (JUS-NC) is a non-profit organization that supports and empowers our international low-income immigrant and refugee community members, by enhancing the social welfare and economic values within our community, connecting our resources to promote unity and to enable an overall community integration and development.

Name: Jamboree Housing
Description: Jamboree Housing Corporation offers affordable housing opportunities throughout California.

Name: James Baldwin High School
Description: James Baldwin High School, in partnership with NYC Outward Bound Schools and EL Education, is perfect for a student who has had a history of truancy but is seeking to improve. The school offers opportunities inside and outside of school to obtain credits. Students have the opportunity to receive up to 21 credits in one school year. The school's goals is to emphasize core values, participatory democracy, inquiry-based learning, performance-based assessments, and community service. Graduation rate is at 61%.

Name: James C. Hormel LGBTQIA Center

Name: Japanese Community Youth Council

Name: Japanese Cultural and Community Center of Northern California (JCCCNC)

Name: JASMYN
