Name: Los Angeles Beautification Team (LABT)
Description: LABT provides job opportunities and mentoring young people through interactive art, tree planting and cleaning project in their own schools and neighborhoods.

Name: Los Angeles Catholic Worker
Description: Los Angeles Catholic Worker is a faith based organization that operates the Hospitality Kitchen ("Hippie Kitchen") that offers free hot meals.

Name: Los Angeles Center for Law and Justice
Description: The Los Angeles Center for Law and Justice offers free or low cost legal services to qualifying clients. They provide assistance in the areas of immigration, domestic violence, sexual assault, youth (ages 14-24) law, and custody disputes.

Name: Los Angeles Centers for Alcohol and Drug Abuse
Description: Los Angeles Centers for Alcohol and Drug Abuse (L.A. CADA) is a licensed and certified substance use and behavioral treatment provider by the State of California Department of Health Care Services and the County of Los Angeles Department of Public Health.

Name: Los Angeles Central Office of Alcoholics Anonymous (LACOAA)
Description: LACOAA is a group of men and women who share their background with alcoholism, their strength to overcome and the desire to stay sober.  All in a confidential environment so each can express themselves and help others to recover from addiction.

Name: Los Angeles Christian Health Centers (LACHC)
Description: Los Angeles Christian Health Centers (LACHC) serve Los Angeles County’s most vulnerable populations in Skid Row and Boyle Heights. There are two full-time health centers and 10 part-time satellite clinics that provides primary care, dental, mental health, pediatric, social services, prescription and vision services.

Name: Los Angeles City College
Description: Los Angeles City College provides a dynamic and innovative learning environment offering more than 100 vocational and professional programs including degrees, transfer programs, certificates plus career or skills improvement.

Name: Los Angeles Community Action Network
Description: Los Angeles Community Action Network helps residents in the Los Angeles community organize and raise awareness about human and civil rights.

Name: Los Angeles Community College District
Description: Los Angeles Community College District serves adults of all ages learn or retrain skills for their careers.

Name: Los Angeles Conservation Corps
Description: Provides 18-24 year olds with an education, paid on-the-job training, and a suite of support services.

Name: Los Angeles Contemporary Exhibitions (LACE)
Description: LACE provides the community a place to view art projects and attend art events.

Name: Los Angeles County Bar Association
Description: Offers licensing, networking and continuing education to legal professionals in Los Angeles county as well as free legal services to immigrants, veterans and domestic violence victims

Name: Los Angeles County Chief Executive Office
Description: Los Angeles County Chief Executive Office assists the Board of Supervisors with administrating the county.

Name: Los Angeles County Chief Information Office
Description: The Chief Information Office (CIO) provides vision and strategic direction for the effective use of information technology (IT) to achieve business objectives and improve the delivery of services throughout the County of Los Angeles. Within the CIO, the Information Security Office establishes and publishes countywide information security policies and standards to mitigate risks to computer assets and data.

Name: Los Angeles County Child Support Services
Description: The Los Angeles County Department of Child Support Services include opening a case, finding parents, establishing a legal parent-child relationship, establishing child and medical support orders and enforcing support orders. It provides these services at no or little cost.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Agricultural Commissioner/ Weights and Measures
Description: Enforces state laws designed to prevent the introduction and spread of injurious insects, rodents, birds, predatory animals, weeds and plant disease as well as regulating the use of pesticides by private and professional applicators. The Agricultural Commissioner/Weights & Measures also inspects all scales and meters used in trade throughout Los Angeles County for accuracy, inspects packages at the wholesale and retail level for accurate labeling and advertised price accuracy and investigates complaints. The Department operates a number of laboratories and provides solutions for urban wildlife and weed management.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Alternate Public Defender
Description: Los Angeles County Department of Alternate Public Defender provides high quality and caring legal representation to people with financial need charged with a crime where the Public Defender is unable to represent (due to a conflict of interest or unavailability) in court proceedings in the Superior Courts and in appeals to higher courts.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Animal Care and Control
Description: Los Angeles County Department of Animal Care and Control provides animal control and rescue services in our service areas 24 hours a day, seven days a week.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Auditor-Controller
Description: Los Angeles County Department of Auditor-Controller safeguards the County’s financial integrity, advocating and implementing best practices, and ensuring compliance with mandates and fiduciary responsibilities.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Beaches and Harbors
Description: Los Angeles County Department of Beaches and Harbors protects the beaches and harbors.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Children and Family Services
Description: Los Angeles County Department of Children and Family Services provides support to improve the well being of families and children.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Community Development Commission
Description: Los Angeles County Department of Community Development Commission and Housing Authority manages housing for county residents.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Consumer and Business Affairs
Description: Los Angeles County Department of Consumer and Business Affairs provides consumer and worker protections.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Health Services
Description: The Los Angeles County Department of Health Services (DHS) consists of health centers and hospitals that provide health care to Los Angeles County residents.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Human Resources
Description: Los Angeles County Department of Human Resources provides workforce and employment development for County residents.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Medical Examiner-Coroner
Description: Los Angeles County Department of Medical Examiner-Coroner inquires into and determine the circumstances, manner and cause of deaths which fall within its jurisdiction.  These deaths include any suspected homicide, suicide, or accidental deaths.  These also include any natural death were there either is no physician to sign a death certificate, or the physician is unwilling or legally prohibited from doing so.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Mental Health
Description: Los Angeles County Department of Mental Health provides mental health resources for county residents.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Parks & Recreation
Description: Provides access to services offered by county parks and recreation facilities for county residents.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Public Health
Description: Los Angeles County Department of Public Health provides public health services for Los Angeles County residents.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Public Health
Description: Los Angeles County Department of Public Health offers public health clinic services and COVID-19 updates.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Public Health- Child Health and Disability Prevention Program
Description: Provides medical and dental care checkups for children under 21 with Full Scope Medi-Cal or care for children under 19 with low family income

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Public Social Services
Description: Los Angeles County Department of Public Social Services provides access to programs and services for children, families, youth, adult and senior residents throughout the region.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Public Works
Description: LA County Public Works is responsible for the design, construction, operation, and maintenance of roads, traffic signals, bridges, airports, sewers, flood control, water supply, water quality, and water conservation facilities. Its diverse operations fall within six core service areas: Transportation, Water Resources, Waste Management, Public Buildings, Development Services, and Emergency Management.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Regional Planning
Description: The Department of Regional Planning performs all land use planning functions for the unincorporated areas of Los Angeles County. Our services include long range planning, land development counseling, project/case intake and processing, environmental review and zoning enforcement for each of our County unincorporated communities.

Name: Los Angeles County Department of Registrar-Recorder/County Clerk
Description: Records, maintains and issues copies of records of real estate transactions, births, deaths, and marriages in Los Angeles County. Maintains fillings of fictitious business name statements, administers notary public oaths and authenticates notary signatures. Issues marriage licenses and performs marriage ceremonies. Provides information on elections, voter registration, absentee ballots, deputy registrars, precinct officers, polling places, candidate filing and campaign financial statements. The Department also issues and accepts voter registration forms and absentee voter applications as well as providing public officials roster, voter guides and polling place locations.

Name: Los Angeles County District Attorney's Office
Description: Los Angeles County District Attorney's Office investigates and prosecutes criminal activity.

Name: Los Angeles County Executive Office of Board of Supervisors
Description: The Board of Supervisors is the governing body of the County of Los Angeles.

Name: Los Angeles County Fire Department
Description: Los Angeles County Fire Department protects lives, the environment, and property by providing prompt, skillful, and cost-effective fire protection and life safety services.

Name: Los Angeles County Housing Resource Center
Description: Los Angeles County Housing Resource Center helps people list and find affordable special-needs and emergency housing within the County of Los Angeles.

Name: Los Angeles County Internal Services Department
Description: Los Angeles County Internal Services Department provides facilities, IT, purchasing and contracts, administration and finance, and sustainability support for all County agencies.

Name: Los Angeles County Museum of Art (LACMA)
Description: Los Angeles County Museum of Art (LACMA) provides culture and art experiences including classes and camps for children.

Name: Los Angeles County Office of Education
Description: Los Angeles County Office of Education oversees the school system for its residents.

Name: Los Angeles County Office of the Assessor
Description: Los Angeles County Office of the Assessor collects property value information to determine and manage property taxes.

Name: Los Angeles County Office of the County Counsel
Description: The Office of County Counsel provides legal representation, advice and counsel to the Board of Supervisors, County departments, special districts, and other public agencies, as mandated and authorized by the County charter and State statutes.

Name: Los Angeles County Office of the Public Defender
Description: The Los Angeles County Public Defender is a law office established and funded by the County of Los Angeles. The office offers legal services to individuals who are accused of public offenses and who cannot afford to retain the services of a private attorney. It also  represents any person under the age of 18 who is facing juvenile delinquency proceedings, or regarding whom the state has instituted wardship proceedings plus individuals who are involuntarily detained in medical facilities, those as to whom conservatorship proceedings have been instituted and patients whose competency to refuse medical treatment is challenged and finally, individuals who are subject to contempt proceedings for violation of court orders.  The office also offers workshops and seminars to assist individuals with legal issues.

Name: Los Angeles County Probation Department
Description: Provides Supervision that is imposed by a Judge instead of detention or incarceration to Juvenile and Adult Offenders. Provides services to assist clients to obtain pro-social skills in order to stay in compliance with the terms and conditions set by the courts. Provides safety and security within all detention facilities and camp settings. To restore victims and provide safety to the community. Empower and Advocate for clients on Probation.

Name: Los Angeles County Superior Court
Description: The Los Angeles Superior Court is dedicated to serving our community by providing equal access to justice through the fair, timely and efficient resolution of all cases.

Name: Los Angeles County Treasurer and Tax Collector
Description: Los Angeles County Treasurer and Tax Collector bills, collects, invests, borrows, safeguards and disburses monies and properties in Los Angeles County.

Name: Los Angeles Department of Water and Power
Description: Los Angeles Department of Water and Power (LADWP) provides water and power utility to Los Angeles residents.

Name: Los Angeles Education Corps
Description: The Los Angeles Education Corps (LAEC) is a 501(c)3 nonprofit organization established in 2008. It is the charter management organization overseeing College Bridge Academy (CBA) charter school and The Education Corps (TEC)/Saito High School.  LAEC educates and supports young people, ages 14-25, who are looking for a second chance to earn their high school diploma. All LAEC campuses are accredited by the Western Association of Schools and Colleges (WASC).

Name: Los Angeles Family Source Center
Description: Los Angeles Family Source Centers offer multi-benefit screening, pre-employment and employment supports, youth education and cultural after-school activities including tutoring and college access activities.

Name: Los Angeles Food Not Bombs
Description: Los Angeles Food Not Bombs provides hot meals throughout the Los Angeles area.

Name: Los Angeles Food Policy Council

Name: Los Angeles Harbor College - Community Services and Continuing Education
Description: Los Angeles Harbor College provides access to associate and transfer degrees, certificates, economic and workforce development, and adult and noncredit instruction.

Name: Los Angeles Housing Partnership

Name: Los Angeles Job Corps Center

Description: The Los Angeles Mission is a Christian organization that provides support services to men, women, and children in need. They provide both residential and emergency services to the community, including meals, showers, clothing, academic courses, employment workshops, job search assistance, and referral services.

Name: Los Angeles Mission College
Description: Los Angeles Mission College is a public community college in the Sylmar district of Los Angeles, California. It is part of the Los Angeles Community College District and it is accredited by the Western Association of Schools and Colleges

Name: Los Angeles Philharmonic

Name: Los Angeles Technology Center
Description: All educational and vocational opportunities are offered without regard to race, color, national origin, sex, or disability. A lack of English language skills will not be a barrier to admission and participation in educational and vocational programs. Los Angeles Technology Center is operated by the Division of Adult and Career Education, Los Angeles Unified School District. Discover the many free or low cost educational and career opportunities that are available. We look forward to helping you achieve your personal and professional goals.

Name: Los Angeles Trade Tech College
Description: Los Angeles Trade Tech College provides courses for career or skills improvement.

Name: Los Angeles Unified School District

Region: Valley Glen, Los Angeles, CA, USA

Services include a student parent program, lactation room, parenting workshops, infant and toddler playgroups, internships, a children’s clothing exchange program, baby supplies, and family events.
Region: Valley Glen, Los Angeles, CA, USA

Description: Love A Child Missions serves homeless women and children of Contra Costa County by providing emergency shelter, food, clothing and offering hope through substance recovery programs, job training, educational support, and many other programs.

Name: Low Income Housing Institute
Description: The Low Income Housing Institute (LIHI) provides housing and hygiene services for low-income individuals, including those experiencing homelessness, in Washington state. LIHI provides a variety of supportive services to help residents maintain their housing and develop self-sufficiency, including case management, life skills training, technology access and training, financial literacy training and savings programs, and activities for children in LIHI housing.

Name: Lower East Side Preparatoy High School
Description: Lower East Side Prep offers a supportive staff to students, with a plethora of programs, clubs and internships for students to participate in. There are various elective options, and the school serves an overwhelmingly Asian student population. Graduation rate is at 55%.

Name: Loyola Center for Conflict Resolution
Description: Loyola Center for Conflict Resolution (LCCR) provides mediation, conciliation and facilitation services, and conflict resolution training to communities throughout Los Angeles County (particularly those adjacent to the Law School).

Name: Lucie's Place
Description: Lucie’s Place provides LGBTQ young adults experiencing homelessness in Central Arkansas with safe living environments, job training and counseling services in order to ensure lifelong stability and success, and works to promote equality and acceptance for LGBTQ young adults.

Name: Lucile Packard Children's Hospital Stanford

Name: Lumos Transforms
Description: Wellness program in Los Angeles, California.

Name: Lupus Foundation of America
Description: Lupus Foundation of America provides answers and support about Lupus.

Over 60% of their staff came to the United States as refugees or asylum seekers. Refugees Northwest staff also speaks over 15 languages.

Name: Lutheran Family Services Rocky Mountains

They provide help and support to children and families during their most challenging times regardless of race, religion, gender, sexual orientation or age.

Name: Lutheran Social Services - Big Bear Lake

Name: Lutheran Social Services - Ventura County

It also defends immigrants in deportation proceedings.

Name: Lutheran Social Services of Northern California

Name: Lutheran Social Services of Southern California - Orange County
Description: The Lutheran Social Services Community Care Centers provide emergency services and social services to individuals and families living in Orange County.

Name: Lynwood Community Adult School
Description: Lynwood Community Adult School has been serving the community of Lynwood since 1954. It presently operates during three-trimester sessions within the traditional school calendar year. The programs offered include Adult Basic Education, Citizenship, English as a Second Language, High School Diploma/GED, Career Technical Education – Business, Career Technical Education - Medical, Program for Older Adults and Parent Education.

Name: Lynwood High School
Description: Lynwood High School is a public school in Southern California.

Name: Lynwood Unified School District
Description: Lynwood Unified School District helps students graduate college-ready and achieve their academic and personal aspirations.

Name: Lyon-Martin Health Services
Description: Lyon-Martin Health Services provides health care to heterosexual women, bisexual women, lesbians and transgender people in a safe and caring environment, with sensitivity to sexual orientation and gender identity. All services are offered regardless of ability to pay. Lyon-Martin Health Services continues to provide primary and preventive healthcare, mental health services and HIV services to all women, including low-income and uninsured, and transgender people.

Name: Mabuhay Health Center

Region: South of Market, San Francisco, CA, USA

MiB offers studios and mentorship in urban, landscape, and architectural design, printmaking, murals, 3D modeling and fabrication, photography, web design plus graphic design and video.

Name: Magnolia Women's Recovery Program
Description: Magnolia Women's Recovery Program empowers women impacted by addiction to reconnect with their lives and family members through a residential treatment program. In addition, they provide education for those loved ones or family members impacted by drug use.

Name: Maine Family Planning
Description: Maine Family Planning's mission is to ensure that all Maine people have access to high-quality, affordable reproductive health care, comprehensive sexual health education, and the right to control their reproductive lives. Maine Family Planning staff provide compassionate, confidential health services, regardless of gender identity or expression. They listen and provide support without judgment.

Name: MainTrain

Name: Maitri
Description: Maitri helps families from South Asia (Bangladesh, India, Nepal, Pakistan, and Sri Lanka) facing domestic violence, emotional abuse, cultural alienation, human trafﬁcking, or family conﬂict.

Name: Maitri Compassionate Care
Description: Maitri Compassionate Care offers short term medical stabilization, as well as a residential program for individuals with HIV/AIDS who have a prognosis of less than six months and are in need of either hospice care or 24-hour nursing care.

Name: Make the Road New Jersey
Description: Make the Road New Jersey builds the power of immigrant and working class communities in New Jersey to achieve dignity and justice through community organizing, legal and support services, transformative education and policy innovation.

Name: Make the Road New York (MRNY)
Description: Make the Road New York (MRNY) is a New York-based community organizing group focused on immigrant communities. MRNY offers legal and survival services, transformative education, community organizing, and policy innovation.

Name: Make-a-Wish Foundation Greater Bay Area
Description: Make-a-Wish Foundation Greater Bay Area fulfills the wishes of children between the ages of 2 1/2 and 18 battling life-threatening medical conditions.

Name: Making Home Affordable
Description: Making Home Affordable is an official U.S. Department of Treasury and U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development program to provide mortgage help and avoid foreclosure.

Name: Malibu Presbyterian Church

Services are offered at locations throughout LA County.

As one of the largest immigration law practices in Canada, their lawyers are able to represent clients in all types of immigration, citizenship, or refugee protection matters.

Name: Managed Care Solutions (MCS)
Description: Managed Care Solutions (MCS) runs the Hollywood WorkSource Center that provides employment services for its community.

Name: Manalive Violence Prevention Program
Description: Manalive Violence Prevention Program provides violence prevention program designed to teach men to stop their violence.

Name: Manhattan Comprehensive Night & Day High School
Description: Manhattan Comprehensive Night & Day High School offers case management, tutoring, paid internships, career readiness, leadership development, peer support groups, post-secondary education planning to enrolled students. Alumni can enroll in a 28 week Medical Assistant training for their post-secondary education. Graduation rate is at 56%, students must be aged 17-21, and have earned at least 10 credits and passed one Regents exam.

Name: MANNA
Description: MANNA (Metropolitan Area Neighborhood Nutrition Alliance) is a non-profit organization that cooks and delivers nutritious, medically-appropriate meals and provides nutrition counseling to individuals who are battling life-threatening illnesses such as cancer, renal disease, and HIV/AIDS. MANNA delivers 3 meals a day, 7 days a week to the Greater Philadelphia area and Southern New Jersey.

Name: Manual Arts Adult School
Description: Adult schools provide education for the adult population to reach their educational goals such as obtaining a GED certificate, job training ESL, etc.

Name: Maranatha Christian Center

Name: Planned Parenthood's Newfoundland and Labrador Sexual Health Centre
Description: Planned Parenthood-Newfoundland and Labrador Sexual Health Centre is the only Sexual Health Centre for the province and deals exclusively with this area of health services. The clinics are inclusive and safe spaces for all individuals in the province, staffed by caring professionals and medical professionals. Planned Parenthood-NLHSC takes a strength based, harm-reduction, and solution focused approach to the issues faced by lesbian, bisexual, gay, transgender, and queer (LBGTQ+) youth. Drop ins are available during their business hours for peer support, pregnancy tests and options counselling, condom pickup and any sexual health related questions you may have. They also sell birth control to patients who received their prescription through their clinics. A friendly reminder that their sexual health clinics operate on an appointment only basis at their office at 203 Merrymeeting Road, and that they do not hold walk-in clinics.

Name: Play-Well TEKnologies
Description: Play Well offers after school and summer programs for children to learn about engineering through play.

Name: Plaza Community Services
Description: Plaza Community Services provides health, education, and housing services to families in Los Angeles.

Name: Plaza de la Raza Child Development Services, Inc
Description: Plaza de la Raza Child Development Services, Inc. provides childcare for children age 0-5.

Name: Pleasant Hill Recreation & Park District Senior Center
Description: The Pleasant Hill Senior Club serves residents of Pleasant Hill, as well as those of surrounding cities, through recreational, social, and educational activities.

Name: Pleasanton Community Counseling Center
Description: Pleasanton Community Counseling Center (PCCC) is a non-profit counseling center that works to promote happiness, peace, and personal growth. Services include marriage and family counseling for individuals, couples, families, and children.

Name: Pleasanton Community Services Department
Description: Pleasanton Community Services Department offers a wide array of indoor and outdoor activities, classes, services, and facilities for all ages.

Name: Pleasanton Paratransit Services (PPS)
Description: Pleasanton Paratransit Service offers door-to-door and shared-ride transportation services for seniors in Pleasanton and Sunol who are 70 years and older or 18 and older and ADA qualified.

Name: Pleasanton Unified School District
Description: Pleasanton Unified School District offers summer school courses for students from Elementary school through High School to help them catch up and learn things they might have missed in previous years.

Name: Plumas County
Description: Plumas County offers supportive services to individuals and families living in Plumas County.

Name: POCOVI
Description: POCOVI provides peer support and counseling classes for men (particularly Latinos) who are batterers, to stop the cycle of violence.

Name: POI 4Ward Academic Center
Description: We provide low-cost weekly tutoring services for students in grades Pre-K through 8th grade.  We provide homework help, reading support, and math enrichment activities that are assigned based on each student's needs.  Our goal is to see every student succeed regardless of background or socioeconomic status.

Name: Point of Pride
Description: Point of Pride provides free chest binders (specially-designed chest compression garments) to any trans person who needs one and cannot afford or safely obtain one. They have donated thousands of chest binders to trans youth and adults in need in all 50 states and 50+ countries and counting. *Note: They average 60 new requests every single day. Even though they ship out hundreds of binders each month, they are a small volunteer-run non-profit with limited resources, so the waiting list is very long. Depending on the size you need, how many other folks also need that size, the donations they receive – it may take months before you receive your binder.

Name: Polaris
Description: Polaris provides the National Human Trafficking Hotline.

Name: Pomeroy Recreation and Rehabilitation Center
Description: The Pomeroy Recreation and Rehabilitation Center (PRRC) provides recreational, vocational, and educational opportunities for people with disabilities and their families.

Name: Pomona CBAS (ADHC)
Description: Community-Based Adult Services (CBAS), formerly known as Adult Day Health Care, offers services to older or disabled adults to restore or maintain optimal capacity for self-care and  prevent inappropriate or personally undesirable institutionalization.

Name: Pomona Economic Opportunity Center
Description: The PEOC provides opportunities for day laborers so they can find safe work at a fair wage, learn new skills, and be empowered to improve their work conditions.

Name: Pomona Hope
Description: Pomona Hope offers after school programs, art programs, parent support and skill-building, and internships & job training.

Name: Pomona Neighborhood Center, Inc.
Description: Pomona Neighborhood Center provides education, mentoring, and support services to low-income women and children. Services include a financial literacy program, a refuge for single mothers, a winter shelter, and case management.

Name: Pomona Unified School District
Description: Pomona Unified School District (PUSD) serves approximately 30,000 Pre-K-12 students and 17,000 adult learners at 44 schools in Pomona and Diamond Bar, California.

Name: Pomona Valley America's Job Center
Description: Pomona Valley America's Job Center connects adults, youths, and seniors to internships, training, and careers. PV AJCC connects employers to a skilled workforce by conducting recruitments and customized training programs. We offer these services at no cost.

Name: Pomona Valley Christian Center
Description: Pomona Valley Christian Center is a faith-based organization that provides food and various ministries to its community. They offer breakfast and holiday meals, bible studies, and prayer groups.

Name: Pomona Valley Health Centers
Description: Pomona Valley Health Centers offer family medicine and urgent care services in Chino Hills, Claremont, La Verne, and Pomona.

Name: Pomona Valley Hospital Medical Center
Description: PVHMC is a not-for-profit, regional Medical Center the offers services ranging from local primary acute care to highly specialized regional services.

Name: Pomona Valley Transportation Authority
Description: PVTA operates 3 services: (1) Get About is a dial-a-ride service for seniors and disabled persons that serves all four Pomona Valley cities. (2) Claremont Dial-a-Ride is transportation for general public within Claremont. (3) The San Dimas Dial-a-Cab provides general public dial-a-ride services for that city.

Name: Pomona Valley YMCA
Description: The Pomona YMCA is a non-profit organization dedicated to strengthening the community through youth development, healthy living and social responsibility.

Name: Portola and Excelsior Family Connections
Description: Portola and Excelsior Family Connections serves low-income and immigrant working families with over 30 programs ranging from childcare to grandparent support groups. Family Connections aims to foster family relationships in order to create a thriving community.

Name: Portola Baptist Church
Description: Portola Baptist Church offers bilingual Sunday School classes, bilingual Sunday worship services, and Spanish worship services, plus food supplies to the community from the local food bank.

Name: Portuguese Organization for Social Services and Opportunities (POSSO)
Description: The Portuguese Organization for Social Services and Opportunities (POSSO) provides social, recreational, cultural and educational activities for the Portuguese-speaking population of Santa Clara County.  Services include help with transportation, exercise programs, and legal assistance.

Name: Positive Images
Description: Positive Images provides support to Sonoma County's LGBTQIA+ young adults.

Name: Positive Living For Us (PLUS)
Description: Positive Living For Us (PLUS) conducts educational and practical workshops for individuals who have recently tested HIV positive and need guidance on making informed decisions. Topics include HIV pathogenesis, acupuncture and Chinese medicine, drug treatment options, stress management, nutrition, insurance, public benefits, sexuality and dating, and addiction recovery.

Name: Positive Resource Center (PRC)
Description: Positive Resource Center (PRC) provides people service in San Francisco living with or at risk for HIV/AIDS along with the benefits of legal, social, and health services.

Name: Post Adoption Center For Education And Research (PACER)
Description: Post Adoption Center For Education And Research (PACER) offers information, support groups and workshops for adoptees, birth parents and adoptive parents, as well as advocacy for change around adoption issues.

Name: Potrero Hill Health Center
Description: Potrero Hill Health Center offers complete medical services for adults and children. Medical services include prenatal and postpartum care, HIV services, women’s clinic, teen clinic, pregnancy testing, children's clinic, immunizations, nutrition services, STD testing, and treatment; limited dental care, including cavity fillings; social work services, including assistance in applying for Medi-Cal; enrollment site for the AIDS Drug Assistance Program (ADAP).

Name: Potrero Hill Neighborhood House
Description: Potrero Hill Neighborhood House is a community center providing programs for children, youth, adults, and seniors.

Name: Pozo Goldstein LLP
Description: At Pozo Goldstein, LLP's attorneys include have a combined experience of 90 years in immigration law. They provide assistance with asylum applications including a free, in-office case evaluation.

Name: Precious Heritage
Description: Precious Heritage provide supported living services such as Supported Living Services  Independent Living Skills, In-Home Respite Services for Individuals with Autism, Health and Wellness, Personal Care Assistance

Name: Precious Life Shelter
Description: Precious Life Shelter offers emergency shelter at no cost for pregnant women 18 and older.

Name: Precita Eyes Muralists
Description: Precita Eyes Muralists teaches children and youth about art through mural projects.

Name: Pregnancy Counseling Center
Description: This women's health clinic is a non-profit 501(c)3 organization.   It offers free support and referrals.  Services include a pregnancy test, ultrasound, STD information, post-abortion counseling, and referrals.

Name: Pregnancy Help Center
Description: Pregnancy Help Center a licensed medical clinic and pregnancy helpline, offering confidential, free, accurate, early pregnancy and STI testing, options consultations, and ultrasound exams. Pregnancy Help Center does not provide or refer for abortions.

Name: PREP/EBCRP
Description: Early intervention, assessment, treatment, support for transition age youth experiencing psychosis.  Multi-faceted treatment approach focused on wellness and recovery model.  Serving youth ages 16-24, support and education for their families and support network.  Community based, culturally relevant, sensitive to the background and goals of each individual.

Name: PreSchool Family
Description: PreSchool Family is a parent education program for families with children ages 0-5.

Name: Prescott Circus Theatre
Description: Prescott Circus Theatre provides free after-school, weekend, and summer programs in West Oakland. Students learn circus skills and receive homework help.

Name: Prescott Joseph Center
Description: Prescott-Joseph Center for Community Enhancement, Inc. is a non-profit corporation organized in 1995 in the Prescott district of West Oakland.

Name: Prevencion y Rescate (Prevention and Rescue)
Description: Prevencion y Rescate (Prevention and Rescue) provides prevention and recovery resources to families struggling with addictions and gang involvement through programs including an outpatient program, support group, family assemblies, and more.

Name: Pride Center of Vermont
Description: Pride Center of Vermont (PCVT) is the New England’s most comprehensive community center dedicated to advancing community and the health and safety of the Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender and Queer (LGBTQ) Vermonters.

Name: Pride Center of Western New York
Description: The Pride Center is a Buffalo-based health promotion organization specializing in lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender and queer (LGBTQ+) health and HIV prevention. Established in 2001, The Pride Center's goal is to promote the lifelong health and well-being of LGBTQ+ people.   Their office is in Buffalo, but they provide services throughout the eight counties of Western New York State.

Name: Pride Centre of Edmonton
Description: The Pride Centre of Edmonton is a non-profit, registered charity whose mission is to provide social support services to members of the LGBTQ2S+ population, their families and their communities. They do this through direct support, outreach, and education, and creating safe spaces.

Name: Pride for Youth
Description: Pride for Youth is a service and an advocate for lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, and queer/questioning (LGBTQ) young people through age 30. The Adult Sexual Health Program serves LGBTQ individuals through age 45. Pride of Youth provide education and supportive services to enhance the health, wellness and cultural competency of LGBTQ young people. Registration is not required for any of their programs. While one may wish to call ahead to ensure eligibility and confirm activity times, walk-ins are always welcome.

Name: Pridecorps
Description: Groups at Pridecorps typically have both a fun and educational component and explore topics such as coming out and disclosure, substance abuse and mental health, suicide prevention, bullying and harassment, self-esteem, safe sex, HIV and STI prevention, wellness and nutrition.

Name: Pridelines (Miami's LGBTQ Community Center)
Description: Pridelines is Miami's LGBTQ Community Center. Pridelines' mission is to educate and empower South Florida’s lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender and questioning (LGBTQ) youth and community in safe and diverse spaces to promote dialogue, wellness, and to foster social change.

Name: Prince of Peace Episcopal Church
Description: Prince of Peace Episcopal Church is a faith-based organization that provides services such as a food pantry and community meals to residents of the west San Fernando Valley.

Name: Priority Care Medical Group
Description: Provides primary health care, women's & children, geriatrics health care services.

Name: Prison Law Office
Description: The Prison Law Office represents individual prisoners, helps them engage in class action and other impact litigation, educates the public about prison conditions, and provides technical assistance to attorneys throughout the country.

Name: Pro Bono Law Saskatchewan
Description: Through Pro Bono Law Saskatchewn programs, lawyers volunteer their time and expertise to provide legal services to individuals who are ineligible for Legal Aid but are of limited means.

Name: Pro Bono Project
Description: The Pro Bono Project provides legal advice and answers legal questions (could be about immigration, bankruptcy, family, housing, etc.) for Santa Clara County residents through clinics held at local libraries.  Additionally, the Pro Bono Project provides family law services to Santa Clara County residents who have cases in Santa Clara County in domestic violence, custody/visitation, and parentage actions.  Services include preparing documents, help with filing, advice and referral to other resources, negotiation and settlement, limited scope representation, and full legal representation.

Name: Pro Youth Recreation & Family Center, Inc.
Description: Some of the services provided are Education, Life Skills, Empowerment & Character Development.

Name: Professional Pathways High School
Description: Professional Pathways High School, in collaboration with CAMBA, allows all members of the school community to work together in supporting students emotionally, socially, and academically. Professional Pathways High School focuses on students who are at a disadvantage for post-secondary life because they have fallen behind in high school. Staff help develop a student's academic foundation, with technical and career competencies that place them at a better advantage for post-secondary success. Graduation rate is at 62%, and students 16-21 can enroll with at least one year behind in their previous school.

Name: Program for Torture Victims Los Angeles
Description: The Program for Torture Victims Los Angeles helps survivors of state-sponsored torture and persecution by providing basic needs such as food, housing and transportation, as well as legal support, access to medical and mental health care and more.

Name: Progress Foundation
Description: The Progress Foundation provides alternative community treatment options to seriously mentally disabled individuals. They offer a variety of residential treatment programs as well as supported housing.

Name: ProHealth Home Care, Inc
Description: Provides, home healthcare services, hospice care services, and a transition program.

Name: Project 20
Description: Project 20 is a San Francisco Pretrial program that permits residents to pay off parking tickets and other motor vehicle violations through community service.

Name: Project ABC
Description: Project ABC serves families of children 0-5 in the Los Angeles County area who would benefit from mental health, particularly those who are in out-of-home care or at risk for out-of-home placement or when there are concerns about the child’s behavior or emotional well-being. We provide family therapy, assessment services, parent support groups, trainings for mental health professionals, and coordinate with schools, other service agencies, and professionals.

Name: Project Angel Food
Description: Project Angel Food provides free meals and nutrition education for individuals affected by life-threatening illnesses throughout Los Angeles County who are too sick to shop or cook for themselves.

Name: Project Caring and Sharing
Description: Project Caring and Sharing serves at-risk families throughout the Pomona Valley Basin by providing food, clothing and personal hygiene items, health fairs, and back-to-school supplies.

Name: Project Commotion
Description: Project Commotion is a community organization that hosts programs for children and adults focusing on learning through movement and play.

Name: Project Homeless Connect
Description: Project Homeless Connect helps San Franciscans experiencing homelessness get access to important health care through our Vision program, Dental program & Hearing Aid program. Services also include support with identifications services, hygiene care, and connecting individuals to other community resources. These services are provided through a Community Day of Service as well as in office during onsite drop-in hours and off-sites.

Name: Project Inform
Description: Project Inform provides up-to-date, life-saving information to help people living with HIV and Hep C make the best choices regarding their treatment and care.

Name: Project Legal Link
Description: Project Legal Link hosts an online database of free and low-cost legal resources in the Bay Area. They also provide legal clinics at select organization sites.

Name: Project Level
Description: Project Level teaches youth about the music industry including pre-production, production, post-production, and marketing.

Name: Project New Hope
Description: Project New Hope provides safe affordable housing and supportive services to individuals or families with disabilities (such as HIV/AIDS) and Seniors, living in Southern California.

Name: Project Ninety (Project 90)
Description: Project Ninety provides comprehensive alcohol and drug recovery services in San Mateo county.

Name: Project Open Hand
Description: Project Open Hand is a nonprofit organization that provides warm nutritious meals and groceries to seniors and adults with disabilities, as well as people living with critical illnesses.

Name: Project Outlet
Description: Project Outlet offers support groups and other services to LGBTQ+ youth living on the Peninsula and South Bay.

Name: Project Peacemakers
Description: The Mission of Project: PeaceMakers, Incorporated (PPMI) is to interact with all aspects of the community in an endeavor to enhance the quality of life by addressing Domestic Family/Intimate Partner Violence (DF/IPV). Through education, intervention, and prevention we are able to teach and apply a coordinated approach in helping break the cycle of violence in our homes and our communities.

Name: Project Read North San Mateo
Description: Project Read North San Mateo helps low literacy adults improve their reading and financial literacy skills.

Name: Project Read Redwood City
Description: Project Read Redwood City provides hope through literacy. They offer tutoring programs to help adults, youth and families with reading, writing, and thinking skills. They offer an adult literacy program, one-on-one tutoring, a kids program, and teen training.

Name: Project Read San Mateo Public Library
Description: Project Read, the adult literacy program of the San Mateo Public Library, offers free, confidential, literacy tutoring.

Name: Project REAL
Description: Project REAL (Richmond Effort to Abate Lead) is a program of the City of Richmond that makes homes and apartments "lead-safe" for children and families and educates the community about the dangers of lead.

Name: Project Renewal
Description: Project Renewal is a New York City nonprofit organization that helps homeless men and women who often have a drug addiction, mental illnessness and involvement with the criminal justice system by providing healthcare, housing and employment services.

Name: Project Renewal's Marsha's House
Description: Project Renewal’s mission is to end the cycle of homelessness by empowering individuals and families to renew their lives with health, homes, and jobs.

Name: Project Return Peer Support Network
Description: Project Return Peer Support Network (PRPSN) provides support groups and a Warmline, respite house, resource centers, and career and employment support for people who have experienced mental illness.

Name: Project Safe Haven Hotline
Description: Project Safe Haven helps domestic violence  survivors who are not safe in their homes find housing in order to heed the County Health Order to stay inside and be protected from the spread of Coronavirus.

Name: Project Sentinel
Description: Project Sentinel assists individuals with housing problems including discrimination, mortgage foreclosure & delinquency, rental issues, home buyer education, post-purchase education, and reverse mortgages.

Name: Project Sister Family Services
Description: Project Sister is a sexual assault crisis service dedicated to reducing the incidence and trauma of sexual assault in the West San Gabriel and Pomona Valleys. They provide support groups, individual counseling, and self-defense classes, and sexual assault outreach.

Name: Project WeHOPE
Description: Project WeHOPE provides shelter, meals and housing search help to individuals and families who are homeless.

Name: Project Wreckless
Description: Project Wreckless is a capacity development program targeting youth in our community who are more likely to drop out of school, abuse substances, and/or engage in criminal activity.  Project Wreckless provides tools for life through an immersive curriculum centered around the restoration of cars. We don't just provide tools and support. We expect more of our youth so they gain the confidence to expect more of themselves.

Name: Prospera
Description: Prospera provides assistance to cooperative business owners through training programs.

Name: Prototypes
Description: Prototypes offer affordable substance use treatment to women.

Name: Proud Ukraine
Description: Proud Ukraine is an association of Ukrainian LGBT+ individuals  seeking to foster a vibrant LGBT+ community in the United States and Canada.

Name: Providence Community Services
Description: Providence Community Services has provided specialty mental health services to children, youth and their families living in South East Los Angeles County (SPA 7)  since 1998. Providence Community Services was formerly known as Aspen Community Services.

Name: Providence Foundation of San Francisco
Description: The Providence Foundation of San Francisco is a non-profit in the Bayview Hunters Point area that offers community services including housing, nutrition, case management, and more.

Name: Providence Health and Services
Description: Providence Health and Services provides health services in the South Bay, Westside, and the Greater San Fernando Valley areas.

Name: Providence Saint John's Health Center
Description: Providence Saint John's Health Center operates a hospital with physicians, nurses, volunteers, and support staff to provide services including heart and vascular care, oncology, orthopedics, and women's health. It also operates the John Wayne Cancer Institute.

Name: Providence Saint Joseph Medical Center
Description: Providence Saint Joseph Medical Center provides health services.

Name: Providence TrinityCare Hospice
Description: Supports patients in need of hospice and palliative care for people of all ages including emergency help in paying bills, support groups and facility-based or in-home hospice and palliative care.

Name: Psychology Today
Description: Psychology Today provides information about mental health and a directory to find psychologists, therapists, support groups, and treatment centers throughout the United States and Canada.

Name: PTA of Brooklyn School of International Studies
Description: The PTA supports the programs that make our school so special: music, dance, multimediia, photography  and chess to name a few. In many cases the money we raise is the only funding these programs receive.  Our PTA also funds a number of critical educational components, including professional development for teachers and staff, and many of the school’s supplies. We also raise money for every single classroom and specialist so our teachers and therapists can deliver the very best to our children.

Name: Public Counsel
Description: Public Counsel offers free legal advice and representation.

Name: Public Glass
Description: Public Glass is a non-profit organization committed to glass, art and education. It is San Francisco's only non-profit public-access glass studio and school.

Name: Public Health Foundation Enterprise WIC Program
Description: The Public Health Foundation Enterprise (PHFE) Women, Infants & Children (WIC) program serves pregnant, breastfeeding and postpartum women, infants and children up to 5 years old.  WIC also serves women who have recently lost a pregnancy.  WIC provides free supplemental foods, nutrition education, breastfeeding support and other services.

Name: Public Health Management Corporation - Health Connection
Description: PHMC Health Connection is a nurse-managed, health care facility that provides a variety of services to children, teens and adults in the community.

Name: Public Health Management Corporation - Rising Sun
Public Media Group of Southern California
Description: Public Media Group of Southern California is a non-profit broadcasting organization operating two TV stations and a non-commercial satellite television channel.

Name: PUEBLO - People United for a Better Life in Oakland
Description: PUEBLO advocates for the needs of low-income residents of Oakland, through grassroots organizing,  leadership trainings and policy reform.

Name: Puente
Description: Puente offers services to individuals and families of San Mateo County South Coast community including healthcare, education programs, financial support, nutrition programs and more.

Name: Puente Learning Center
Description: Puente Leaning Center offers education and job training to students of all ages.

Name: Puertas Abiertas Family Resource Center
Description: Puertas Abiertas Family Resource Center strives to strengthen Latino families in Napa Valley through providing resources such as life skills training, immigration law and assistance, as well as ESL courses.

Name: Pukuu Cultural Community Services
Description: Pukuu Cultural Community Services provides a variety of services for Native American and indigenous people.

Name: Purpose Church
Description: Purpose Church is a faith-based organization that provides various missions to assist and help those in need throughout the community. They offer clothing, homeless services, and food.

Name: Pursuit
Description: Pursuit offers a 12 month intensive training program for youth interested in a tech job.

Name: Pursuit of Excellence Foundation
Description: The pursuit of Excellence Foundation provides scholarships for low-income hard-working students.

Name: Putnam Clubhouse
Description: Putnam Clubhouse is a community for adults recovering from mental illness. Members can participate in health and wellness activities, expressive arts programming and gain access to education resources and paid employment opportunities.

Name: PVJOBS
Description: PVJOBS helps at-risk and disadvantaged youth, adults and veterans get training and jobs in the construction industry.

Name: Q Center
Description: Q Center is Portland's LGBTQ Community Center. It is the largest LGBTQ community center in the Pacific Northwest. Q Center proudly serves the LGBTQ2SIA+ communities of Portland Metro and Southwest Washington. Q Center provides community-based support for LGBTQ2SIA+ community members seeking connection and resources. Their drop-in and event space on North Mississippi Avenue is a frequent first stop for new arrivals in Portland, and for longtime residents who are newly out or questioning their sexual or gender identity. Q Center also serves as an information hub for friends, partners, community, and family members of LGBTQ2SIA+ individuals.

Name: Qmunity
Description: Qmunity empowers queer, trans, and Two-Spirit individuals to be their best selves through free counseling, referrals, peer support, and gender-affirming chest wear.

Name: Queen of the Valley Hospital
Description: Queen of the Valley hospital provides quality and affordable medical and therapeutic care for Napa Valley residents.

Name: Queen of the Valley Medical Center
Description: St. Joseph Health's Queen of the Valley Medical Center helps provide case management care to individuals battling chronic diseases, including referrals to care, health education and other affordable health care services .

Name: Queens Community House
Description: Queens Community House (QCH) is a multi-site, multi-service settlement house that serves the diverse neighborhoods of Queens. QCH serves residents of all ages, races, faiths and ethnicities by offering services including healthcare, education, housing, nutrition, senior services, legal, homeless support and more.

Name: Queens Satellite High School for Opportunity
Description: Queen Satellite High School for Opportunity offers various programs and internship opportunities for students. It is one of the few transfer schools that accept 15 year old students. Graduation rate is at 40%, students aged 15-21 can apply for enrollment.

Name: QueensCare Health Centers
Description: QueensCare Health Centers provides primary, preventive and acute care to all individuals including adult and pediatric medical, dental, and vision care.

Name: Queer Asylum Accompaniment Team
Description: The Queer Asylum Accompaniment (QAA) team has made a long-term commitment to fulfill the essential needs of LGBT asylum seekers and their sponsors. They will assist the asylum seeker in acquiring housing, food, legal support and connecting them to local social services while they go through the legal asylum process. The QAA team will honor asylum seekers and their quest for comfort and safety with warmth, acceptance and respect.

Name: Queer Detainee Empowerment Project (QDEP)
Description: The Queer Detainee Empowerment Project assists individuals coming out of immigration detention in securing structural, health/wellness, educational, legal, and emotional support and services. They serve LGBTQ and HIV+ immigrant detainees in the United States.

Name: Queer Healing Oasis
Description: Queer Healing Oasis has served as a medium for healing circles, trainings, and workshops to provide affordable mental health services to Queer, Trans, and gender non-conforming people from a trauma-informed lens.

Name: Queer LifeSpace
Description: Queer LifeSpace provides LGBTQ-focused mental health services in individual, couples and group settings and for people of all ages.

Name: Queer Yukon
Description: Queer Yukon organizes events and support groups for LGBTQ+ people in the Yukon territory to get together, help each other, and have fun.

Name: Quest Bridge
Description: QuestBridge provides high-achieving low-income youth with opportunities at prestigious universities.

Name: R-Transit/Paratransit
Description: R-Transit provides safe transportation for seniors and people with disabilities.

Name: Rafiki Coalition
Description: Rafiki Coalition provides health and wellness services including transitional housing, health education, advocacy, health case management and other health-promoting activities for San Francisco’s Black and marginalized communities.

Name: Rahima Foundation
Description: The Rahima Foundation provides financial, educational, emotional, social, and spiritual resources to communities in need.

Name: RAICES
Description: RAICES is a nonprofit agency that provides free and low-cost legal services to underserved immigrant children, families, and refugees in Texas. Description: The School of Cooperative Technical Education is a half-day vocational program that offers high school students hands on training in a variety of trade areas.

Name: School of Imagination
Description: School of Imagination is an inclusion school offering preschool, kindergarten and infant development classes to children both with and without developmental disabilities.

Name: School of Music and Dance
Description: The School of Music and Dance at San José State University prepares students for professional careers in teaching, performance, choreography, composition, research, and related fields with bachelor, master degree programs and other professional studies. They produce over 20 ensembles and 120 performances each year.

Name: School of Unity and Liberation (SOUL)
Description: SOUL supports social change and justice by teaching organizing skills to youth and leaders of grassroots organizations.

Name: School on Wheels
Description: School on Wheels provides academic tutoring to children living in shelters, motels, cars, group foster homes and on the streets in Southern California.

Name: Schurig Center for Brain Injury Recovery
Description: The Schurig Center for Brain Injury Recovery raises awareness about the causes and effects of brain injuries and provides rehabilitative and supportive services to help survivors and their families rebuild their lives after an injury.

Name: Schurr Adult School
Description: Provides individualized study program for adults to receive their high school diploma.

Name: SCO Family of Service's Brooklyn Drop-In Center
Description: Located in Cypress Hills, the Brooklyn Drop-In Center (BDIC) provides a wide array of services to run away and homeless youth throughout the borough of Brooklyn. BDIC staff provide crisis intervention, counseling and mediation as well as services to help youth pursue educational and career goals and develop independent living skills. They treat all youth and their families with dignity, respect, privacy, and utmost confidentiality. All services are free. No appointment necessary.

Name: SCO Family of Services - Center for Family Life
Description: Center for Family Life, a program of SCO Family of Services, is a neighborhood-based family and social services organization serving the community in Sunset Park, Brooklyn.

Name: Scotts Valley Band of Pomo Indians Tribal TANF
Description: Scotts Valley Band of Pomo Indians Tribal TANF provides Contra Costa Native American families with services and benefits. They offer job preparation, life skills, CPR, nutrition, and parenting classes.

Name: SCRAP
Description: SCRAP collects quality re-usable materials such as textiles, buttons, paper, craft and, office supplies, plastics, and wood and makes them available for free or low-cost to teachers, students, artists, and organizations in San Francisco's Bayview District.  SCRAP also hosts arts and crafts workshops.

Name: SCV Pregnancy Center
Description: SCV Pregnancy Center is a faith-based medical provider for those facing an unplanned pregnancy and sexual health decisions. Services include patient education about sexual health, pregnancy testing, prenatal care referrals, HIV screening and STD testing and treatment for men and women, and referrals for adoptions and community resources.

Name: SDS Hope House
Description: SDS Hope House provides safe housing for women survivors of human trafficking and commercial sex work.

Name: Search to Involve Pilipino Americans (SIPA)
Description: The Search to Involve Pilipino Americans (SIPA) provides services to Filipino Americans in Los Angeles. Programs include case management, counseling, afterschool and senior programs, small business development, cultural enrichment, and affordable housing.

Name: Seattle Area Support Group & Community Center
Description: SASG promotes well-being through peer support, providing a variety of groups catered towards health & wellness, recovery, social and support. SASG services are geared specifically for the LGBTQ community and include all allies. The only requirement for participation in programming is acceptance of others.

Name: Seattle Counseling Service (SCS)
Description: Seattle Counseling Service (SCS) is a community based organization dedicated to promoting health and wellness within the LGBTQ community. They provide crisis counseling on issues related to: youth, sexual orientation, ‘coming out,’ HIV/AIDS and gender identification. Practical skills assistance places emphasis on job-finding, ‘coming out,’ making productive decisions and utilizing community resources for tangible needs (food, shelter, etc.). The SCS Immigrant, Refugee, and Undocumented Outreach (IRUO) Program helps new LGBTQ Americans find housing, learn English, traverse the city, obtain jobs, receive essential supplies, develop a documentation safety plan and become self-sufficient.

Name: Seattle Frontrunners
Description: Seattle Frontrunners is a gay, lesbian, bisexual, and transgender running and walking club in Seattle. Seattle Frontrunners provides a safe space for LGBTQ individuals interested in running and sport from all over the world.

Name: Sebastopol Community Cultural Center
Description: Sebastopol Community Cultural Center offers a program to help youth prepare for jobs.

Name: Sebastopol Senior Center
Description: Sebastopol Senior Center offers special events, classes, weekly activities, and a variety of services to senior members of the community ages 55 and up.

Name: Second Chance at Loving Life
Description: Second Chance at Loving Life works with individuals post-incarceration for finding and maintaining employment.

Name: Second Harvest Food Bank of San Joaquin County
Description: We help you get connected with food pantries, screen for calFresh, and learn about emergency food services.

Name: Second Harvest Food Bank of Santa Clara and San Mateo Counties
Description: Second Harvest Food Bank of Santa Clara and San Mateo Counties is a food bank that provides weekly and monthly food distribution, home-delivered meals, meals for children to bring home, a food connection hotline, and nutrition education workshops. They are located in Silicon Valley.

Name: Second Harvest of Silicon Valley
Description: Harvest of Silicon Valley is one of the largest food banks in the nation. We provide food to more than a quarter of a million people in Santa Clara and San Mateo counties every month.

Name: Second Nature Behavioral Health
Description: Counseling and mental health services within the Bay Area.

Name: SEE-LA (Sustainable Economic Enterprises of Los Angeles)

Name: SEEDS Community Resolution Center
Description: SEEDS Community Resolution Center is a nonprofit community-based organization that provides mediation, facilitation, training and restorative justice to residents and organizations in the Bay Area.

Name: Self-Help And Recovery Exchange (SHARE!)
Description: Self-Help And Recovery Exchange (SHARE!) provides self-help support groups to address issues such as anger management, health, depression, self-esteem, relationships, childhood abuse, substance abuse, reaching goals, and more.

Name: Self-Help for the Elderly
Description: Self-Help for the Elderly provides meals, health care, employment, training, and social activities for seniors in San Francisco, San Mateo, Santa Clara, and Alameda counties. They also offer housing assistance, nutrition, and cleaning services.

Name: SelfHelp
Description: Selfhelp Community Services is licensed and certified through the New York State Department of Health to offer home care services. Its not-for-profit home care program employs over 1,500 home health aides some of whom are graduates of Selfhelp's home health aide training program.

Name: Selton medical Center
Description: Seton Medical Center has been serving the health care needs of San Francisco and northern San Mateo County since its founding as Mary’s Help Hospital in 1893.

Name: Selton Medical Center Coastside
Description: We believe caring is powerful medicine. We take pride in operating the only 24-hour standby Emergency Department from Daly City to Santa Cruz, which is well-equipped and staffed to serve the needs of the community.  Our key medical services include physical, occupational and speech therapies, radiologyy and laboratory. At Seton Coastside, we collaborate with our professional staff and community partners to shape the future of quality healthcare on the coast side.

Name: Seneca Family of Agencies
Description: Seneca Family of Agencies is a leading innovator in the field of education, community-based, and family-focused treatment services for children and families.

Name: Senior Access

Name: Senior and Disability Action Housing Collaborative
Description: Senior and Disability Action Housing Collaborative offers services and support to seniors and people with disabilities so they can live well and safely.

Description: Senior Center Without Walls offers activities, friendly conversation, classes, and support groups to home-bound elders and others who find it difficult to go to a community senior center. Participants call from the comfort of home through telephone conference calls. No special equipment is needed and the calls are completely free.

Name: Senior Coastsiders
Description: Senior Coastsiders provides opportunities, support, and resources for older adults and adults with disabilities living on the coastside, from Montara to Pescadero and Skyline to the Sea.

Name: Senior Support Program of the Tri-Valley
Description: Senior Support Program of the Tri-Valley (SSPTV) is an independent, nonprofit agency serving seniors over the age of 60 in the cities of Pleasanton, Livermore, Dublin, and Sunol. Their aim is to improve the quality of life for local seniors by offering health services, case management, wellness programs and more.

Name: Seniors At Home
Description: Seniors At Home offers a range of services to help older adults live more independently in their own homes.

Name: SEO Scholars

Name: Sequoia District Adult School

Name: Serenity Recuperative Care Facility

Services include but are not limited to: self-advocacy training, assistive technology, housing information, independent living skills training, peer counseling, benefits planning and information & referral services.

Name: Services for Brain Injury

Expert psychologists, therapists, life skills instructors and job coaches help patients recover and regain independence through independent living skills, clinical therapies and employment services.

Name: Services, Immigrant Rights and Education Network (SIREN)
