Description: The Children’s Clinic (TCC) provides primary healthcare services for children, adolescents, and adults.

Name: The Children's Collective, Inc (TCCI)
Description: The Children's Collective, Inc - Willowbrook helps to improve life outcomes for children, youth, and their families in South Los Angeles by providing educational and support services.

Name: The Children's Dental Center
Description: The clinic provides dental services to youth who have no health insurance, and their caregivers, in Los Angeles County.

Name: The Church of Hope
Description: The Church of Hope operates the only full-time food pantry in Santa Clarita.

Name: The Church on the Way
Description: The Church on the Way offers a weekly food pantry.

Name: The City of Novato
Description: The City of Novato provides public services to its residents.

Name: THE CO-OCCURRING DISORDER PROGRAM
Description: The mission of Alo House Recovery Centers is to use ‘connection, not control’ to help our clients achieve autonomy, empowerment, and a sense of community.

Name: The COLOURS Organization
Description: The COLOURS Organization has been providing community building and health and wellness services to the Black LGBT community in Philadelphia since 1991.

Name: The Cornell Law School Advocacy for LGBT Communities Clinic
Description: The Cornell Law School Advocacy for LGBT Communities Clinic provides free legal assistance to low-income LGBT people in Tompkins County and the surrounding area. The LGBT clinic is dedicated to achieving equal rights for LGBT people, and represents diverse members of the LGBT community in a range of civil legal matters. Note: due to limited resources, the clinic can only take on new cases at certain times during the year. If the clinic's intake is closed or they are unable to assist a new client, they will refer them to another organization that may be able to help.

Name: The Crucible
Description: The Crucible is an arts education organization that provides training in the fine and industrial arts. Along with art classes, we host art installations and performances.

Name: The Custody Project
Description: The Custody Project assists mothers with essential needs due to the loss of funds from defending a custody or visitation of their children.

Name: The Detained Immigrant Solidarity Committee (DMSC)
Description: The Detained Immigrant Solidarity Committee (DMSC) seeks to end detention and border militarization. DMSC stays in contact with detained migrants and their families through phone calls and visitation to better support their needs. They are the creadorxs of the Fronterizo Fianza Fund.

Name: The Dignity Project
Description: The Dignity Project provides refurbished computers, low-cost computer repairs and support plus low-cost autos to the community. It also offers hands-on automotive and computer training to youth.

Name: The Door
Description: The Door’s mission is to empower young people to reach their potential by providing comprehensive youth development services in a diverse and caring environment. The Door provides a wide range of services to meet the needs of New York City youth aged 12-24. The Door’s members are diverse – black, Asian, Latino, gay, straight, immigrant, in foster care, out-of-school or out-of-work. In addition to health, legal, education, counseling and career services, The Door provides a wide range of programs and services geared towards Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, or Questioning (LGBTQ) members.

Name: The Door
Description: The Door offers services to youth including health care, legal, employmnet, arts, sports and nutrition.

Name: The Episcopal Church of St Andrew and St. Charles
Description: The Episcopal Church of St Andrew and St. Charles is a faith based organization that offers services to the community in Granada Hills, CA.

Name: The Exodus Foundation for Recovery
Description: The Exodus Foundation for Recovery provides behavioral health services to vulnerable individuals with mental illness, substance use disorders, and chronic physical health issues. It assists individuals with limited resources with subsidized housing and treatment services.

Name: The Fairfield Church of Christ
Description: The Fairfield Church of Christ provides religious and community services.

Name: The Family Link
Description: The Family Link provides low-cost temporary lodging for those who have traveled to San Francisco to visit an individual with a life threatening illness.

Name: The Family School
Description: The Family School has helped thousands of San Francisco families achieve self-sufficiency through family support, education, employment training, and job placement.

Name: The First Tee of Contra Costa
Description: The First Tee of Contra Costa is a youth development program that uses golf to teach students life skills in a classroom setting and on the golf course.

Name: The First Tee of San Francisco
Description: The First Tee of San Francisco is a youth development program that uses the sport of golf to teach students life skills in a classroom setting and on the golf course.

Name: The First Unitarian Congregational Society in Brooklyn's Queer Caucus
Description: The First Unitarian Congregational Society in Brooklyn is a joyful, caring, religious community that inspires and empowers people to grow spiritually, care for one another, and work for social justice and stewardship of the earth. The Queer Caucus is a community of LGBTQIA members and friends at the First Unitarian Congregational Society in Brooklyn.

Name: The Florence Immigrant and Refugee Rights Project
Description: The Florence Immigrant and Refugee Rights Project provides free legal and social services to detained adults and unaccompanied children facing immigration removal proceedings in Arizona.

Name: The Fronterizo Fianza Fund
Description: The Fronterizo Fianza Fund is a community bond (fianza) fund based in El Paso and serving Far West Texas and New Mexico. While people remain detained simply because they can't pay for their freedom, the Fund will work with them and their families to pay bonds, support people inside, and navigate the long and confusing road to freedom.

Name: The Gathering Place
Description: The Gathering Place is a non-profit center for those experiencing loss and grief after the death of a loved one.

Name: The Gay and Lesbian Latin AIDS Education Initiative (Galaei)
Description: GALAEI is a queer latin@ social justice organization providing HIV prevention services; social, economic, and medical support for transgender individuals; and grassroots organized action.

Name: The GBLT National Help Center
Description: The Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual and Transgender (GLBT) National Help Center provides vital peer-support, community connections and resource information to people with questions regarding sexual orientation and/or gender identity

Name: The Gender Pathways Clinic at Kaiser Permanente San Francisco Medical Center
Description: The Gender Pathways Clinic at Kaiser Permanente San Francisco Medical Center provides mental health therapy along with access to gender affirming surgery and hormone therapy. Along with hormone therapy is general education regarding gender affirming care post surgery and guidance to hormones recommended.

Name: The Grantsmanship Center
Description: The Grantsmanship Center provides training and publications on best practices to secure grant funding for nonprofit, academic and government agencies in Los Angeles County and across with U.S. Some services are free, others require a fee. Topics include how to secure and manage grants and how to create earned income to supplement grant funding. The Center also offers its own publications.

Name: The Greater Portland Immigrant Welcome Center
Description: The Greater Portland Immigrant Welcome Center serves as a hub of collaboration that strengthens the immigrant community through language acquisition, economic integration and civic engagement.

Name: The Gubbio Project
Description: The Gubbio Project offers a space for rest and recovery for individuals who are homeless in Catholic churches located in the Tenderloin and the Mission. The Project also offers food, blankets, socks, hygiene kits, referrals to resources, foot care, massage services, and listening services.

Name: The Guidance Center
Description: The Guidance Center provides mental health treatment to children and their families living with mental illness and abuse in Long Beach, Compton, San Pedro, and Avalon.

Name: The Harmony Project
Description: The Harmony Project provides a youth program for children and teens to learn life skills, prepare for college, and learn music through a music program.

Name: The Hayward Center Adult School
Description: The Hayward Center Adult School is part of the Hayward Unified School District providing classes for students to complete their high school diploma, get a career or technical training, and learn English as a second language.

Name: The Healing Well
Description: The Healing Well offers supportive services to individuals and families in San Francisco's Tenderloin neighborhood.

Name: The Help Group
Description: The Help Group provides education services in the Los Angeles area for children, adolescents and young adults with special needs related to autism spectrum disorder, learning disabilities, ADHD, developmental delays, abuse and other challenges that prevent them from attending a public school.

Name: The Homeless Church
Description: The Homeless Church is a faith-based organization that provides religious services and meals to the homeless.

Name: The House of Acts, Inc.
Description: The House of Acts, Inc. offers substance abuse treatment programs in a transitional housing setting for men, women and youth. It is licensed and certified by the California State Department of Alcohol and Drug Programs.

Name: The Human Rights Initiative at The University at Buffalo
Description: The Human Rights Initiative was founded in July 2014 to meet the growing needs of the asylum seeker population in western New York. They are a medical student-run asylum clinic that collaborates with licensed healthcare professionals in their area to provide forensic evaluations for survivors of torture seeking asylum in the United States. To date, they have served over 80 clients from over 30 countries, including multiple from the Democratic Republic of Congo, El Salvador, Rwanda, Afghanistan, and Angola. Their services have now been used by multiple applicants who have successfully received asylum in the United States.

Name: The Hume Center
Description: The Hume Center provides high quality, culturally sensitive, and comprehensive behavioral health care services and training.

Name: The Jamestown Community Center
Description: The Jamestown Community Center provides free or low-cost services for San Francisco's children and youth ages 4-18 and their families.  Services include after school and summer educational enrichment, tutoring and homework help, youth leadership development, competitive and recreational sports, youth employment, college and career counseling, and counseling and prevention programs.

Name: The Jennifer Diamond Foundation
Description: The Jennifer Diamond Foundation provides support for individuals diagnosed with cancer.

Name: The Jewish Federation of Greater Seattle
Description: The Jewish Federation of Greater Seattle leads a strong Jewish Puget Sound by serving as a community voice, strengthening connections to Israel and World Jewry, and making investments in Jewish life, for today and the next generation.

Name: The John Stewart Company
Description: The John Stewart Company provides affordable and market rate housing, special needs housing, senior housing, and common interests development throughout the State of California.

Name: The Journey @ Mayfair Community Church
Description: The Journey @ Mayfair Community Church is a faith-based organization that provides religious and community services.

Name: The Karsh Center
Description: The Karsh Center provides social services to all members of the Los Angeles community. Services include legal aid, counseling, grief groups, English (ESL) classes, citizenship classes, food pantry, dental care, vision care, books for children, and daily needs such as loans, toiletries, clothing vouchers, and baby supplies. All of their services are free or at a low cost.

Name: The Knowledge House
Description: The Knowledge House offers free technology and workplace skills needed to build a successful career in the tech industry.

Name: The Lab Learning Space
Description: The Lab provides a personalized learning experience for participating students in Long Beach grades 1st-8th, and provide support to homeschooling families in the region.

Name: The Lantern (la Linterna) Center for Hospitality and Education
Description: The Lantern (la Linterna) Center for Hospitality and Education offers hospitality for men and women from the immigrant community, 5 levels of ESL instruction, a computer lab, and preparation classes for U.S. citizenship.

Name: The Latino Commission (TLC)
Description: The Latino Commission (TLC) operates licensed facilities in San Mateo County that provide residential and outpatient substance abuse treatment for men, women and young women with children plus transitional sober living environment for both men and women.

Name: The Leeway Foundation
Description: The Leeway Foundation supports women and trans artists and cultural producers working in communities at the intersection of art, culture, and social change.

Name: The Legal Aid Society
Description: The Legal Aid Society exists to ensure that no New Yorker is denied the right to equal justice because of poverty. For over 140 years, they have protected, defended, and advocated for those that have struggled in silence for far too long – working on the front lines and behind the scenes to offer their clients the legal services they deserve. Through their Civil, Criminal Defense, and Juvenile Rights Practices, they offer legal expertise to vulnerable New Yorkers in over 300,000 legal matters each and every year.

Name: The Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual & Transgender Community Center
Description: New York City’s Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual & Transgender Community Center, known as "The Center", fosters a welcoming environment where everyone is celebrated for who they are. The Center offers the LGBT communities of NYC health and wellness programs; arts, entertainment, and cultural events; recovery, wellness, parenthood, and family support services.

Name: The LGBT Asylum Project
Description: The LGBT Asylum Project is a San Francisco Bay Area non-profit organization exclusively dedicated to providing high quality legal representation for LGBTQ+ immigrants who are fleeing persecution and seeking asylum in the United States. The LGBT Asylum Project provides support to immigrants in the San Francisco Asylum Office jurisdiction (from Bakersfield, CA to Seattle, WA), identify as LGBTQ+, and have been persecuted or have fears of future persecution if they return to their home country.

Name: The LGBT Center OC
Description: The LGBT Center OC offers services to the community including mental health, HIV testing, the David Bohnett CyberCenter, educational services and more.

Name: The LGBTQ Center
Description: The LGBTQ Center offers support groups and a resource guide of affirming and accepting vendors, businesses, and social services.

Name: The Libertas Center for Human Rights
Description: The Libertas Center for Human Rights provides medical and mental health care (individual therapy, group therapy and medication management), psycho-social support, psychological and medical forensic evaluations, care-coordination and intensive social and legal case management to survivors of torture who were persecuted at the hands of an authority figure outside of the United States.

Name: The Literacy and Language Center
Description: The Literacy and Language Center is an educational center that develops methods to address difficulties in reading, spelling, writing, verbal expression, comprehension, critical thinking, and study skills in clients from age 5 to adult. Specialists at the center have experience with various literary and language conditions, such as learning differences, learning disabilities, dyslexia, and an autism spectrum disorder.

Name: The Living Room
Description: The Living Room is a drop-in center in Sonoma County specifically serving homeless and at-risk women and their children.

Name: The Lord's Church
Description: The Lord's Church provides religious and community services.

Name: The Los Angeles County + University of Southern California Medical Center
Description: The Los Angeles County + University of Southern California Medical Center is one of the largest public hospitals in the country. The medical center offers specialized inpatient care units, unique outpatient clinics including an HIV/AIDS clinic, a violence intervention program for domestic violence and sexual assault survivors and a clinic for children at risk for or in foster care. Outpatient primary care is available as well.

Name: The Los Angeles County Development Authority (formerly Housing Authority of the County of Los Angeles)
Description: The Los Angles County Development Authority (formerly Housing Authority of the County of Los Angeles) runs both the Section 8 Housing and Public Housing programs.

Name: The Lundquist Institute's Summer Fellowship Program
Description: The Lundquist Institute's Summer Fellowship Program is designed to encourage graduating high school seniors and high school juniors to explore careers in the field of biomedical science.

Name: The Maple Counseling Center
Description: We offer low-cost, high-quality mental health counseling.

Name: The Marine Mammal Center
Description: The Marine Mammal Center is a nonprofit veterinary research hospital and educational center dedicated to the rescue and rehabilitation of ill and injured marine mammals – primarily elephant seals, harbor seals, and California sea lions.

Name: The Marks JCH's LGBT Refugee Center
Description: The Marks JCH provides assistance to lesbian and gay Russian-speakers – individuals and families who are fleeing Russia and Ukraine following a growing wave of discrimination and violence aimed at the LGBT community. The Marks JCH offers comprehensive support and serves as a hub for LGBT Russian-speakers. Their experienced staff focuses on the provision of concrete services to refugees and asylum seekers. Case management will enable each client to be assessed for and receive numerous services. In cases where appropriate, emergency cash assistance is provided.

Name: The Marsh
Description: The Marsh provides arts performances, workshops, and internship programs in theater.

Name: The Mazzoni Center
Description: The Mazzoni Center provides health and wellness services, counseling and legal services to the LGBTQ communities.

Name: The Mental Health Association of San Mateo County
Description: The Mental Health Association of San Mateo County provides shelter, life skills training, and social activities for individuals with HIV or mental illness.

Name: The Mentoring Center
Description: The Mentoring Center supports youth to grow into healthy adults and become productive citizens with the ability to transform themselves and the communities where they live.

Name: The Midnight Mission
Description: The Midnight Mission provides individuals and families who are homeless with food, shelter, and many other resources to live a self-sufficient life.

Name: The Mission Continues
Description: The Mission Continues is a nonprofit that provides opportunities for veterans to grow and develop professionally while giving back to the community.

Name: The Mosaic Project
Description: The Mosaic Project aims to teach peace and understanding to children in the Bay Area. Programs include an outdoor program, leadership projects, volunteer opportunities, and educational skills that reinforce empathy, community, individuality, open mindedness and mutual respect.

Name: The Mount Sinai Center for Transgender Medicine and Surgery
Description: The Mount Sinai Center for Transgender Medicine and Surgery (CTMS) takes a comprehensive multidisciplinary approach to caring for trans and gender non-binary people. All CTMS patients have access to their broad team of professionals to ensure optimal health care, including primary care, hormone therapy, surgical care, gynecology, urology, social work, and mental health support.

Name: The Mouton Center
Description: The Barbara A. Mouton Multicultural Wellness Center (The Mouton Center) is a new mental health facility and programmatic initiative resource for East Palo Alto (EPA) residents. Opened in June of 2009 by One East Palo Alto (OEPA), The Mouton Center is a place where consumers of mental health services and their family members can go to receive support, information, and be in community with each other.

Name: The Napa Storehouse
Description: The Napa Storehouse provides free food for needy families.

Name: The Ness Counseling Center
Description: The Ness Counseling Center offers low-fee services including therapy for individuals, couples and families, mental health assessments, monitored visitations, drug and alcohol counseling, domestic violence treatment, anger management, parenting, sexual addiction, drug testing plus livescan fingerprinting in the greater Los Angeles area.

Name: The New Friends Homeless Center
Description: New Friends Homeless Center provides weekly hot meals, clothing, and hygiene kits to individuals experiencing homelessness, senior citizens, disabled individuals, low-income individuals, and others in need.

Name: The Northwest Network of Survivors
Description: The Northwest (NW) Network of Survivors increases communities’ ability to support the self-determination and safety of bisexual, transgender, lesbian and gay survivors of abuse through education, organizing and advocacy. They work within a broad liberation movement dedicated to social and economic justice, equality and respect for all people and the creation of loving, inclusive and accountable communities.

Name: The Obama Foundation
Description: The Obama Foundation provides a community center in South Side Chicago and a national fellowship program for young people to receive professional development and connections in the sector of their passion.

Name: The Okra Project
Description: Collective focused on addressing the struggles faced by Black Trans People. They provide home-cooked, healthy, and culturally specific meals in addition to other resources.

Name: The One Inc.
Description: The One, Inc. seeks to build relationships with members of the homeless community so that they may then identify barriers to obtaining income and housing, and help their friends move beyond their homelessness.

Name: The Orinda Association
Description: The Orinda Association provides community programs, publishes a newspaper, and delivers transportation services to residents of Orinda.

Name: The OUTreach Center
Description: The OUTreach Center provides quality support services, events, and professional resources for the development and well-being of Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, and Transgender people, their friends, and families living in the Antelope Valley.

Name: The Pacific Center
Description: The Pacific Center for Human Growth (Pacific Center) fosters and enhances the well-being and self-respect of diverse Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, and Queer youth, seniors, adults, and families through the delivery of LGBTQ-proficient mental health and wellness services, and through the training of a strong and inclusive community of LGBTQ-proficient mental health care professionals.

Name: The Parish of St. Mary in Palms (Episcopal) Church
Description: Founded in 1919, we are a parish of the Episcopal Diocese of Los Angeles within The Episcopal Church, offering a ministry of compassion, love, mercy and justice. We are a sacramental church offering on a daily basis the sacraments of the church especially daily Eucharistic service at 9 am to all who need spiritual nourishment. Our facilities are in constant use Monday to Friday by our partners in ministry: The Try God Group of AA (since mid 1970s); the So Cal D A. (since mid 2000's); the Archangels and Seraphims Church and Angeles Workshop School. We have deep roots in our community actively working with the Palms Neighborhood Council, the IMAN Cultural Center, L.A; the Culver City Interfaith Alliance; our local Food Bank, the St. Augustine Volunteer Emergency Services (SAVES) and the Palms Emergency Preparedness Coalition as well as local law enforcement and wellness-oriented communities.
Region: West Los Angeles, Los Angeles, CA, USA

Name: The Partners Program
Description: The Partners Program offers tutoring and academic enrichment services to underserved public middle school students in Oakland.

Name: The Peggy Albrecht Friendly House
Description: The Peggy Albrecht Friendly House helps women seeking recovery from alcohol and other substance use disorders.

Name: The Peninsula College Fund
Description: The Peninsula College Fund supports college-bound high school students academically and financially.

Name: The People Concern
Description: The People Concern (formerly OPCC) provides services and shelter for individuals who are homeless and victims of domestic violence.

Name: The Perry Initiative
Description: The Perry Initiative is a grassroots non-profit organization founded in 2009 by Dr. Jenni Buckley (a mechanical engineer) and Dr. Lisa Lattanza (an orthopedic surgeon) with the eventual goal of increasing the number of practicing women orthopedic surgeons and engineers.

Name: The Phillips Academy
Description: The Phillips Academy is a special education school with students from grades 6-12.

Name: The Phoenix Scholars
Description: The Phoenix Scholars provides support services to high school seniors with the college application process.

Name: The Political Asylum/Immigration Representation (PAIR) Project
Description: PAIR provides free immigration services to indigent asylum seekers and detained immigrants.

Name: The Pollock-Krasner Foundation
Description: The Pollock-Krasner Foundation provides financial assistance to individual visual artists of established ability.

Name: The Pride Centre of Edmonton
Description: The Pride Centre of Edmonton is a non-profit, registered charity whose mission is to provide social support services to members of the LGBTQ2S+ population, their families and their communities. They do this through direct support, outreach, and education, and creating safe spaces.

Name: The Pride Community Services Organization (PCSO)
Description: The PCSO operates the only community-based Pride Center in Kentucky, which is often utilized as a free meeting space for LGBTQ+ organizations in the community.

Name: The Primary School
Description: The Primary School is an integrated health and education model serving children, and their families, from birth through the transition to high school.

Name: The Primary School - Hayward
Description: We integrate education, health care, &  family support services & build family well-being throughout a child’s development.  Kaiser Permanente staff at Sleepy Hollow Medical Offices in Hayward will support the design of our school’s health care program.

Name: The Princess Project
Description: The Princess Project - San Diego provides free prom dresses and accessories to high school girls who cannot otherwise afford them.

Name: The Q Foundation
Description: The Q Foundation helps members of the LGBTQ or HIV+ communities find housing and employment.

Name: The Rainbow Community Center of Contra Costa County
Description: The Rainbow Community Center works to build community and promote well being among Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender and Questioning individuals and their allies.

Name: The Ranch
Description: The Ranch formerly known as the Belvedere-Tiburon Joint Recreation Committee is an organization providing recreation programs for adults and children in Tiburon, Belvedere and Angel Island.

Name: The REACH Program at Mount Sinai
Description: The REACH Program provides primary care and medication-assisted therapy for persons who use alcohol and other drugs, as well as hepatitis C care and treatment.

Name: The Reentry Network
Description: The Reentry Network is a Contra Costa County program that helps coordinate reentry services for formerly incarcerated individuals.

Name: The Refugee and Asylum Seeker Health Initiative at UCSF
Description: The Refugee and Asylum Seeker Health Initiative at UCSF provides HIV/AIDS testing and treatment for refugees and asylum seekers. The organization also provides recovery support groups and interpretation services for communicating with doctors and physicians.

Name: The Relational Center
Description: Non-profit organization in Los Angeles, California that offers support groups and other services.

Name: The Respite Inn
Description: The Respite Inn provides out-of-home care to adults with developmental disabilities.

Name: The Richard M. Cohen Residence
Description: The Richard M. Cohen Residence is a residential care facility for homeless men and women living with disabling HIV or AIDS.

Name: The Richmond Neighborhood Center
Description: The Richmond Neighborhood Center offers various youth, adult, and family programs within San Francisco's Richmond District.

Name: The RightWay Foundation
Description: The RightWay Foundation helps current and former foster youth find a job and keep it through services including workshops, case management, housing, financial literacy, and education/career planning.

Name: The Ronald McDonald House at Stanford
Description: Ronald McDonald House at Stanford creates a home-away-from-home and supportive community for families of children with life-threatening illnesses receiving specialized treatment at local hospitals.

Name: The Salvadoran Association of Los Angeles (Sociation de Salvadorans en Los Angeles)
Description: The Salvadoran Association of Los Angeles (ASOSAL) improves the quality of life of Salvadorans, Central American and Latino communities by assisting immigrants to obtain Legal Permanent Residence.

Name: The Salvation Army - Antelope Valley Corps
Description: The Salvation Army Antelope Valley Corp offers services to the community including a 24 hour shelter, food, clothing, homeless support and more.

Name: The Salvation Army - Gainesville
Description: The Salvation Army Gainesville offers services including food, clothing, furniture, and more to the community.

Name: The Salvation Army - Golden State Division
Description: The Salvation Army - Golden State Division provides social services including senior housing, rehabilitation programs, and after school programs in San Francisco, the Central Coast, and the Central Valley area.

Name: The Salvation Army - Stillman Sawyer Service Center
Description: Provides assistance to families in Harbor City, Torrance, Lomita, Carson and Wilmington.

Name: The Salvation Army Long Beach
Description: The Salvation Army in Long Beach serves the community of Long Beach, Signal Hill, Lakewood and Hawaiian Gardens.

Name: The Salvation Army of Northern California
Description: The Salvation Army of Northern California provides services to those in need throughout Northern California and Northern Nevada. They provide services to families, the homeless, seniors, youth, and disaster victims.

Name: The Salvation Army of San Francisco
Description: The Salvation Army offers services to children, individuals, ​and families in the United States.

Name: The Salvation Army of Silicon Valley
Description: The Salvation Army of Silicon Valley is a faith-based organization that offers services to the community including clothing, groceries, transitional housing and more.

Name: The Salvation Army of Southern California
Description: The Salvation Army of Southern California provides services to those in need from San Luis Obispo to Orange County at 40 separate sites. Its services include: drug and alcohol rehabilitation, disaster services, health services, homelessness support services, senior services, veteran services, and youth services.

Name: The Salvation Army Redwood City
Description: The Salvation Army Redwood City provides homeless support services, financial assistance, food programs, home, and school supplies, and counseling for individuals and families in need.

Name: The Salvation Army Santa Cruz Corps Community Center
Description: The Salvation Army provides food, shelter, and emergency services for all in need.

Name: The Salvation Army: Bayview Impact Center
Description: The Salvation Army: Bayview Impact Center offers assistance with email accounts; identification - CA ID vouchers, CA DL suspensions and reissues, birth certificates (must demonstrate need); reports & discovery - 3 credit reports, California DMV online services, 10 year driving record, R.A.P. Sheets, California county court searches, probation searches, Chex System Report, Dept. of Child Support Services; financial counseling - income statement/balance sheet (budgeting exercise), credit repair, back taxes, liens and judgments, ID theft, child support (COAP), civil & criminal court, banking and financial products and services (with Wells Fargo Bank).

Name: The Sam Simon Foundation Feeding Families
Description: Distribute nutritious vegan groceries, at no cost, to individuals and families.

Name: The San Diego LGBT Community Center
Description: The San Diego LGBT Community Center provides health and well-being services for the lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender and HIV communities.

Name: The San Francisco-Osaka Sister City Association
Description: The San Francisco-Osaka City Association offers programs supporting individual and civic exchanges that foster better understanding and appreciation between citizens on both sides of the Pacific Ocean.

Name: The San Gabriel Valley Foundation For Dental Health
Description: The San Gabriel Valley Foundation For Dental Health provides dental services and education for under-insured children, ages 2 through 19, in the San Gabriel Valley.

Name: The San Mateo Small Business Development Center (SBDC)
Description: SBDC provides expert no-cost advising, low cost workshops and small business trainings to guide small businesses to success and accomplishment.

Name: The Santa Anita Church
Description: The Santa Anita Church seeks to provide religious services and fellowship.

Name: The Santa Clarita Valley Food Pantry
Description: The Santa Clarita Valley Food Pantry distributes food to individuals and families in need throughout the Santa Clarita Valley.

Name: The Santa Clarita Valley Scholarship Foundation
Description: SCV Scholarship Foundation administers scholarships donated by local businesses and community organizations, as well as memorial scholarships established for individuals, educators or alumni.

Name: The Shanti Project
Description: The Shanti Project offers support for people living with a chronic or life-threatening illnesses.

Name: The Social Engineering Project, Inc.
Description: The Social Engineering Project, Inc. (TSEP) provides STEM programs that lead to technical careers for underrepresented students of color, including summer camps, camping conferences, and family science nights.

Name: The Society of St. Vincent de Paul of Contra Costa County
Description: St. Vincent de Paul of Contra Costa County provides support services including food, clothing, shelter, rental assistance, medical services, employment, and workforce development for residents of Contra Costa County.

Name: The Source Program
Description: The Source Program provides survivors of domestic, dating and sexual violence with legal representation, mental health counseling and case management. It is offered as part of the Intimate Partner Violence Assistance Clinic (IPVAC) at the Levin College of Law.

Name: The Soze Agency
Description: The Soze Agency creates campaigns about compassion, authenticity and equity. This worker-owned cooperative is made up of entrepreneurs, activists, storytellers, artists and strategists.

Name: The Spahr Center
Description: The Spahr Center is an organization that works to serve, support and empower the LGBTQ population of Marin County. Services include LGBTQ social and support programs; HIV/AIDS support, prevention, and testing; and HIV and LGBTQ information and referrals.

Name: The SPARK (Stable Pathways to Achievement, Resilience, and Knowledge) Initiative
Description: The SPARK Initiative connects homeless and at risk youth ages 14-24 with housing, employment, education, legal, and wellness services.

Name: The Stegner Registry
Description: The Stegner Registry has compiled in-depth information regarding residential care facilities for the elderly, assisted living facilities, senior residential hotels, retirement communities, and continuing care communities.

Name: The Stride Center
Description: The Stride Center provides a comprehensive career development program that includes job skills training, credentials, career coaching, work experience, and job placement assistance.

Name: The Sylvia Rivera Law Project (SRLP) - Immigrant Justice Project
Description: The Immigrant Justice Project at SRLP works with low-income people and people of color who are transgender, gender nonconforming, and/or intersex (TGNCI) and either seeking legally recognized immigration status or are adjusting to a different immigration status. Services include: Representation of TGNCI immigrants in applications for immigration status; Adjustment of immigration status; Assistance with obtaining gender-affirming immigration documents; Holistic support of TGNCI immigrants in public benefits, healthcare, Social Security, and Screening; and Assistance with Asylum and DACA. *Note: SRLP is only able to provide legal services to people living in the five boroughs of New York City and people incarcerated by New York State.

Name: The Table
Description: The Table offers a hot meal to anyone in Napa County, five days per week.

Name: The Town Kitchen
Description: The Town Kitchen provides Culinary & Food Entrepreneurship Training. The training is a 60-hr course that is accredited though San Francisco State University and teaches culinary skills, entrepreneurship, & technology. After completing the training you are placed in the Oakland food businesses.

Name: The Transgender Clinic of Tom Waddell Health Center
Description: The Transgender Clinic of the Tom Waddell Health Center is committed to providing quality, integrated health care in an atmosphere of trust and respect. Anyone who identifies as transgender can be seen in their clinic: male-to-female, female-to-male, intersex, and those in-between. All are welcome. They are a multidisciplinary primary care clinic, which means they treat all of your medical issues (not just issues related to gender), they have mental health and social services, and they work closely with community organizations.

Name: The Transgender Resource Center of New Mexico
Description: The Transgender Resource Center of New Mexico provides support, community, and connection to transgender, gender nonconforming, nonbinary, and gender variant people and their families through advocacy, education, and direct services. The Center offers a drop-in center which includes a computer lab, a lending library, support groups, free confidential HIV testing, syringe exchange, an open donation closet (clothes, binders, and other items), informal case management, medical care, information and referrals on name change, and more.

Name: The Trevor Project
Description: The Trevor Project offers a 24 hour, national, free and confidential crisis and suicide prevention hotline for LGBTQ youth. They also offer educational programs and services to LGBTQ youth and aim to create safe, accepting and inclusive environments for all.

Name: The Unity Council
Description: The Unity Council is a non-profit community development corporation serving families primarily in the Fruitvale District of Oakland. The mission is to promote social equity and improve quality of life by building vibrant communities where everyone can work, learn, and thrive.

Name: The University of California 4-H Youth Development Program (San Mateo and San Francisco Counties)
Description: The 4-H program offers leadership development, life skills training, and supplemental learning opportunities for youth in grades 5 and up. The 4-H Youth Development Programs focus on educating youth in arts and sciences and encouraging community service.

Name: The University of Michigan Asylum Collaborative (UMAC)
Description: The University of Michigan Asylum Collaborative (UMAC) provides physical and psychological evaluations as medical testimony, documenting and validating for asylum, human trafficking, and other legal cases. UMAC requires a referral, a PHR-completed intake form, and a client personal statement/declaration before taking on any case. They also require that all case-related communication take place through the representing attorney (they do not email clients directly).

Name: The Vacaville Storehouse
Description: The Vacaville Storehouse is a distribution center for food to families in need in Vacaville, CA. Food is given free of charge to those who are in need and any homeless persons in the area.

Name: The Veterans Resource Program
Description: The Veterans Resource Program provides veterans who are in need of assistance with transitional and permanent housing, legal services, help with applying for benefits, and opportunities for higher education.

Name: The Village Family Services (TVFS)
Description: The Village Family Services (TVFS) is a social care and behavioral health agency that helps underserved, abused, and neglected children, youth, and families.

Name: The Village Health Foundation
Description: The Village Health Foundation provides natural health services including acupuncture.

Name: The Village Method
Description: The Village Method (TVM) provides comprehensive support and programming to young people to help them succeed in school and college. They provide an after school program, work closely with families and partner with other community organizations.

Name: The Village Project
Description: The Village Project is a non-profit, community based organization providing a safe haven for academic, cultural and enrichment activities for youth, 6 to 17 and their families.

Name: The Viola Blythe Community Service Center of Newark
Description: The Viola Blythe Community Service Center of Newark provides supportive services to those in immediate need, via emergency food and clothing distribution, referrals to other agencies, holiday programs at Thanksgiving and Christmas, and more.

Name: The Vision Academy
Description: The Vision Academy is a student-centered and collaborative learning community that focuses on the needs of young learners.

Name: The Volunteer League of the San Fernando Valley
Description: The Volunteer League of the San Fernando Valley provides community services such as free clothing for children and a choral music group that performs at nursing facilities.

Name: The Wall-Las Memorias
Description: The Wall-Las Memorias is a community health and wellness organization dedicated to serving Latino, LGBT, and other underserved populations in LA. They provide substance abuse prevention, HIV/AIDS education, and other health related support services.

Name: The Wanda Alston Foundation
Description: The Wanda Alston House is the first and only housing program in Washington, D.C. that is solely dedicated to offering pre-independent living services to homeless LGBTQ youth ages 16-24. Their services include: long-term transitional living (up to 18 months), case management, educational guidance and support, job training and guidance, and support service referrals. Wanda Alston House residents have their own rooms and live with an advocate with extensive experience with housing and LGBTQ issues.In addition, Wanda Alston House offers each youth a life skills counselor who works with the individual daily on issues relating to education/vocational training, housing, and other matters as necessary.

Name: The Well
Description: The Well focuses on providing space for public engagement, public discourse, and the creation of intentional community.  They provide residential and nonresidential communities to become involved with to grow your connections with others in the Seattle area.  The Well also offers workshops on racial and social equity, such as "Talking to Your Kids About Race." The organization will also begin provide low cost and donation based breathe and gentle movement classes in the Fall of 2017.

Name: The Wellness Center

Most services are free, there are no membership fees and the Center is open to all residents of L.A. County. Services include counseling for stress, anxiety, grief or depression, physical fitness activities, diabetes prevention and control, stroke prevention, arthritis support, multiple sclerosis support services, parent/child health support, meditation activities, legal services, medical insurance enrollment assistance, health career activities, and youth activities.

Name: The West Island LGBTQ2+ Centre

Name: The Whole Child

The Wright Institute Assessment Services offers low-fee psychological and neuropsychological testing for children (age 6 and above), adolescents, and adults. The Recovery Clinic focuses individuals challenged by drug addiction and trauma.

Name: Young Community Developers, Inc
Description: The Young Community Developers (YCD) provides training and support opportunities for residents of the Bayview Hunters Point neighborhood of San Francisco. Services include job placement, youth employment programs, summer work experience, community participation, career certification, and a GED/high school diploma class.

Name: Young Horizons Child Development Centers
Description: Young Horizons is a nonprofit organization serving children of low-income families since 1969. All teachers are certified and meet the requirements to teach young children of the comission on Teacher Credentialing. They are required to continue their education to maintain their teaching permit and background checks are required for ALL staff.   Our goal is to create an enviorment in which children are cared for, loved, and an enviorment in which they can learn. Our center has three purposes: Provide for the care and education of young children, provide parents with the resources they need tp help them in their role as parents, and provide quality, certified caregivers who are well-trained, warm and caring.

Name: Young Hwa United Methodist Church
Description: Operates a Food Oasis food pantry the 2nd and 4th Saturdays every month 3:00 pm - 3:45 pm.

Name: Young Women's Freedom Center (formerly The Center For Young Women's Development)
Description: Young Women's Freedom Center (formerly The Center For Young Women's Development) works with young women experiencing incarceration or life on the streets to create positive personal and social change. They offer a Sister's Internship Program, participate in research, advocate and organize, and create community leaders.

Name: Youth ALIVE!
Description: Youth ALIVE! works to educate and train young leaders to create a more peaceful community, interrupt the cycle of violence on the streets, convince angry victims and their loved ones not to retaliate, provide ongoing support to help the wounded and grieving get needed services and heal from their trauma. We primarily serve Oakland, but also work internationally.

Name: Youth Alliance
Description: Youth Alliance is a nonprofit that offers after-school programs and school-based counseling in South Santa Clara and San Benito counties. These programs include after-school, summer, and late night prevention programs, early intervention bilingual counseling and case management, and intervention programs that serve at-promise youth in the juvenile justice system, teen parents, and more.

Name: Youth Art Exchange
Description: Youth Art Exchange offers citywide arts, education programming, field trips and events.

Name: Youth Community Service
Description: Youth Community Service offers meaningful public service learning experiences that encourage youth to make purposeful school and life choices.

Name: Youth Emerging Stronger (YES)
Description: Youth Emerging Stronger (YES) provides services and support to youth who have ran away or who are experiencing homelessness. YES provides food, clothing, hygiene services, emergency shelter, a transitional living program plus educational and career development programs.

Name: Youth Employment Partnership (YEP)
Description: Youth Employment Partnership (YEP) provides career exploration, workforce training, supplemental education, and supportive services.

Name: Youth Engagement Advocacy Housing (YEAH!)
Description: YEAH! is an emergency shelter program for young adults age 18-25 years in Berkeley who are currently homeless. Services include nightly shelter, basic necessities, case management, counseling and more.

Name: Youth Funding Youth Ideas
Description: CHALK provides a variety of youth empowerment services including employment services, youth funded business ventures, service opportunities, television broadcast opportunities, and telephone hotline services.

Name: Youth Homes Inc.
Description: Youth Homes Inc. serves the needs of abused and neglected children and adolescents in California's San Francisco Bay Area. They provide intensive residential treatment programs and community-based counseling services that promote the healing process for emotionally abused and traumatized children and adolescents.

Name: Youth Mentoring
Description: Youth Mentoring matches at-risk youth to adult mentors in a structured group dynamic. Programs include worksite mentoring, community mentoring, support groups, employment skills, film academy, surf club, and college application support.

Name: Youth Moving On (YMO)
Description: Youth Moving On (YMO) provides transitional-age youth support services in areas of health and wellness, workforce development, life skills and financial literacy to help them find independence and personal fulfillment.

Name: Youth Pride Inc. (YPI)
Description: Youth Pride, Inc. is the only 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization in Rhode Island that provides support, education, and advocacy for LGBTQQ youth. Youth Pride, Inc. is dedicated to meeting the unique needs of youth and young adults impacted by sexual orientation and gender identity/expression while working to end the homophobic and transphobic environments in which they live, work and play. The Center seeks to address the needs of youth in schools or in out of home care.

Name: Youth SEED
Description: Youth SEED supports the development of community-led social enterprises by providing training, resources and investment to young innovators who traditionally face barriers to economic opportunities.

Name: Youth Seen
Description: Youth Seen provides assistance to LGBTQ+ youth in Colorado through case management, counselling, and support groups.

Name: Youth Service Bureaus of YMCA San Francisco
Description: The Youth Service Bureau provides counseling, crisis intervention, mentoring, and guidance for youth and their families in San Francisco and San Mateo counties.

Name: Youth Speak Collective
Description: Youth Speak Collective provides various youth programs including support to get into college, soccer program and arts programs.

Name: Youth Spirit Artworks
Description: Youth Spirit Artworks helps homeless and low-income young people with art jobs and job training.

Name: Youth United for Community Action
Description: Youth United for Community Action (YUCA) youth have taken on pressing community issues - whether it is environmental racism, tenant rights or juvenile justice.

Name: Youth UpRising
Description: Youth UpRising (YU) offers comprehensive, fully integrated health, wellness, educational, career, arts and cultural programming to Alameda County youth and young adults, ages 13-24.

Name: Youth With A Mission
Description: Youth With a Mission San Francisco is a faith-based non-profit organization that offers services to San Francisco's Tenderloin district.

Name: Youth@Work
Description: Youth@Work is a program sponsored by the NOVA Workforce Board. It serves as an online employment database and resource operated by the NOVA Youth Employment Program.

Name: Youthful Hearts
Description: Youthful Hearts is a fitness program hosted by two senior centers in Marin.

Name: YR Media (formerly Youth Radio)
Description: YR Media (formerly Youth Radio) offers digital media and technology education to youth.

Name: Yu Ai Kai
Description: Yu-Ai Kai promotes healthy aging and successful independent living for all seniors while embracing Japanese-American tradition.

Name: YWCA - Seattle
Description: The YWCA offers programs regarding health and safety and economic advancement to immigrants and refugees.

Name: YWCA Berkeley/Oakland
Description: YWCA Berkeley/Oakland provides programs, classes, and resources for the Berkeley and Oakland communities.

Name: YWCA Glendale
Description: YWCA Glendale provides domestic violence shelter and services in Glendale.

Name: YWCA Greater Los Angeles
Description: YWCA Greater Los Angeles (GLA) offers child development services, sexual assault crisis services, and senior engagement for people living in the Greater Los Angeles area. It administers the Los Angeles Job Corps Program, a residential and educational training program for homeless, emancipated, and at-risk youth ages 16 to 24.

Name: YWCA Of San Francisco And Marin
Description: YWCA Of San Francisco And Marin provides advocacy, housing, employment, and other community programs and services for women, girls, and families.

Name: YWCA of Sonoma County
Description: YWCA of Sonoma County provides direct services and advocacy for survivors of domestic violence.

Name: YWCA of the Harbor Area and South Bay
Description: YWCA of the Harbor Area and South Bay is dedicated to eliminating racism, empowering women, and promoting peace, justice, freedom, and dignity for all.

Name: YWCA San Gabriel Valley
Description: YWCA San Gabriel Valley provides women, girls, seniors and their families in the San Gabriel and Pomona Valleys with community education, residential, and service programs.

Name: YWCA Silicon Valley
Description: YWCA Silicon Valley provides therapy, victim support, childcare, and educational services for women.

Name: Zaccho Dance Theatre
Description: Zaccho Dance Theatre is a performance art and dance company located in the Bayview District of San Francisco.

Name: Zen Hospice Project
Description: Zen Hospice Project provides training and education for care givers and family members of individuals receiving end of life or hospice care.

Name: Zion Hill Baptist Church
Description: Zion Hill Baptist Church is a faith based organization that offers services to the Los Angeles community.

Name: Zoe Christian Fellowship
Description: Zoe Christian Fellowship offers free food and other services for those in need.

Name: Zohar Dance Company
Description: Zohar Dance Company offers dance classes for children and adults.

Name: Zoomers to Boomers
Description: Zoomers to Boomers offers easy, fast, and safe grocery delivery for the elderly and immunocompromised.

Name: Zuckerberg San Francisco General Hospital
Description: Zuckerberg San Francisco General Hospital and Trauma Center provides inpatient, outpatient, emergency, diagnostic, and psychiatric services for adults and children.
